<HEAD>Norway Coalition Agrees To Topple Labor Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three opposition parties agreed on a basic platform for a new non-socialist coalition and stand ready to topple the minority government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Gro </PERSON> <PERSON> Harlem </PERSON> <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON>, an opposition leader said Monday. The emerging coalition was expected to submit a no-confidence motion in Parliament this month if Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> refuses to resign, the national news agency <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Syse </PERSON>, who probably would become prime minister under the new coalition's plan, declined to reveal details of its platform until the three parliamentary groups review and approve the recommended policies. `` Lots of work remains to be done, including distribution of ministerial posts,'' <PERSON> Syse </PERSON> said on national <ORGANIZATION> NRK </ORGANIZATION> radio. The alliance of Conservative, <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> and Center parties won a total of 62 seats in the 165-seat parliament in Sept. 11 elections. Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON>'s Labor party won 63 seats, and the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, allied with <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, won 17. There was one independent. The right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION>, with 22 seats, held the balance of power. Its chairman, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagen </PERSON>, says he would support a no-confidence vote against Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON>, but would not pledge future loyalty to the new coalition unless his party became a full partner. `` We are ready to present such a no-confidence motion, if necessary,'' <PERSON> Syse </PERSON> said in a radio interview. Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s central board on Sunday she will decide the future of her government only after seeing the opposition's platform. The three non-socialist leaders demanded she resign as early as possible `` in order not to delay the coalition's and the Parliament's work,'' <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` She can chose to step down after Labor has presented its 1990 state budget proposal to the parliament on Oct. 12, or she risks being toppled by a general no-confidence vote on Oct. 24,'' the agency said.
