<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Mystery Train,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elvis Presley Haunts Jim Jarmusch's New Movie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON>'s involvement in the plot of <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarmusch </PERSON>'s new movie, `` Mystery Train,'' was a mystery to the filmmaker. The writer-director of `` Stranger Than Paradise'' and `` Down by Law'' says he started with a few characters, like he always does, and came up with the idea for shooting the movie in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, home of Presley's Graceland mansion and <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>, where `` The King'' first recorded. `` He snuck in there; you got to watch out for him,'' said the director at a recent press conference after the film's preview at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Film Festival. `` When I first came to Memphis I went to Graceland immediately. By the time I left <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, I was so sick of Elvis I never wanted to hear about him again.'' But for now, questions about <PERSON> Jarmusch </PERSON> and Presley are unavoidable. <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> is everywhere in `` Mystery Train,'' named after an old blues song that Presley recorded at Sun. His music is on the soundtrack, his pictures hang in hotel rooms, characters see his ghost and <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON>, a working-class Englishman played by rock' n' roller <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Strummer </PERSON>, is even nicknamed `` Elvis. `` Mystery Train'' is broken into three segments, which take place in the same time frame: A young Japanese couple visit <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> to see Graceland and Sun; a young Italian woman, recently widowed, and a talkative stranger share a hotel room for one night; and three buddies are forced to leave town when <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> kills a liquor store clerk. `` The Japanese couple are fans, they're kind of an audience,'' <PERSON> Jarmusch </PERSON> says. `` As the story progesses, the way <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> is treated changes somwewhat. By the third story, <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON>'s saying, ` That guy is everywhere.''' Fans of <PERSON> Jarmusch </PERSON>'s earlier films will quickly recognize the director's dark humor and fondness for characters usually found only in barrooms and poolhalls. `` Mystery Train'' is, however, <PERSON> Jarmusch </PERSON>'s first movie shot in color. `` I have to write very visually,'' he said. `` When I start to visualize the film, I make an intuitive decision and I stick to that. I ca n't say why. If you ask someone whether they dream in black and white or color, they ca n't say why. `` I have future projects and I already know that some are color and some are black and white.'' <PERSON> Jarmusch </PERSON> did say he will continue to make low-budget films outside the Hollywood studio system. He recalled a conversation with producer <PERSON> Dino </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLaurentiis </PERSON>. `` He asked me, ` Why do you make amateur films instead of professional ones?' I asked what made a film amateur or professional. He said any film that costs more than $ 5 million is professional. `` I guess I'm still making amateur films.'' The cast includes <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Bracco </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Aviles </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nicolette </PERSON> <PERSON> Braschi </PERSON> and rhythm' n' blues stars Screamin' <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rufus </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. `` Mystery Train'' is scheduled for a mid-November release by Orion Classics.
</TEXT>
