<HEAD>In the Tabloid TV Battle, `Current Affair' and `Hard Copy' Fight
for No. 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first reports from the new tabloid television wars are in, and `` A Current Affair'' and `` Hard Copy'' both have opened strongly while `` Inside Edition'' and `` USA Today on TV'' appear doomed. In this fall's jammed field of reality-based shows, other early casualties look to be `` Crimewatch Tonight,'' `` Trial by Jury'' and `` USA Today Weekend.'' According to the initial <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Syndication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> ratings, <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>'s nightly `` A Current Affair'' was the seventh most popular syndicated show at the start of the new television season. Finishing ahead of `` Entertainment Tonight'' and `` Donahue'' in the ratings, `` A Current Affair'' was seen in more than 6.9 million homes, the survey said. `` Every time a new show starts like ` Hard Copy,' ` Inside Edition' or ` Crimewatch Tonight' it becomes more competitive,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, co-executive producer of `` A Current Affair.'' `` But the strange thing ... is that when ` Inside Edition' started we never had better numbers. So far, in the first week against ` Hard Copy,' we've done the highest numbers we've ever done.'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said `` A Current Affair'' has attempted to fight off its challengers by trying to `` give more serious thought to the stories we do. You try to avoid doing the celebrity rip-offs and the easy <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; A shock-value stories.'' He said critics who blast `` A Current Affair's'' coverage of news and personalities as tawdry are n't fair to the show's intent. `` The worst kind of criticism that's written says that shows like ` A Current Affair' seek to horrify, shock and offend,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said. `` Because if somebody shocks and horrifies and offends me on a regular basis, I'm going to turn off. And I wo n't let my kids to watch it, either. Because it debuted Sept. 18, `` Hard Copy'' was not included in the first Nielsen syndication report. But the news-oriented program, once entitled `` Tabloid,'' has performed strongly in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, according to its producers. Furthermore, `` Hard Copy'' consistently has boosted some stations' ratings from four months ago, the show's representatives say. In <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, for example, `` Hard Copy'' is delivering to WVIT an audience 60 percent larger than `` Win, Lose or Draw'' did in May. `` For a new show, we got off to a pretty solid start,'' says <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Monsky </PERSON>, executive producer of `` Hard Copy.'' `` We came off the blocks very quickly. Right now we have to prove to the people who did tune us in that what they got was just a little bit of what they could get.'' In its first few weeks on the air, `` Hard Copy'' has reported exclusives on <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and the death of her husband and the bombing of the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> airliner over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. `` I think our intention is very clear. At the top of the show, we want to be very close to what's going on,'' <PERSON> Monsky </PERSON> said. `` And then we want to go deeper and deeper in trying to explore the widest possible range of the people involved.'' The top five shows in the syndicated market for the week ending Sept. 17 are, in order, `` Wheel of Fortune,'' `` Jeopardy,'' `` The <PERSON> Oprah </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfrey </PERSON> Show,'' `` The Cosby Show'' and the weekend version of `` Wheel of Fortune.'' `` Inside Edition'' finished at No. 22, `` USA Today'' landed at No. 32 and `` Crimewatch Tonight'' was No. 46. `` Trial by Jury'' was No. 62 and the weekend version of `` USA Today'' was No. 77. In one strange twist, the makers of `` Inside Edition'' have discussed the possibility of inviting celebrities on the show to rebut any distortions written about them in the supermarket tabloids. However `` Inside Edition'' is revamped, though, it seems likely it will be replaced by `` 30 Minutes.'' Producer <PERSON> Av </PERSON> <PERSON> Westin </PERSON>, a veteran of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, has joined `` Inside Edition'' maker King World Productions to create the new syndicated news magazine. New reality shows added to network schedules all have debuted poorly. Of the 81 shows covered in last week's regular Nielsen survey, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Primetime Live,'' hosted by <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, finished 49th. CBS' `` Rescue 911,'' with <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatner </PERSON>, landed in 55th. And CBS' `` Saturday Night With Connie Chung'' came in 71st.
</TEXT>
