<HEAD>Reports of Rape, Beatings by Police Endanger Peace Process</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ILOPANGO, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It had been almost a week, and 21-year-old <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendoza </PERSON>'s crying was done. But her mother, <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>, who had listened stoically to her daughter's account of rape by a policeman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, could contain herself no more. She sobbed when <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> described the soft-voiced rapist zipping up his pants and saying, `` Maybe that will make you want to collaborate.'' Allegations of mistreatment of prisoners have abounded since the rightist government of <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> took office June 1 and began to move against what they called `` guerrilla fronts'' _ public organizations that sympathize with or support guerrilla positions on some or many issues. The rebels, over the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>'s clandestine radio, called the police `` animals'' for the alleged rapes `` This is too much to stand for,'' they said. The insurgents warned that continued repression and rights abuse will endanger a preliminary peace process begun last month in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> with talks between government and guerrilla representatives. `` Just as we have been flexible and broadminded in order to negotiate, we are likewise completely disposed to, and capable of accompanying the struggle of the entire people, and to take hold of the flagpole of democracy and peace and carry it forward to drive it into the heart of those who only want war,'' said the rebel high command. Asked about the accusations, Maj. <PERSON> Mauricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Caceres </PERSON>, head of the armed forces press committee, said: `` All commanders take pains to ensure that a prisoner's human rights are respected, because they know these people will come out of the police stations alleging this and that kind of abuse in order to make us look bad.'' In what they called a response to escalated repression, the guerrillas last week launched their first nationwide offensive since May. Seventy-eight people were killed or wounded in the combat, adding to the toll of a 10-year-old civil war that has taken 70,000 lives. It was visiting day at the women's prison six miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> sat outside next to <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> behind a backboard on the cement basketball court as she told her story. <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendoza </PERSON> is one of three women at <LOCATION> Ilopango </LOCATION> jail who say they were raped at <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> headquarters after their arrest the night of Sept. 18 following a demonstration that turned violent. The National Federation of Salvadoran Workers sponsored the march, during which police were taunted by masked demonstrators wielding iron bars and two city buses were set afire. Authorities released 25 of 64 arrested demonstrators, but seven women and 32 men were held. Dr. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Maldonado </PERSON>, a forensic specialist who examined 37 of the 39, found corroboration of the rape allegation only in Miss <PERSON> Mendoza </PERSON>'s case. The government and armed forces say prisoners like <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendoza </PERSON> are leftist guerrilla operatives masquerading as labor activists and that they invent accusations of torture and abuse to slander authorities. The workers federation, known as FENESTRAS by its Spanish initials, in fact espouses a political agenda identical to that of rebels who have waged war against a succession of U.S.-backed governments. But union and peasant organizations, as well as local and international rights groups, say the fact that an individual might support guerrilla positions does not strip him of the right not to be tortured, raped or summarily executed. <PERSON> Maldonado </PERSON> found bruises, cuts and scrapes on 20 of those arrested after the Sept. 18 march. All said they were beaten during interrogation. All said their interrogators belabored them about alleged membership in guerrilla units and insisted they provide names of cohorts. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON>, in charge of the unionists' cases, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that many of the injuries could have been inflicted with billy clubs during the suspects' The New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, after a four-month study of justice in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, said in a report this year, `` We have identified a pattern of psychological as well as physical abuse of detainees.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in its 1989 human rights report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>: `` Reports of abuse by arresting forces continue .... Instances of severe beatings, rape, choking, injection with drugs and electric shock were reported.'' The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the allegations `` are extremely difficult to prove or disprove.'' <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> said that's because the judiciary depends entirely on the police forces for investigations. `` We receive many allegations of rape, but they never get anywhere,'' he said. `` In Miss <PERSON> Mendoza </PERSON>'s case, practically speaking, resolution would be impossible. She was blindfolded and can not identify the man. And the same National Police that are accused of committing the crime would be in charge of investigating it.'' He suggested creation of a police force responsible solely to the judiciary to avoid such conflicts of interest. `` Just having an investigative arm separate from the executive branch would be great progress,'' he said. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> were accused of raping and beating detainees after the April arrests of dozens of members of refugees organizations considered guerrilla fronts by authorities. Col. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Emilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON>, chief of the joint chiefs of staff, promised an investigation. After repeated requests by the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Caceres </PERSON> reported that the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> had investigated itself and found no wrongdoing.
