<FIRST>r w PM-GIBill     10-02 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GI Bill,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>GI Bill Running out for Vietnam-era Veterans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> era veterans who want to take advantage of the GI <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> to further their educations will soon run out of luck. The GI bill program that covers people who served during <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> ends Dec. 31. A new GI bill has taken its place, but only the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans who remained on active duty from June 1985 through June 1988 may benefit. According to Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ariz </LOCATION>., 250,000 veterans are affected Many are GIs who stayed in the military but left before the end of June 1988. Although legislative efforts have been made to extend the benefits, neither veterans' committee in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is taking up the measures. `` It's a damn shame this is going to come to an end and is going to hurt so many <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans who have made the military a career,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> of the 35,000-member <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> Veterans of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> VVA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Egan </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of the Non-Commissioned Officers' Association, argue that the veterans being squeezed out of the programs are the ones who `` carried'' the military during the 1970s, when it was plagued by low enlistment and low morale. The 153,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, representing career enlisted personnel in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, has urged an extension of benefits. Neither of the two major veterans' groups, the American Legion or the Veterans of Foreign Wars, spoke out on the issue in a recent <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee hearing on the GI bill. Rep. G.V. `` Sonny'' <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, opposes extending benefits under the so-called `` Cold War'' GI bill. The <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Democrat says the bill is too costly, unnecessary to help veterans readjust 14 years after the war, and unneeded for a group of people who had already made a career choice _ for the military. `` It's time to move on to a new bill designed to recruit and retrain rather than just reintegrate,'' said committee spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Holley </PERSON>. The GI bill that expires Dec. 31 followed the Korean War GI bill and the pioneering World War II GI bill. There was also a Veterans' Educational Assistance Program for people who enlisted from 1977 to 1985. The program offered a maximum benefit of $ 225 monthly and was based entirely on the enlistees' contributions. The <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> era bill is the most used, having served 8.1 million veterans, compared with 7.8 million for the World War II program. The <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> bill, with no contributions, pays a maximum $ 376 million monthly benefit to full-time students with no dependents. The maximum eligibility is 45 months. The Veterans' Affairs Department said in February that 750,000 people were eligible for benefits under the Vietnam-era bill and 60,000 were currently enrolled. The new program relies partly on pay deductions from recruits. It pays $ 250 to $ 300 a month for up to three years, reflecting the three years of active duty required for eligibility. A person is eligible for up to 10 years after discharge. Those who entered the service during <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> could take advantage of the new program if they served three years of active duty starting June 30, 1985, when the bill took effect. The <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> vets were not required to make further contributions. But <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of the 160,000-member <ORGANIZATION> NCO </ORGANIZATION> group said the service regulations force many career non-commissioned officers to retire, and many lost eligibility because they had to quit before the end of June 1988.
