<HEAD>House Members Doubt Senate Rationale on Star Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters of Star Wars believe the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> strengthened its hand in negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by restoring funds for the missile shield, but <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members are casting doubt on that rationale. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> slashed $ 900 million from President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s fiscal 1990 request of $ 4.9 billion for <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> last Tuesday, then came back two days later and restored two-thirds of the money. What transpired in 48 hours were proclamations that the initial vote signaled the demise of the program, formally known as the Strategic Defense Initiative, introduced six years ago by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as a nuclear-age antidote to a strike against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. There also was a negotiating session between <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> conferees thrashing out the defense authorization bill in which confident <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members argued that the true <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Star Wars number was the $ 3.7 billion adopted Tuesday in the appropriations bill, not the $ 4.5 billion the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved last month in authorization legislation. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which had agreed to $ 3.1 billion for the program, wanted a final figure closer to their total. Faced with that argument, Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, took his case to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for a stronger negotiating position He succeeded by a narrow margin, 53-47. Despite the win, lawmakers stressed that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> would