 Samuelson </PERSON>'s tax adviser, who has discussed the error with <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> officials. The San Francisco-based bank, with 640 branches throughout the state, hires about 2 million people each year on a contract basis, said spokesman <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellog </PERSON>. The inflated income reports have been tentatively traced to one of <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION>'s many computers that handle <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> Form 1099, which is submitted for all non-employees who perform more than $ 600 worth of work for the company. The cause of the malfunction remains unknown. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said taxpayers called to account for non-existent income should be able to prove the bank's figures were inaccurate but could face a large amount of paperwork. But <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said that any problems in setting the record straight should be minimal. `` It's just a couple of additional zeroes,'' he said. `` It's not a problem for the taxpayer. We send out hundreds of thousands of letters like those, and it's not unusual to have some problems.''
