<SECOND>PM-Children and Families,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Children Locked in Poverty, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Millions of children, particularly blacks and <PERSON> Hispanics </PERSON>, are being launched on `` courses of failure'' because they live in poverty, says a congressional report that warns there appears little prospect for improvement. Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., said the report released Sunday paints a `` disturbing'' portrait of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> children, many of whom never benefited from the economic expansion of the 1980s under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration `` We're launching millions of children on courses of failure,'' said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who heads a committee on families. Most disturbing, he said, is that `` I really see very little that holds out the prospect that this will change. ... The prospect is that those incomes are going to stagnate.'' Neither the White House nor <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been willing to put enough resources into social programs to give families the support they need so children can grow up well-fed, healthy and educated enough to participate in the economy, he said. However, Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., ranking Republican on the panel, took issue with the chairman's conclusion that the federal government, under a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> president, has ignored the problem <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON> said the net that is keeping so many children in poverty was not cast by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> but is the result of social forces that are breaking up families and sexual behaviors that are leading more girls to become teenage mothers. `` We have known for two decades that single parenthood is a prescription for poverty, regardless of race,'' <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON> said. `` How you solve these problems I really do n't know.'' <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON> agreed with <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was not likely to vote more money for social programs overall. `` You can always use more money, but I do n't see it there with the budget crunch we're in,'' he said. The 300-page report by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> and Families compiles statistics from a variety of sources. The figures show that children are the poorest segment of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population. In 1987, nearly 21 percent of children under age 18 and more than 22 percent of children under age 6 lived in families with incomes below the poverty line, compared with 12 percent of the elderly and 14 percent of people of all ages. The childhood poverty rate rose from 15 percent in 1970 to more than 18 percent in 1980 and more than 22 percent in 1983 before dropping to 20.5 percent in 1986. Poverty has been more persistent for black and Hispanic children, for whom the rates have risen since 1970. In 1987, more than 48 percent of black children and nearly 42 percent of Hispanic children lived in poverty. In 1988, 71 percent of children were living with two parents, while about 24 percent were living with only their mother or father. In 1981, about 74 percent were living with both parents and about 20 percent were living with a single parent. About 42 percent of children in 1986 were living with two working parents, while 29 percent were in two-parent families where only the father worked. About 15 percent lived with one parent who was in the labor force and about 8 percent were in single-parent homes where the parent was unemployed.
