ed himself to truck farming and politics. He managed to unify his fractious party into a political force and rally <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s splintered conservatives. He ran for <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION> governor in 1986 but lost to the governing party candidate in balloting also allegedly marred by fraud. <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON>, whose family has lived in <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION> for more than a century, was born in <LOCATION> Culiacan </LOCATION> on June 13, 1934. An agricultural engineer by profession, he headed leading business organizations for more than two decades. <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> studied at the <ORGANIZATION> Technological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>, graduating with a degree in agronomy and botany. He taught biology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinaloa </ORGANIZATION>. He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Leticia </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrillo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON>, and their 10 children.
