<HEAD>Bomb Heavily Damages Town Center, Slightly Injures Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb exploded outside the police station of a small town 20 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, heavily damaging the town center and slightly injuring three people, police said. No group immediately claimed responsibility for the blast late Sunday in <LOCATION> Randalstown </LOCATION>, but suspicion inevitably fell on the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, which is fighting British rule in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> police headquarters said in a statement that the injured were two civilians and a police officer. Police said the bomb exploded as police officers were evacuating scores of families from their homes in the area following a telephoned warning by an anonymous caller. They said the attackers put the 500-pound bomb in a hijacked van, then left the vehicle outside the police station, which like many police stations in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> is fortified against bomb attacks and manned only part-time. The building, unoccupied at the time, was extensively damaged while dozens of nearby homes, shops and offices were wrecked, police said. They said only the prompt action of the security forces in evacuating homes had prevented a major disaster. The mainly Roman Catholic <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> wants to unite the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> province with the mainly <LOCATION> Catholic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> under socialist rule.
