<HEAD>Tired Refugees Weep With Joy On Arrival In West Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Refugees, Bjt ^By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A young East German woman screamed, `` We made it, we made it,'' as she sobbed with happiness, squeezed into a throng of hundreds of other refugees arriving in this northern Bavarian city. The refugees, many with small children in tow, looked tired but still showed nearly unbounded joy as crowds of West Germans welcomed them after their overnight journey to the West. <PERSON> Elke </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebecke </PERSON>, her 12-year-old son <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> and 3-year-old daughter <PERSON> Christine </PERSON>, tried to push through the refugees and well-wishers on the train platform. `` My husband managed to make it across through <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> three weeks ago, but we did n't go,'' the 32-year-old woman said, her eyes wet with tears. Mrs. <PERSON> Ebecke </PERSON>, from the <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION> area, was on the second train packed with East German refugees that arrived from <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. `` My husband does n't even know we're here yet,'' she said. <PERSON> Annamarie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenz </PERSON>, 52, told of how Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> announced late Saturday to refugees at <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>'s embassy in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> that they would be permitted to go West. `` I was just walking by in the embassy garden when he said it. Such a cheer went up from all the people. It was unbelievable,'' she said. `` I had applied three times in two years to leave for the West, but they turned me down each time. I went to <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, because I thought this was my only chance.'' The refugees formed long lines at public telephones in the train station to call families in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> or relatives in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. Outside the station, many refugees picked out donated clothing stacked high on yellow railway carts. Most had arrived with just one or two canvas bags packed with their belongings. <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, police and railway workers mingled with the crowd, many smiling and chatting. Some handed out hot drinks, bananas and bowls of soup to the refugees. At a table in the train station snack bar sat 21-year-old <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Monique </PERSON>, 19. <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, a cook, and his wife, a waitress, said they were fed up with harsh political conditions at home. `` They -LRB- Communist authorities -RRB- control everything you do,'' <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> said. `` We applied to go to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> on vacation, but they turned us down. We did n't need permission to go to <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, so we went to the embassy and joined the others, hoping to get out.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> said, `` You ca n't get ahead over there -LRB- in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> -RRB-. You always have the feeling you are being watched. You are afraid to discuss anything with your friends.'' She said the East German news media `` lie and try to tell us the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> just wants to make slaves of us. They really think we're so stupid we do n't know better.'' East German news media have claimed that <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is luring East Germans as a source of cheap labor. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Shutz </PERSON>, an auto mechanic, said East German authorities `` try to control everything we do. The young are tired of putting up with that. It's a dictatorship. All I can say is I'm happy to be here ... If I work hard over here I know I can get ahead.'' <PERSON> Shutz </PERSON> was asked why he and other refugees turned down an earlier East German offer of travel to the West within six months on condition they first leave the embassy in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and return home. `` There are n't many people who would fall for something like that,'' he said. <PERSON> Uwe </PERSON> <PERSON> Thuemmel </PERSON>, a 30-year-old East German truck driver, said he had planned to take advantage of that offer and had traveled to <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Plauen </LOCATION>, near the Czechoslovak border. `` I left my wife and family at home, thinking I would be back in three days. But then <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>'s announcement came, so I decided to leave without my family,'' he said. `` I hope they'll be able to follow me.''
