<HEAD>Composer, Critic Virgil Thomson Dead at 92</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Virgil </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON>, the Pulitzer Prize-winning composer and music critic whose career spanned more than half a century, has died at age 92. <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON>, who had been in failing health for a long time, died in his sleep early Saturday in his room at <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Chelsea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> where he had lived almost 50 years, said his secretary, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> won the Pulitzer Prize for music for his score to the documentary film `` <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Story </LOCATION>,'' in 1949 _ the only time the Pulitzer has been awarded for a movie score. `` The death of <PERSON> Virgil </PERSON> <PERSON> T </PERSON> is like the death of an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> city: it is intolerable,'' said composer-conductor <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Virgil </PERSON> was loving and harsh, generous and mordant, simple but cynical, son of the hymnal yet highly sophisticated. ... `` But he will always remain brightly alive in the history of music, if only for the extraordinary influence his witty and simplistic music had on his colleagues.'' <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON>'s long career included orchestral and choral works as well as incidental music for plays by authors from Shakespeare to <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> <PERSON> Capote </PERSON>. In 1988, <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> was one of 12 recipients of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, an award created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> four years earlier at the suggestion of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Born in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> began to play piano at age 5 and, as a teen-ager, worked as a church organist. In 1922, he graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and moved to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, where he was among a group of young American musicians such as <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Copland </PERSON> to study with <PERSON> Nadia </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulanger </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, he also met the iconoclastic composer <PERSON> Erik </PERSON> <PERSON> Satie </PERSON>, who was a great influence on him. While in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, he met <PERSON> Gertrude </PERSON> <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> and wrote one of his most famous works, the opera `` Four Saints in Three Acts,'' with her as librettist in 1928. It premiered in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, in 1934 and had a short but successful run on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. He settled in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1940 and joined the staff of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, where he was music critic until 1954. In 1982, he won a National Book Critics Circle Award for `` A Virgil Thomson Reader.'' <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON>'s latest book, `` Music with Words,'' is to be released officially Oct. 18 by <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> described it as a `` how-to book for composers, people who are interested in setting words to music or music to words.'' In an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> before his 90th birthday, the cherubic, white-haired <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said, `` I've got nothing wrong with me except I'm deaf and overweight. You do n't die from those.'' <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said the hearing problem kept him from enjoying musical performances more than 10 years ago, but he continued to compose and kept busy on the lecture circuit. He recalled that his first Tribune music review said violinist <PERSON> Jascha </PERSON> <PERSON> Heifetz </PERSON> played `` silk underwear music,'' but joked that when some other critic is unkind about his own music, `` I'm convinced the writer is an ignorant pipsqueak and probably in the pay of my enemies.'' <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON>, who never married, is survived by a niece, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Stouffer </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Longwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. He will be buried in a family plot in <LOCATION> Slater </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. A memorial service is planned at the Cathedral of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> the Divine in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Nov. 25 _ what would have been <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON>'s 93rd birthday.
