<HEAD>Stocks Fall, Dollar Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s key index fell back from its record high morning close today, and the dollar declined against the Japanese yen for the sixth consecutive trading day. The dollar closed at 139.30 yen, down 0.05 yen from last Friday's 139.35-yen finish. It opened at 138.77 yen and moved between 138.65 yen and 139.48 yen. The dollar now has fallen 5.70 yen in six days. Market players, reassured by the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s parliamentary by-election victory on Sunday, tended to buy the yen in early trading, said <PERSON> Minori </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeuchi </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` But the dollar rose afterward in mixed trading, mainly for technical position adjustments,'' she said. She added that market players were reluctant to buy the dollar at the 139.50-yen level for fear of <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> intervention. The central bank has been selling dollars over the last week to check the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's recent rise. The amount of selling was unknown, and the bank does not comment on its exchange market activities. On the stock exchange, the 225-issue <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> lost 13.79 points, or 0.04 percent, ending at 35,622.97. In early trading, it had climbed to 35,701.33, its highest ever morning closing. The index had shed 53.22 points on Friday. The Liberal Democrats' by-election victory also prompted the index's early gain, said <PERSON> Masahiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Umemori </PERSON>, a stock analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` But the index started falling later mainly because participants became afraid of recent rapid rises in share prices,'' he said, noting the index's 500-point gain last week. `` Afternoon trading was directionless, too,'' he said. A rumor that <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> might raise its interest rates soon also discouraged investors, <PERSON> Umemori </PERSON> said. `` The rumor even said there might be a coordinated interest rate hike in a few countries,'' he added, without elaboration. Trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated at 750 million shares, down from 900 million last Friday. Electrical issues such as <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> and Pioneer and steel issues were losers.
