<SECOND>PM-Driving Dropouts,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Becomes Fifth State to Ban Dropouts From Driving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> has joined the growing list of states that withhold driver's licenses from high-school dropouts, but teachers are n't sure the change will improve education or just keep bad students in school. The law, which took effect Sunday, drew praise from some educators as an attention-grabbing way to cut the dropout rate. `` I believe this is an excellent tool for parents to use to encourage their students to remain in school,'' said <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Castor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> commissioner of education. But others say the law could create a bureaucratic nightmare and just might cause discipline problems by keeping reluctant students in the classroom. `` There may be more children who will be in school. But they do n't want to be in there and they may become problems in the classroom,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Cariseo </PERSON> of the state <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION>. `` Sometimes these children just do n't care.'' <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> broke ground last year with a law requiring teen-agers to stay in school to keep their driving privileges. <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> followed suit, and dozens of similar bills are pending in legislatures around the country. Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sangmeister </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., has introduced legislation to make such a ban nationwide The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law says students must stay in school or an eligible program _ such as a course for a high school equivalency test or a training program _ or the license will be suspended until age 18. The state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> estimates 9,200 students will decide to stay in school in order to keep driving. Because the law also limits unexcused absences _ 11 in a row or 20 for the year _ supporters of the law say attendance might improve for perhaps 62,000 students. Nearly 30,000 drop out every year in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. The report card on similar laws in other states is mixed. `` It's so new that I do n't think anybody really knows all the effects,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Secondary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Principals </ORGANIZATION>. `` A lot of people simply think it's too broad. Through February, 1,809 dropouts returned to school in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, but 48 percent of them then left school a second time, said <PERSON> Therese </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, acting director of state educational support services. More than 780 teen-agers' licenses have been revoked under the law, she said. In <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, schools across the state must certify in writing that each student meets the attendance rules when they apply for driver's licenses. Teen-agers become eligible to drive at age 16. Many <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> school administrators anticipate the law will bring a deluge of paperwork that could clog up the system, Ms. <PERSON> Cariseo </PERSON> said. `` Every child has got to get these forms,'' Ms. <PERSON> Cariseo </PERSON> said. `` I think the main problem is going to be keeping up with that and notifying the <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> once they drop out.'' Castor, the education commissioner, plans to ask the Legislature for $ 5.8 million to cover administrative costs, with the funds to come from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s lottery. Backers say the law will back up parents' warnings about the danger of dropping out. `` It's hard to tell a student he'll have a lower-paying job when he's 30 and have him listen,'' said education department spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Voss </PERSON>. `` When a parent says ` You ca n't drive any more,' it's immediate.
