 Tropical Storm <PERSON> Colleen </PERSON> moved toward this <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory and the Commonwealth of the <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mariana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> packing winds up to 45 mph. <PERSON> Colleen </PERSON> was expected to intensify to typhoon status, with 75 mph winds, when it sweeps within 70 miles south of <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> on Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Typhoon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> said. At 1 p.m. today -LRB- 10 p.m. Sunday EDT -RRB-, <PERSON> Colleen </PERSON> was at 11.5 degrees latitude and 148.6 degrees longitude, or 247 miles east-southeast of <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION>, the center said. As of 3 p.m., maximum winds were 40 to 45 mph and the storm was moving to the west-northwest at 12 to 14 mph. <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> issued a tropical-storm alert and said <PERSON> Colleen </PERSON> could hit the island within 72 hours. Military officials were meeting to determine when airplanes and ships should be moved for protection. The storm formed Sunday 500 miles east of Guam. The term `` typhoon'' is used for hurricanes west of the international date line.
