<HEAD>Three Chinese Pro-Democracy Members Lead Washington March</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, adds 3 grafs at end to include Canadian protests.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former members of the Tiananmen Square democracy movement are urging Americans and `` peace-loving people all over the world'' to continue pressing for freedom in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Three former members of the pro-democracy movement led about 3,500 demonstrators Sunday to protest the 40th anniversary of communist rule in their homeland. The marchers walked in a downpour from the Lincoln Memorial to the Chinese Embassy here to protest the violent crackdown on the student democracy movement in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square. Nearly 2,000 other marchers demonstrated in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, and hundreds marched in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. `` The Chinese government must stop killing,'' said <PERSON> Shen </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON>, one of the three pro-democracy leaders, who fled <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> after the crackdown last summer. `` We appeal to peace-loving people all over the world to stand together with us and fight for a <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in which basic freedoms are guaranteed.'' Another of the three emigres, Wu'er Kaxi, told a small news conference outside the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> that `` the attitude of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people as well as that of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been clear since the events'' of the crackdown. Asked whether he had any specific criticisms or demands of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, he replied, `` No comment.'' Shen, Wu'er and the third leader, LiuYan, were in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for a fast and protest. Police estimated the crowd of marchers at 3,500. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, 1,200 people shouted and waved signs outside the Chinese consulate in a noisy but peaceful protest against National Day, the celebration of the 40th anniversary of the People's Republic of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Protesters during the three-hour demonstration said four decades of communism had been a failure for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and blasted the Chinese government's repression of the pro-democracy movement. Many of the signs pledged to remember the `` martyrs'' of democracy, hundreds of students who were killed when troops fired on <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square last June. Police reported no arrests or problems because of the protests. In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, some 700 people gathered peacefully outside the Chinese consulate downtown waving human rights signs, singing peace songs and cheering speeches by university students, <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> clergyman and community leaders. The crowd, mainly Chinese natives, formed a semicircle on the street in front of a military tank, two tents, a 5-foot Goddess of Liberty statue and a gray coffin, on which dozens of spectators placed white flowers. The <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> and Scholars sponsored the two-hour protest which included a re-enactment of the student massacre and a mock trial. <PERSON> Ting </PERSON> <PERSON> Huang </PERSON>, a computer engineer and native Chinese, donned a T-shirt with a picture of <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, the 85-year-old senior leader in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The words above the photo stated `` Wanted for Murder.'' `` I'm here to protest continuing human rights violations in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, secret arrests and imprisonment,'' <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> said. On Oct. 1, 1949, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Zedong </PERSON> declared the founding of the People's Republic of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. About 500 people demonstrated in front of the Chinese embassy in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>, while 300 rallied in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. `` We are going to use every occasion to help people remember June 4 and tell the world we will never forget, nor will we stop fighting for democracy,'' said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Lu </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> and Scholars in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. Several protesters wore brown paper bags on their heads, fearing for the safety of relatives still in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
