<HEAD>500 Arrested in Five-Day Protest at U.S. Military Facility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NURRUNGAR, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-nuclear protesters have ended a five-day protest at a U.S.-Australian military intelligence base after 500 demonstrators were arrested, some after breaking into the base. About 50 soldiers were called in to reinforce base security forces and police at the base in southern <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. In the action that ended Sunday, protesters broke into the facility several times, police said. Today, Defense Minister <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Beazley </PERSON> ordered an investigation into security measures at the base. Demonstrators picked the intelligence-gathering base 360 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Adelaide </LOCATION> as a protest site because they consider it a likely target in the event of a superpower nuclear confrontation. Police said 217 of the 500 protesters were arrested inside the <LOCATION> Nurrungar </LOCATION> base's security zone. The media were prohibited from covering a march from the security gate to the main complex by protesters who broke into the grounds. Six journalists were arrested during protests on Saturday. A <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> newspaper said the protest was `` an embarrassment for <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s defense forces and must give American military authorities cause for concern.'' `` If we are to have <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases and equipment here we should be able to protect them,'' said today's editorial in The Sydney Daily Telegraph.
