 A black student praised the congregation of an all-white church that allowed him to attend worship services after turning him away the week before. `` They are good people,'' the Rev. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> said after attending services Sunday at <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. `` The church needs to be commended.'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, a 24-year-old divinity student at <ORGANIZATION> Selma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, was joined by three other black men who walked into the sanctuary before the start of services at the 1,300-member church. `` The church has allowed Christ to prevail and the gates of hell to be defeated,'' he said. There were no incidents and the men were greeted warmly on the front steps as they prepared to leave. `` This is a wonderful, great day,'' said the church's pastor, the Rev. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. He said the 18-member board of deacons met Friday night and `` made the decision to seat anyone who comes to worship.'' The full congregation will vote Oct. 11 on whether to back the deacons, he said. The formal policy of not admitting blacks dates from the days of civil rights demonstrations in the 1960s. `` I can not speak for the congregation, -LRB- but -RRB- I think if it's ever rescinded, now is the time it would be,'' the pastor said On Sept. 24, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and two women students at the predominately black Christian college arrived at the church planning to attend the service, but a deacon told them the church had a policy excluding them from worshiping there. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said he was `` shocked and encouraged'' Saturday when a telephone call to <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> revealed a change in the policy. After the service, he called <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> `` a great preacher.'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said much of the controversy over his bid to attend services at Central Baptist had been blown out of proportion. He also denied ever saying that a $ 50 bet with one of his professors prompted him to seek entry.
