<BYLINE>Supreme Court Refuses to Revive Maryland Suit About Foster Home
^By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to revive an allegedly abused foster child's federal lawsuit against the social workers and government agency that placed him in his foster home. The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling in a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> case that no such right to sue exists. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Milburn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, now 20, was not quite 2 years old when in 1971 the <ORGANIZATION> Anne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arundel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> placed him with foster parents <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> of <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnie </PERSON>. His parents voluntarily had placed him in the custody of the social services agency. <PERSON> Milburn </PERSON>'s federal lawsuit against the <ORGANIZATION> Tuckers </ORGANIZATION>, individual social workers and the county agency said he was subjected to physical abuse for nearly two years before being removed from the <ORGANIZATION> Tuckers </ORGANIZATION>' home The suit, which sought $ 66 million in damages, said his injuries included two leg fractures, a facial laceration and severe burns that left his hands permanently scarred and disabled. The suit alleged that Mrs. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, with her husband's knowledge, inflicted all the injuries _ including her immersing the youngster's hands in boiling water. <PERSON> Milburn </PERSON>'s suit, based on alleged violations of his constitutional due-process rights, was thrown out by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, and the 4th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the dismissal last March 31. Such lawsuits must establish that the alleged harm was caused by the government or some government agent. The 4th Circuit ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> Tuckers </ORGANIZATION> did not fit the definition of government agents. `` The state of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> was not responsible for ... the -LRB- alleged -RRB- physical child abuse itself,'' the appeals court said. `` It exercised no coercive power over the <ORGANIZATION> Tuckers </ORGANIZATION>; neither did it encourage them.'' The appeals court noted that a parallel lawsuit filed in state court, alleging <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> tort law violations, is awaiting action. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last February ruled that public officials may not be sued in federal court when their alleged gross negligence permits a child to be abused by a parent. That decision in a <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> case said a state does not have a constitutional duty to protect people, including abused children, who are not in the state's custody. Writing for the court then, Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> said, `` As a general matter, we conclude that a state's failure to protect an individual against private violence simply does not constitute a violation of the -LRB- Constitution's -RRB- due process clause.'' That constitutional provision bars deprivation of life, liberty and property without due process of law. A footnote in the February decision, however, said the justices were leaving undecided whether due-process considerations would arise in the case of children abused by foster parents. The case is <PERSON> Milburn </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Anne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arundel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, 89-96.
