<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A golf club that has counted presidents and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> among its members failed today in a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> bid to regain a tax break revoked because of the club's refusal to admit women as members The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> officials did not violate the rights of <ORGANIZATION> Burning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> members by scraping a tax break worth more than $ 300,000 a year. Burning Tree has 440 members and is located just outside the nation's capital in the affluent suburb of <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, The club had a long-term agreement with the state to preserve its open spaces in return for favorable property-tax treatment. But in 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> canceled the agreement. The club, an all-male bastion since its founding in 1922, was told it must either admit women or have its land taxed at full value. <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> officials also said the club's refusal to admit women violated the state's <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amendment </ORGANIZATION> enacted in 1972. The <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in March that a law forcing the club to choose between admitting women or losing its tax break did not violate the members' freedom-of-association rights. The law `` does not even prohibit Burning Tree from discriminating,'' the state's highest court said. `` It simply provides that if Burning Tree continues to discriminate, its property will be assessed in the same manner as the property of other taxpayers in the area.'' Burning Tree officials argued their club should be exempt from recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings empowering government officials to end sex discrimination at such large, national organizations as the <ORGANIZATION> Jaycees </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Rotary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clubs </ORGANIZATION>. Burning Tree's appeal said the club is a more intimate group and has a limited purpose: providing a `` congenial'' setting for men devoted to the game of golf. The <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> appeals court, however, ruled that the state is only withdrawing a benefit, not forcing the club to accept women. `` The state is simply declining to subsidize any organization that engages in discriminatory activities,'' the state court said. `` Just because Burning Tree's members may have associational rights does not oblige the state to subsidize the exercise of those rights.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling in 1988 gave states and local communities power to ban sex and race bias at private clubs smaller than the <ORGANIZATION> Jaycees </ORGANIZATION> and Rotary. The court upheld a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> law banning discrimination by private clubs with more than 400 members. Two justices who joined that unanimous opinion, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, once belonged to male-only clubs. The case is Burning Tree vs. <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, 88-1970.
