<HEAD>Court to Decide Postal Service Soliciting Issue in Maryland Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether the government may prohibit soliciting on all Postal Service property, including sidewalks adjacent to post office buildings. The justices said they will review a case from <LOCATION> Bowie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, in which a federal appeals court struck down the ban as unconstitutional. Other federal appeals courts have upheld the ban. <PERSON> Marsha </PERSON> <PERSON> Kokinda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearl </PERSON> were arrested outside the <PERSON> Bowie </PERSON> post office on Aug. 6, 1986, after they refused to stop soliciting contributions and distributing literature from a sidewalk table. The two are volunteers for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the political arm of an organization headed by political extremist <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>. They had set up the table on a sidewalk adjacent to the post office building. The post office in <LOCATION> Bowie </LOCATION>, like many in suburban and rural communities, is a freestanding building with its own sidewalk and parking lot. A municipal sidewalk runs in front of the post office property, separating the parking lot from the street. Ms. <PERSON> Kokinda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pearl </PERSON> were convicted in a trial before a federal magistrate of violating a regulation banning `` soliciting, electioneering, collecting debts, vending and advertising'' on <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> property. There was no evidence that the two had blocked or interfered with people entering and leaving the post office. But postal officials said they received more than 40 complaints from patrons during the several hours Ms. <PERSON> Kokinda </PERSON> and Pearl were there. Ms. <PERSON> Kokinda </PERSON> was fined $ 50 and sentenced to 10 days in jail. Pearl was fined $ 100 and given a suspended 30-day jail term. A federal judge upheld the convictions, but the 4th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> threw them out by a 2-1 vote last Jan. 31. The appeals court rejected the government's argument that there is a difference between city sidewalks and a sidewalk located entirely on <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> property. The appeals court called the activities by Ms. <PERSON> Kokinda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pearl </PERSON> `` classic political speech pursued peacefully in a place that traditionally has been held open to the public for expressive activities.'' Because the sidewalk outside the post office is a `` public forum,'' the appeals court said, soliciting and other forms of speech could not be banned `` except by content-neutral time, place and manner regulations that furthered a significant government interest.'' The 4th Circuit court's ruling set a binding legal precedent for <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. In the appeal acted on today, government lawyers noted that two other appeals courts have upheld the soliciting ban after ruling that a sidewalk like the one at issue in <LOCATION> Bowie </LOCATION> is not a public forum. `` The Postal Service will not be able to enforce a single nationwide standard to deal with the problem of solicitation and other forms of speech on the grounds of the 35,000 post office facilities around the country,'' the appeal said. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Kokinda </PERSON>, 88-2031.
