<HEAD>High Court Agrees to Hear Virginia Medicaid Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether hospitals and nursing care homes may sue in federal court to challenge how a state-run Medicaid program reimburses their costs. The court said it will review a ruling that would allow a hospital association to invoke a federal civil rights law in suing <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> over the state's Medicaid reimbursement rates. The attorneys general of 36 states told the court its ruling, expected sometime next year, will affect hundreds of millions of dollars in federal and state funding. The <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> sued the state in 1986, attacking the state's Medicaid reimbursement rates. The lawsuit alleges that the too-low rates violate the federal Medicaid Act and the due-process rights of participating hospitals. Medicaid is paid primarily by the federal government but individual state agencies administer the program aimed at providing health care to the poor. <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> officials sought to have the suit dismissed, contending that only health care recipients _ not individual or associated health care providers _ have the right to sue under the Medicaid Act. The 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> rejected that contention last Feb. 22 in a decision that set a binding legal precedent for <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. Acknowledging that the Medicaid Act does not expressly give hospitals and nursing care home the right to sue a state, the appeals court ruled that the right is implied. Such suits may be filed under a much-used, Reconstruction era civil rights law, the 4th Circuit court said. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> argued that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did not intend to enable hospitals and nursing care homes to sue over Medicaid rate disputes. They also contended that the state should be shielded from such suits by immunity granted under the Constitution's 11th Amendment. A `` friend-of-the-court'' brief written by the <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> attorney general's staff and submitted in behalf of 36 states urged the justices to reverse the 4th Circuit court's ruling. The ruling leaves Medicaid providers `` free to attack ... the reasonableness of each state's reimbursement rates,'' the states' brief said `` Every routine rate challenge may be made a federal case.'' The case is <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, 88-2043.
