<HEAD>Court to Decide Federal Union Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether federal agencies sometimes must negotiate with employee unions over what goods and services the government buys from private businesses. The justices said they will resolve conflicting court rulings in the `` contracting-out'' dispute. The appeal granted review today was filed by lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which contends that an agency's power to contract for the goods and services it needs from private industry is an exclusive management prerogative not subject to negotiation. But the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, which adjudicates collective bargaining disputes between federal agencies and their employees, ruled against the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>. The authority said grievance and arbitration provisions of the tax agency's labor contract with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> apply to disputed contracting-out cases. The authority ordered the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> to bargain with the <ORGANIZATION> NTEU </ORGANIZATION> over the union's proposals. A <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> panel here, by a 2-1 vote, upheld the <ORGANIZATION> FLRA </ORGANIZATION> ruling last Feb. 28. Other federal appeals courts, however, have ruled that federal agencies have no such obligation. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> argued that the FLRA ruling will harm government efficiency. `` Under the scenario contemplated by the <ORGANIZATION> FLRA </ORGANIZATION>, long after an agency has decided to contract work out and has accordingly entered into ... a contract with a private entity, the agency may be told by an arbitrator that the contracting-out decision must be reconsidered under the conditions that existed when it was made,'' the appeal said. `` That prospect is not conducive to efficient agency management,'' it added. <ORGANIZATION> FLRA </ORGANIZATION> lawyers told the justices that the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> case was decided correctly by the appeals court, but the authority did not oppose the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> appeal. The case is <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> vs. FLRA, 88-2123.
