<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to consider reinstating the murder conviction of a <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> man who says he was duped into driving the getaway car in a gas station holdup. The court said it will review a ruling that police violated the man's rights when they arrested him without a warrant at the house a where he was staying. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> was convicted of murder, armed robbery and assault in the July 18, 1987, holdup of a <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> gas station. The station's manager was shot to death. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> was sentenced to life in prison plus six years. The <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> overturned <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>'s conviction last February and granted him a new trial, ruling that he had been the victim of an unlawful arrest. Police, acting on an informant's tip, did not obtain a court warrant or permission to enter the house where <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> was staying before they went in and arrested him. The fact that <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> was a guest at the home did not deprive him of privacy rights, the state court said. Noting that police said they failed to get a warrant because it was a Sunday, the state court said that is `` surely a curious reason for not observing the constitutional safeguards of citizens.'' The state court also rejected arguments that police were faced with an emergency. Ordering a retrial, the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said prosecutors may not use a statement <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> made shortly after the arrest in which he admitted driving the getaway car. Prosecutors said discrepancies in the statement undermine <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>'s claim that he was an innocent dupe of the man who held up the gas station and shot the manager. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>'s appeal to the nation's highest court was supported by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attorneys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and officials from 10 states: <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>. The justices were urged to clarify whether house guests have the same right against unreasonable police searches and seizures as people in their own homes. The case is <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, 88-1916.
