<HEAD>Supreme Court Agrees to Hear Case from Illinois About Political Patronage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today set the stage for an important ruling on political patronage, agreeing to decide whether public employers may be forced to put aside partisanship when hiring, promoting and transferring workers. The court said it will hear an appeal by two men and a woman who said their job status suffered because they did n't support the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. The court also agreed to hear a related appeal by <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> officials seeking to preserve patronage powers in determining when government workers may be laid off and rehired. <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Rutan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> asked the court to reinstate their lawsuit against Illinois Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and state and local <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> officials. They said their rights of free speech and association, protected by the Constitution's First Amendment, were violated. Ms. <PERSON> Rutan </PERSON> said she repeatedly was denied promotions to supervisory positions in the state <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> because she did not support Republicans candidates. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, an equipment operator, allegedly was denied an <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> transfer to another county because party officials opposed it. And <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said the state <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has refused to hire him since 1978 because he could not get the backing of key Republican leaders. `` Those who are politically favored are promoted, transferred or hired,'' they said. `` Those who are not so favored are not promoted, transferred or hired.'' They sued for more than $ 1 billion in damages, and sought to have control of the state employment system shifted to a court-appointed federal receiver. A federal judge threw out their suit, and the 7th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, by a 7-2 vote in February, upheld the dismissal. The appeals court, relying on a series of <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions, said public employees enjoy broad First Amendment protection from being fired or threatened with firing. But the high court has not extended the same constitutional safeguards to hiring, promotion and transfer, the appeals court said. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a 1980 ruling that significantly weakened the patronage system, said government workers may not be fired solely because of their political affiliation unless that was an appropriate requirement for carrying out their jobs. The 7th Circuit court said, `` Employment decisions not involving dismissals ... are significantly less coercive and disruptive than discharges ... A person denied a promotion or transfer ... still retains his job and his ability to meet his financial obligations.'' The appeals court said a judge should be reluctant to intrude into the political process and become `` a platonic guardian over state employment systems.'' Changes in the patronage system are better left to legislatures, the appeals court added. But the appeals court ruled in favor of two workers laid off from state jobs, saying layoffs are similar in key respects to firings. It ordered additional hearings in those cases. The cases are <PERSON> Rutan </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1872, and <PERSON> Frech </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Rutan </PERSON>, 88-2074.
