<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Bail     10-02 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Bail,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Consider Bail Issue in New Mexico Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to consider increasing the federal government's power to keep some accused criminals behind bars while they await trial. The court said it will review a ruling in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> case that forces the government to free, on bail, some defendants deemed to be dangerous or a risk to flee before trial. A federal appeals court said pretrial release is required _ even for a defendant who otherwise could be held in custody _ if a pretrial detention hearing is not held the first time that person appears before a judge or magistrate. The justices in 1987 upheld a federal law allowing denial of bail before trial to people deemed dangerous to the community, even if accused of non-violent crimes. Before the 1984 law, called the Bail Reform Act, pretrial bail generally would be denied only if a judge determined the defendant was likely to flee. In practice, however, federal judges could get around the old law by setting very high bail, ostensibly aimed at guaranteeing the defendant's appearance in court but effectively keeping the accused in custody while awaiting trial. A provision in the 1984 law states that a hearing to determine whether pretrial detention is justified must be held `` immediately upon the person's first appearance before the judicial officer, unless that person or the attorney for the government seeks a continuance.'' A federal trial judge and the 10th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the `` first appearance'' provision of the law had been ignored in the case of <LOCATION> Guadalupe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Montalvo-Murillo </LOCATION>, charged with possessing nearly $ 1 million worth of cocaine. Montalvo-Murillo, a citizen of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> then legally living in this country, was stopped last February while driving a pickup truck near the Mexican border at <LOCATION> Orogrande </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> N.M. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents found 72 pounds of cocaine, with a wholesale value of almost $ 1 million, in the truck. At a Feb. 16 proceeding, a federal magistrate put off a detention hearing until Feb. 21. After that hearing, the magistrate decided to release Montalvo-Murillo on $ 50,000 bail and other conditions. Government prosecutors appealed to a federal judge, who ruled that <PERSON> Montalvo-Murillo </PERSON> posed both a danger to the community and a risk to flee. But the judge ruled that the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> magistrate, in postponing the detention hearing for five days, violated the federal bail law's `` first appearance'' rule. The judge said the only appropriate remedy was the defendant's release on bail. Montalvo-Murillo was freed on $ 88,500 bail, and has been a fugitive from justice ever since. He is believed to have fled to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The 10th Circuit court upheld the judge's ruling that the only remedy for denying a defendant a timely detention hearing is release on bail _ even if the result of the hearing would have been holding the defendant without bail. In the appeal acted on today, government lawyers argued that automatic release for such procedural infractions is not required by the 1984 law. `` The court of appeals erred in imposing a remedy so plainly at odds with the objectives of the Bail Reform Act,'' the appeal said. Lawyers for <PERSON> Montalvo-Murillo </PERSON> urged the court to reject the government's appeal, contending among other things that their client's status as a fugitive makes his case moot. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. Montalvo-Murillo, 89-163.
</TEXT>
