<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected an appeal by an anti-pornography activist who says sexually explicit photographs and caricatures in Hustler magazine libeled her and invaded her privacy. The court, without comment, refused to revive a $ 150 million lawsuit by feminist author <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON>. A federal judge threw out the suit, and the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the dimissal last January. The Hustler references to <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON> were opinion, not statements of fact, and therefore are protected by the free-speech guarantees in the Constitution's First Amendment, the appeals court said. `` <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON> errs by limiting opinion to high-minded discourse,'' the appeals court said. Shielding all opinion from lawsuits `` means that outrageous and outlandish statements are sometimes protected,'' the appeals court said. But it added, `` Ludicrous statements are much less insidious and debilitating than falsities that bear the ring of truth. We have little doubt that the outrageous and outlandish will be recognized for what they are.'' The appeals court also noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1988 threw out a $ 200,000 award against <ORGANIZATION> Hustler </ORGANIZATION> won by television evangelist <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON>, who accused the magazine of causing him emotional distress by publishing a pornographic parody. In that decision, the justices gave broad free-speech protection to parodies and satire. <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON> said she was viciously lampooned by Hustler and its publisher, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynt </PERSON>, because of her opposition to pornography. She is the author of an <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> ordinance, since declared unconstitutional, that defined pornography as a violation of women's civil rights and permitted lawsuits against pornographers. <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON> sued over features published in three 1984 issues of Hustler. One was a cartoon of two women engaged in lesbian sex in which one woman says to the other, `` You remind me so much of <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON>.'' A second feature included a series of photographs that referred to `` the <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON> fan club.'' A photograph in a third issue identified a woman engaged in sex as <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON>'s mother. <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON> sued in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> but the case was transferred to a federal court in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> at the request of Hustler. The case is <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON> vs. Hustler, 88-1900.
