<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Libel Award Against Rhode Island Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a $ 278,600 libel award against a <LOCATION> Pawtucket </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, newspaper. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that news stories may be libelous even if they contain no false statement. Today's action sets no national legal precedent, but instead leaves unresolved conflicting lower court rulings on the issue. The <ORGANIZATION> Pawtucket </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, published by a subsidiary of the <ORGANIZATION> Ingersoll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> group, was ordered to pay $ 28,600 in compensatory damages and $ 250,000 in punitive damages to Dr. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Healey </PERSON>, a prominent <LOCATION> Pawtucket </LOCATION> surgeon who chaired the local <ORGANIZATION> YMCA </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors The <ORGANIZATION> Rhode </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the jury award last March 3, ruling that an Evening Times article falsely implied that <PERSON> Healey </PERSON> was asked, and refused, to interrupt a <ORGANIZATION> YMCA </ORGANIZATION> board meeting to help a heart attack victim. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON> had gone to the board's June 23, 1980 meeting to criticize the firings of two <ORGANIZATION> YMCA </ORGANIZATION> staff members but was ordered by <PERSON> Healey </PERSON> to leave. <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON> then joined a group of protesters about 200 yards from the room where the board meeting was being held. He collapsed minutes later. <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON> was given first aid almost immediately, and an ambulance arrived within 10 minutes. The heart attack, however, was fatal. An Evening Times article two days later reported that <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON>'s sons were angry over the <ORGANIZATION> YMCA </ORGANIZATION> board's treatment of their father. The article said the family felt <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON> `` should have been given early attention by either a doctor or a paramedic at the board meeting.'' The next paragraph said, `` Dr. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Healey </PERSON> is Y president and was at the meeting when <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON> collapsed.'' The following paragraph noted that <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON> collapsed 200 yards from where the board was meeting, and the article went on to quote a <ORGANIZATION> YMCA </ORGANIZATION> official refuting any implication that <PERSON> Healey </PERSON> or any other board member was lax in responding to an emergency. The official was quoted as saying that board members, when told of <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON>'s collapse, also were told that `` the situation was well in hand and already being taken care of.'' In its ruling, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s highest court said the June 25 article that included the <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON> family criticism could have `` created the implication that -LRB- <PERSON> Healey </PERSON> -RRB- was asked and refused to help <PERSON> Lampinski </PERSON> and that there was enough time for -LRB- him -RRB- to render aid.'' The state court added: `` The evidence could support a finding that -LRB- the newspaper -RRB- knew these implications were false or that it acted in reckless disregard of whether these implications were true or false ... The defamation here really consists of what was left unprinted as well as what was actually printed.'' Using a legal definition employed by other state courts, the <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> court said publishing an opinion can be libelous `` if it implies the allegation of undisclosed defamatory facts as the basis for the opinion.'' In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> argued that the legal definition used by the state court violates free-speech rights. `` Only false statements of fact,'' and not the reporting of someone's stated opinion, can be libelous, they said. The newspaper's appeal was supported in a `` friend-of-the-court'' brief sumbitted by five news media organizations _ the <ORGANIZATION> Reporters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Newsletter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Radio-Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalists </ORGANIZATION>. They said the Evening Times had been punished `` for attempting to fairly and neutrally report both sides of a controversial local matter.'' The case is <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Healey </PERSON>, 88-1939.
