<HEAD>Texas Anti-Abortion Protesters Lose Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three people convicted of trespassing for handing out anti-abortion booklets to students outside a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> high school lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal today. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that distribution of the `` pro-life'' literature on school grounds was not protected by the Constitution's free-speech guarantees. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> were arrested outside <ORGANIZATION> Friendswood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> on Jan. 22, 1987, after refusing to leave. A state jury convicted them of criminal trespass, and a judge sentenced each to 90 days probation and 40 hours of community service. The high school, where more than 1,000 students attend classes, is fronted by a public road that has no adjacent sidewalk. There is no access to students from the roadside because most arrive by car or bus, and are dropped off on school grounds. In the appeal acted on today, the three convicted trespassers contended that their peaceful action before the start of classes should be constitutionally protected. `` The vehicle unloading area and adjacent grounds in front of the school ... should be considered a limited public forum'' where distribution of literature is allowed, the appeal argued. Under past free-speech rulings, a limited public forum is an area opened for use by certain speakers or on certain occasions. But a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> appeals court ruled that the Friendswood High grounds are not any kind of public forum, and the handing out of booklets there is not constitutionally protected. The appeals court upheld the convictions. `` The place is not an area which by tradition has been devoted to public assembly or debate by the general public ... there is no evidence that it had ever been opened by the school authorities as a place for public expressive activity,'' the state court said. It added: `` A limited public forum can not be created ... simply because members of the public are permitted to come and go at will.'' The case is <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, 88-2077.
