<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a ruling that allows states to file criminal charges against employers accused of neglecting the health and safety of workers. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling in an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case that federal workplace regulations do not bar such state prosecutions. Five officials of <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magnet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> are awaiting trial on charges they recklessly injured 42 workers by exposing them to toxic chemicals, extreme heat and other unsafe conditions at a wire-coating plant. Prosecutors said conditions at the plant were extremely hazardous, and accused the officials of callously disregarding worker safety. Prosecutors said air in the plant was filled with smoke and chemical fumes, temperatures reached 300 degrees on catwalks and employees were not allowed to wear masks. The state said workers often passed out from the heat and fumes, and on at least one occasion the plant manager laughed at an employee who suffered enamel burns. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Magnet Wire officials argued that the criminal charges should be thrown out because the federal government pre-empted state prosecutions when it enacted the Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970. The officials said permitting such prosecutions would allow `` wholly uninformed and, most likely, wholly unconcerned'' local prosecutors and juries to decide when a factory is unsafe. They said the job should be left to `` experienced and knowledgeable federal officials setting uniform national workplace safety standards.'' Their appeal was supported by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> and other business groups that said allowing criminal prosecutions will cause `` regulatory chaos.'' In refusing to squelch the prosecution, the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last February said, `` State criminal law can provide a valuable and forceful supplement to insure that workers are adequately protected and that particular egregious conduct receives appropriate punishment.'' The Chicago Magnet Wire officials indicted were <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, president; <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Keane </PERSON>, plant manager; <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Asta </PERSON>, maintenance foreman; <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, plant engineer; and <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Colby </PERSON>, an engineering and maintenance supervisor. If convicted, they face maximum sentences of 10 to 20 years in prison. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Asta </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1783.
