<HEAD>Court Says States May Require Auto Insurance Despite Religious Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let states require automobile insurance for motorists who say it violates their religious convictions. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> man who believes having insurance belittles a promise from God to provide in any situation. <PERSON> Lindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Reliance </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> S.D. </LOCATION>, was stopped by a state trooper in January 1988 while driving on a road closed because of a blizzard. When he did not produce proof he had car insurance, <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> was charged with violating a state law requiring motorists to `` maintain financial responsibility'' for motor vehicles. The law requires either liability insurance or the posting of a $ 75,000 bond or $ 50,000 certificate of deposit to protect others who might be injured by a motorist. <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> pleaded not guilty, saying that since 1972 he has refused, because of his religious beliefs, all forms of insurance. As evidence of his sincerity, <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> said he and his wife refused free insurance from their employers. <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> was fined $ 75, and his license could be revoked under the state law. The <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in May that while <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON>'s religious beliefs apparently are sincere, the state has a legitimate interest in requiring car insurance. The law `` is clearly designed to protect the public,'' the state court said. Without the law, damages caused by car accidents `` could be borne by the public at large rather than those who are responsible,'' the state court said. It added that the options of a bond or certificate of deposit permit <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> to maintain financial responsibility for his driving without purchasing insurance. But <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> said the bond or the certificate would be a tremendous economic burden for him. The alternatives `` place an unmistakable burden on <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON>'s free exercise of his religious beliefs,'' his lawyers said They also argued that the state's interest in requiring insurance is less than compelling because many motorists _ tourists from out of state, for example _ are permitted to drive without insurance. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1985, by a 4-4 vote, barred <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> officials from requiring a driver's license photograph for a woman who believes the Bible forbids such a `` graven image.'' But that tie vote, while upholding a lower court ruling in favor of the woman, established no national precedent. In other cases, the high court has ruled for individuals whose observance of the Sabbath conflicted with state authority. Last March, the justices unanimously barred states from denying unemployment benefits to people who refuse to work on their Sabbath even if the refusal is based on individual religious belief rather than a religious group's doctrine. The case acted on today is <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, 89-10.
