<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Michigan Lawyers' Fee Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a $ 1.2 million bonus in fees awarded to the lawyers for consumers who sued over allegedly defective transmissions in some <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> cars. The justices, without comment, turned away arguments that federal law does not allow such fee bonuses when lawyers win cases in which there was a substantial risk of non-payment because of a loss. Various lawsuits against <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, each alleging that less efficient engines and transmissions were substituted in certain lines of cars, were consolidated into one `` class action'' case in 1982. The case was settled in 1985 after <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> agreed to establish a $ 17 million fund to be shared by those who sued. A federal judge awarded the consumers' lawyers nearly $ 2 million in fees, to be paid out of the fund. The award was based on time expended and reasonable hourly rates. The judge refused to enhance the fee award as a bonus for taking a risky case on a contingency fee basis, ruling that the federal Magnuson-Moss Act bars any such `` risk multiplier'' of a lawyer's fees The 7th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> threw out the award ruling last year and ordered the judge to apply a risk multiplier in the GM case. The judge then awarded an additional $ 1.2 million in lawyer fees. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> argued that the appeals court ruling conflicts with language in the Magnuson-Moss Act and with a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision limiting lawyer-fee bonuses. The 7th Circuit court rejected a narrow reading of the federal law's language. The appeals court said the 1987 ruling did not apply to the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> case because a settlement had resulted in a common fund for payments to consumers and their lawyers. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> lawyers called the appeals court ruling a `` patent evasion'' of the 1987 high court ruling. They said the appeals court decision `` will increase the incentive for plaintiffs' attorneys to clog the courts with marginal lawsuits in the hope of recovering large multipliers, while spawning complex litigation over the collateral issue of attorneys' fees.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal was supported in a `` friend-of-the-court'' brief submitted by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Counties </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>. The brief noted that state and local governments `` are among the defendants most frequently sued under federal statutes providing for awards of attorney fees.'' The case is <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Skelton </PERSON>, 88-1848.
