<HEAD>High Court Lets Pennsylvania Require Judges to Retire at Age 70</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today allowed <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> to require its state judges to retire at age 70. The court, without comment, turned away arguments that such a mandatory retirement age for judges is unconstitutional. The controversy may have had special poignancy at the nation's highest court, where four of the nine justices are over 70 and a fifth will turn 70 next year Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> are over 80. Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> is 72, and Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> will turn 70 on April 20. Each has life tenure, as do all federal judges. Since 1968, the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Constitution has required all state judges _ who generally are elected to 10-year terms _ to step down at 70. Four judges challenged the state constitutional provision, saying it conflicts with the equal-protection and due-process guarantees offered in the federal Constitution. But the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last March 1 upheld the mandatory retirement scheme as a rational way to promote legitimate state purposes. The state court identified those purposes as: _ Continually bringing in younger judges while retaining part-time services of retired judges willing and able to help out _ Eliminating unpleasantness of removing aged and disabled judges on an individual selective basis _ Preventing harm caused by senile judges In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the four state judges attacked each stated purpose. `` Removing older judges to make room for younger ones is unfair, legally unsupportable and unwise,'' the appeal argued. `` The public interest is not served by forcing mature, experienced judges off the bench before their elected terms expire.'' It added that because chronological age `` bears no scientific relationship to mental competence,'' a blanket policy on retirement `` denies judges their rights to individualized determinations of their fitness for service.'' Removing the unpleasantness that may accompany such individual determinations `` has never been considered a legitimate excuse for rank discrimination,'' the appeal said. The mandatory retirement is not an effective way of protecting the public from senile judges, the appeal said, because mental incompetence may set in far earlier than someone's 70th birthday. The justices in 1976 upheld a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> law requiring mandatory retirement of state police officers at age 50, and in 1979 upheld a federal law requiring mandatory retirement of foreign service officers at age 60. The four state judges who appealed the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> mandatory retirement are <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rauhauser </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfadt </PERSON>. The case is <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, 89-80.
