<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Appeal by Older Postal Inspectors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected an appeal by older <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> inspectors who say they are being forced illegally to transfer to other cities. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the inspectors are not victims of illegal age discrimination. The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which employs more than 1,900 inspectors, has faced a problem of chronic staff shortages in 14 major metropolitan areas. The service in 1980 adopted what it calls its career path policy to ease the big-city shortages. Inspectors are urged to volunteer for work in the big cities. As an incentive, inspectors who have spent two years in one of the big cities are exempt from similar transfers later on when they reach senior-level status. Also, anyone who has served five years in one of the 14 metropolitan areas is eligible to be asked for reassignment. Another provision of the career path policy puts senior-level inspectors who have not worked in the big cities at the top of the list for involuntary transfers. It is that so-called senior-first rule that was challenged by the older inspectors. They said the policy disproportionately harms inspectors over age 40. A federal judge ruled that the provision violates the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act, which is aimed at protecting older workers against arbitrary bias. The judge's ruling was overturned in December 1988 by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here. The appeals court said the senior-first rule should not be examined in isolation. `` The senior-first rule was not a free-standing element of an employment program,'' the appeals court said. `` Under the career path policy, every -LRB- senior-level -RRB- employee was expected to spend five years in a major metropolitan area. Thus, each -LRB- senior-level -RRB- employee can fulfill this uniform service requirement through either an early voluntary, or a later involuntary, transfer.'' The appeals court said the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> properly refused to adopt an alternative system of random transfers because that would have reduced the incentive for voluntary moves to big cities. In the appeal acted on today, the senior inspectors said they have been hit with significant hardship by the transfer rule. After living for years in the same location, they said the system forced them to uproot their families and move to areas with a higher cost of living. Regardless of the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s motives, the senior inspectors said the senior-first rule is illegal because it has a disproportionate impact on older workers. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration lawyers urged the justices to reject the appeal, saying, the system `` ensures that the burdens of employment are distributed fairly while giving postal inspectors as much control as possible over their careers.'' The case is <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> vs. Postmaster General, 89-8.
