<HEAD>President of Nauru in South Pacific Loses Bid to Revive Libel Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president of the tiny <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> republic </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Nauru </LOCATION> today lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal aimed at reviving his libel lawsuit against a Guam newspaper. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that President <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> <PERSON> DeRoburt </PERSON> was not libeled by the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. The newspaper, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, reported in 1978 that DeRoburt secretly made an illegal $ 600,000 loan to a <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> political faction that favored separating the islands from <LOCATION> Micronesia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> DeRoburt </PERSON> said the article and a related one were false. He said the loan was legal, was a matter of public record and was made before <PERSON> DeRoburt </PERSON> was elected president. <LOCATION> Nauru </LOCATION> is an indepedent island nation of about eight square miles with some 4,000 residents. It is among the wealthiest nations per capita because of vast phosphate deposits. After years of legal maneuvering, a federal jury in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> decided in favor of the newspaper in 1985. The jury found that <PERSON> DeRoburt </PERSON> failed to prove actual malice _ that the newspaper knowingly printed falsehoods or acted with reckless disregard for the truth. A key issue in the case was the identity of two confidential sources relied on by the newspaper. DeRoburt at one point alleged that the sources did not exist. His lawyers wanted the jury told it could presume there were no sources. But during trial, the reporter who wrote the first article named two sources, including one who by that time had died. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the jury verdict in October 1988. The appeals court said DeRoburt's lawyers, in effect, abandoned their claim that no sources existed. They `` chose to present -LRB- DeRoburt's -RRB- case in a manner inconsistent with a theory of no sources,'' the appeals court said. For the judge `` to then instruct the jury that it should conclusively presume that there were no sources would have been contrary to the evidence presented at trial by both parties and contrary to the truth,'' the appeals court said. In the appeal acted on today, <PERSON> DeRoburt </PERSON> urged the justices to overturn their 1964 ruling that established the `` actual malice'' defense in libel suits filed by public officials. In the alternative, DeRoburt's lawyers said the burden of proving there was no actual malice should be shifted to the newspaper when it has withheld, concealed or destroyed relevant evidence. DeRoburt alleged that the reporter who wrote the first 1978 article destroyed his notes. The case is DeRoburt vs. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>, 89-9.
