<HEAD>Court Refuses to Disturb Virginia's Ban on Funeral Phone Solicitation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to disturb a state's ban on telephone solicitation for pre-arranged funerals. The court, without comment, rejected arguments by an insurance firm and two funeral directors that such a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law violates their free-speech rights. The 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last March upheld a 1951 <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law banning the telephoning of potential customers to line up funeral business. The appeals court said the Constitution permits such restrictions on commercial speech. The law was challenged by <ORGANIZATION> Guardian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, an insurance-funded funeral program, and two funeral homes that participate in the plan. Guardian sells pre-arranged, or `` pre-need'' funerals by including in the company's life insurance policies benefits to pay for funerals. When a policyholder dies, the family must agree to release the policy proceeds to a funeral home. Guardian said the plan is intended to be humane and a help to customers, sparing family members the anguish of deciding how much to pay for a funeral at the time of a loved one's death. But the <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funeral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embalmers </ORGANIZATION>, saying it was trying to protect consumers, complained about the soliciting of business over the phone. Guardian and its participating funeral homes said the state board is influenced by the funeral industry, and that the ban on phone solicitations is a ploy to reduce competition. The 4th Circuit court said, `` The <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> statute leaves open ample alternatives for -LRB- Guardian and its plan participants -RRB- to advertise their services. Consequently, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s ban on telemarketing does not violate the First Amendment.'' Guardian's appeal was supported by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cemetery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 2,000 funeral homes nationwide. The association's lawyers cited a statement by <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> officials that restricting such telephone solicitations is anti-competitive. The case is Guardian Plans vs. <PERSON> Teague </PERSON>, 89-38.
</TEXT>
