<HEAD>Court Won't Hear Alaska's Appeal to Stop Offshore Oil and Gas Exploration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s attempt to forestall offshore oil and gas exploration in its <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> suffered a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> setback today. The court, over one dissenting vote, left intact rulings that allowed the federal government last year to sell leases on 5.6 million acres of <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, off <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s southwestern coast. Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> voted to hear arguments in the case but four votes are needed to grant such review. The court turned away warnings by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> and others that an oil spill in <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> could do more environmental harm than the massive Exxon Valdez spill in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> last March. The disputed leases were sold for nearly $ 100 million after a federal judge and the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> rejected a challenge by <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> and numerous enviromental groups, fishing associations and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> communities. The federal government first began considering oil and gas leasing in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aleutian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>, which underlies <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, in 1974. After twice canceling plans for lease sales in the bay at <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s request, the secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 proposed leasing all 32.5 million acres, beginning in 1985. The secretary, in response to concerns expressed by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> officials, later restricted the leasing to the southwest corner of the region by deleting nearly 83 percent of the acreage from the sale. Under the federal Outer Continental Shelf Lands Act, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> must give the governor of any affected state a chance to make recommendations about any proposed lease sale. The governor recommended that the federal government delay selling any <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> leases for eight years, and then not sell any tracts within 25 miles of shore. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary rejected both recommendations, sparking the lawsuit. The appeal acted on today contended that the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary violated the continental shelf law because his rejection of the state's recommendations was `` arbitrary and capricious.'' In the appeal, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Baily </PERSON> referred to last March's oil spill by the grounded tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> as a dramatic example of `` the devastating impact of oil on biological resources.'' `` <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aleutian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> are substantially more remote and inaccessible than -LRB- Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> -RRB-, the weather is much more problematic ... efforts to clean up an oil spill in this area accordingly would be even less successful than in the sound,'' the appeal said. It accused the federal government of not striking `` a proper balance ... between satisfying the nation's thirst for oil and gas and protecting one of the most biologically productive and important areas in the world.'' The appeal was supported by the attorneys general of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and by the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coastal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration urged the justices to reject the appeal. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said federal law gives the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary _ not a governor _ the authority to make a final decision on lease sales. The case is <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> vs. Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION>, 88-2000.
