<HEAD>High Court Rejects Abandoned Property Case from Connecticut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to bar states from using abandoned property laws to recover some unclaimed insurance benefits. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by an insurance company ordered to turn over to <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> $ 2.5 million in unclaimed benefits. The 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last February that the state's power to collect the money is not pre-empted by the federal Employee Retirement Income Security Act -LRB- ERISA -RRB-, which regulates pensions and other employee benefit programs. <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which provides group health and accident coverage for workers, said it should be allowed to keep unclaimed benefits and use the money to lower its premiums or increase benefits. The insurance company said tens of millions of dollars could be at stake if all states sought to recover unclaimed benefits. <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> in 1981 amended its laws on abandoned property _ or escheating _ to enable the state to acquire property left unclaimed after three, rather than seven, years. The state said <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> must turn over to it $ 2.5 million in unclaimed benefits. A federal judge ruled in favor of <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> but the 2nd Circuit court reversed that decision. `` We think that the impact of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>'s escheat law on <ORGANIZATION> ERISA </ORGANIZATION> benefit plans is too tenuous, remote and peripheral to require pre-emption'' of the state law by the federal statute, the appeals court said. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Borges </PERSON>, 88-1883.
