<HEAD>Jury-Selection Decision Expanded in 3 Southern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today allowed its decision barring prosecutors from excluding potential jurors based on their race to be applied to all non-criminal trials in three southern states. The justices, over one dissenting vote, let stand a federal appeals court ruling in a <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> case that extended their 1986 decision to all civil trials. Although today's action sets no national precedent. It leaves intact a binding precedent for courts in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> voted to hear arguments in the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> case but four votes are needed to grant such review. The justices in 1986 curtailed dramatically the traditionally broad power of prosecutors to bar prospective jurors from trials by using `` peremptory'' or automatic challenges. The court ruled that the exclusion of potential jurors from any criminal trial because of their race violates the equal-protection rights of defendants and of those people excluded. At the time of the ruling, legal experts said it likely would not apply to peremptory challenges made by defense lawyers in criminal trials or to any civil, or non-criminal, trial. But the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last Jan. 17 took a much more expansive view of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s 1986 ruling. The appeals court reinstated a lawsuit filed by a black man against the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, deputy sheriff who shot him. The appeals court said the trial judge must determine whether the deputy sheriff's lawyer used two peremptory challenges to exclude black potential jurors for non-racial reasons. `` We hold that -LRB- the 1986 ruling -RRB- applies in civil as well as criminal cases,'' said the 11th Circuit court, which has jurisdiction over <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Some government action must be present for the 14th Amendment's guarantee of equal protection to be violated, but the appeals court said such a violation can be found even in a lawsuit in which neither the government nor a government employee is involved `` When blacks are excluded from jury service on account of their race ... the trial judge constitutes the discriminatory state actor,'' the appeals court said. Although the appeals court did not say so, the decision's rationale would appear to mean that the prohibition against race-based juror exclusions applies to criminal defense lawyers as well In the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> case, deputy sheriff <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiller </PERSON> shot <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Fludd </PERSON> while attempting to apprehend a suspected narcotics trafficker. <PERSON> Fludd </PERSON> sued <PERSON> Tiller </PERSON> in federal court under a much-used civil rights law. The case is <PERSON> Tiller </PERSON> vs. Fludd, 88-2088.
</TEXT>
