<HEAD>Former Delta Pilot Fired for Flying While Drunk Loses Appeal to Regain
Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> pilot fired for operating a commercial jet while drunk lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal today in his effort to win back his job. The justices, over one dissenting vote, let stand lower court rulings that the pilot's reinstatement would be contrary to public policy. A labor arbitration board previously had ordered his reinstatement. Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> voted to hear arguments in the case but four votes are needed to grant such review. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>, a Boston-based pilot for <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, was fired in 1985 after airline officials discovered he had been drunk while commanding a flight from <LOCATION> Bangor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The flight was without incident. Shortly after his firing, Day was medically diagnosed as an alcoholic. After treatment, he was recertified by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Day challenged his firing, and under the terms of a contract <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> and his union, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, his grievance was submitted to a five-member arbitration board. Comprised of two members appointed by the airline, two appointed by the union and one neutral chairman, the board split 3-2 in finding that Day had been fired without `` just cause.'' Although stating that Day was guilty of serious misconduct, the board concluded that he should have been offered the option of enrolling in <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s alcohol rehabilitation program. The board ordered his reinstatement without back pay. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> challenged the board's reinstatement order in federal court, and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orinda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> overturned the board. `` Requiring Delta to cooperate with Day and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> in recertifying Day is violative of public policy,'' the judge ruled. The 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld that ruling last Dec. 8. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> argued that the lower court rulings conflict with a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision that limited the power of federal judges to overrule labor arbitrators. In that decision, the court ruled unanimously that judges may reverse an arbitration award for public-policy reasons only if the award creates an explicit conflict with laws or legal precedent. Such judicial reversals can not be based on `` general considerations f supposed public interest,'' the justices said in their 1987 ruling. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the pilots' union called the lower court rulings examples of `` the continuing erosion of the doctrine of finality of arbitration awards.'' They urged the justices to restore the arbitration board ruling that would reinstate Day. The case is <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1901.
