<HEAD>Cancer Institute Says Drug Combination Aids Colon Cancer Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A drug used to deworm farm animals combined with a common cancer drug has been found to save the lives of patients who would have died from an advanced type of colon cancer, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> announced today. <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Broder </PERSON> said that a national study involving about 1,300 patients with a stage 3 type of colon cancer showed increased survival rates for those treated with a drug called levamisole in combination with 5-fluorouracil, a cancer drug now in common use. The study was directed by Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moertel </PERSON> of the Mayo Clinic. At a news conference today, <PERSON> Moertel </PERSON> said that the study showed 49 percent of stage III colon cancer patients were alive five years after therapy with the drug combination compared to only 37 percent of such patients who received no drugs. Both of the patient groups being compared had been treated with surgery, which revealed that the colon cancer had spread to nearby lymph nodes. In cancer therapy this stage of the disease is called <PERSON> Dukes </PERSON>' C. With today's announcement, <PERSON> Broder </PERSON> said that physicians are encouraged to discuss this treatment option with patients at this stage of colon cancer. He said the combination drug therapy is started three to five weeks after surgery and is continued for about a year. <PERSON> Levamisole </PERSON> is a drug that is used by veterinarians to clear worms from the intestine of barnyard animals. It is not now approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> for any human use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The drug, however, is commonly used in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to treat worm infestation in humans and it has been used widely in experimental treatment of cancers. <PERSON> Moertel </PERSON> said the drug combination of levamisole and 5-fluorouracil has not been proven effective against colon cancers at an earlier stage in the disease or for those whose surgeries occurred at a much earlier time. <PERSON> Broder </PERSON> said a specific description of this new treatment method is being mailed to doctors around the country and that physicians may obtain levamisole through the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>.
