<HEAD>Unprecedented Protest March Held in `Independent' Homeland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 25,000 blacks demanded clemency for two condemned <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas today in the largest protest march ever held in one of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s nominally independent tribal homelands. The marchers, most of them schoolchildren, paraded peacefully through the center of <LOCATION> Umtata </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION>. Some carried <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> flags and displayed placards urging the release of two members of the guerrilla movement who are on death row in <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION> for a 1986 bombing which killed two people at the <ORGANIZATION> Wild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION>, a posh gambling resort overlooking the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. The homeland's official radio estimated the crowd at 25,000 and said police did not interfere. The protest came a day after <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION>'s military leader, Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Bantu </PERSON> <PERSON> Holomisa </PERSON>, declared at a funeral service that he would consider holding a referendum to let homeland voters decide if they wanted to rejoin <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The Star, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s largest daily newspaper, said the government faced a `` major challenge to its grand apartheid plan'' if <PERSON> Holomisa </PERSON> proceeded with a referendum. The result, said The Star, would be an overwhelming vote to rejoin <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, thus repudiating the white government's longstanding contention that blacks preferred autonomy in separate ethnic states. The homeland system also came under heavy criticism Sunday in <LOCATION> Botshabelo </LOCATION>, a vast rural shantytown in the <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> which the government has placed under the jurisdiction of Qwaqwa, one of six semi-autonomous homelands. An estimated 15,000 to 20,000 of <PERSON> Botshabelo </PERSON>'s 500,000 residents marched in protest against their incorporation into Qwaqwa, which is 180 miles from their community. Many Botshabelo residents fear Qwaqwa may be declared independent, thus depriving them of South African citizenship. Like many other blacks, they feel <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, despite its segregation laws, offers better opportunities than the impoverished homelands in regard to pensions, employment and housing. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 28 million blacks have voting rights only in the homelands and in local elections. National policy is controlled by the 5 million whites. <PERSON> Holomisa </PERSON>, at the funeral Sunday of a tribal chief who opposed <ORGANIZATION> Transkei </ORGANIZATION>'s independence, shared a podium for the first time with prominent anti-apartheid activists. Speakers at the service denounced the homeland system and praised the late chief, <PERSON> Sabata </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalindyebo </PERSON>, for his staunch opposition to the excision of <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in 1976. <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION> was the first of four homelands to accept `` independence'' from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as part of a plan by white officials to create separate nations for each major black tribe. None of the four are recognized internationally. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, declined to comment on <PERSON> Holomisa </PERSON>'s statement, saying he had received no official communication from <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION>. A ministry official, requesting anonymity, said any bid by <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION> to renounce its independence would be a matter for negotiations between <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the homeland. <PERSON> Holomisa </PERSON>, 34, took power in <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION> in a bloodless coup in 1987. He is the first leader of a nominally independent homeland to make favorable references to the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and he reportedly held secret talks earlier this year with the group's exiled president, <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Tambo </PERSON> <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION> lies along <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s southern coast between the port cities of <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. It covers about 18,000 square miles and has about 3.5 million residents.
