 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to hear an appeal by non-union <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> state employees who oppose paying the equivalent of dues to a union that represents them in collective bargaining. The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that the employees' rights were not violated when they were forced to financially support the union's negotiating efforts. The employees are challenging the deduction from their paychecks of what is known as agency fees. The fees average $ 263 a year per worker and are paid in lieu of union dues. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and Municipal Employees -LRB- AFSME -RRB- is the collective-bargaining agent for <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s state employees, union and non-union members alike. The union signed an agrement with state officials July 28, 1988, to deduct the agency fees from some 18,000 non-union employees beginning the following month. Fifteen non-union employees sued in federal court to block the deductions. They said the fees violate their constitutional rights because some of the money would be used to support causes and politicians they do not support _ including Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. After the suit was filed, the union agreed to place the fees in an escrow account _ barring their use by the union _ until an arbitrator decides whether the union may use the money or refund it. The non-union members then sought a court order returning the money to them and barring the union from collecting any further deductions pending outcome of the case. The 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> den