ay building which had fallen 4.5 percent in July. `` That's a number which from time to time shows a big one-month increase and quite often will come back to the previous trend-level in the following months and I suspect we'll see that this time,'' <PERSON> Obrinsky </PERSON> said. Residential construction, which accounts for nearly half of construction spending, posted a tiny fractional increase of 0.05 percent to an annual rate of $ 198.9 billion. But single-family construction fell 0.2 percent to an annual rate of $ 113.1 billion while apartment building gained 0.4 percent to $ 23.5 billion. <PERSON> Obrinsky </PERSON> said he expects the pace of housing starts to improve in the fourth quarter, but at a modest pace. Non-residential construction was up 2.9 percent to an annual rate of $ 100.3 billion, led by advances of 4.5 percent in office buildings and 1.8 percent in factories. Total construction was up 3.4 percent from the level of building a year ago.
