grant review. Picks up graf 3, The justices.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A blind, aspiring minister who for nine years has sought financial aid from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state so he can attend <PERSON> Bible </PERSON> college lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal today. The court, without comment, let stand the state's refusal to subsidize vocational training for <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Witters </PERSON>. He argued that the refusal violates his religious freedom. The justices in 1986 ruled unanimously that the state's providing <PERSON> Witters </PERSON> with financial aid would not violate the constitutionally required separation of church and state The 1986 decision overturned a <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that had said giving <PERSON> Witters </PERSON> money under a state vocational-training program for the blind would promote religion impermissibly. <PERSON> Witters </PERSON>' case then returned to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which last April 20 ruled, by a 5-4 vote, that letting <PERSON> Witters </PERSON> receive the state funding would violate a state constitution ban. A provision of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s constitution says, `` No public money ... shall be appropriated for or applied to any religious ... instruction.'' In the appeal acted on today, <PERSON> Witters </PERSON> argued that the state constitution's provision violates his religious freedom protected by the federal Constitution's First Amendment. His case crystalizes the inherent tension between two First Amendment clauses _ one banning official `` establishment'' of religion and one banning official interference with `` the free exercise'' of religion. <PERSON> Witters </PERSON>, who is legally blind, was first denied aid in 1980. As a result, he was forced to drop out of the Inland Empire School of the Bible in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> and take a dish-washing job in a medical laboratory. His appeal said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had excluded <PERSON> Witters </PERSON> `` from receiving the benefits of public welfare legislation because of his faith.'' The appeal likened the state's treatment of <PERSON> Witters </PERSON> to an attempt by <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> to ban religious clubs from meeting on state college campuses and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>'s attempt to bar ministers from holding elective office. The nation's highest court struck down both of those state attempts as unconstitutional infringements of religious rights. In urging the justices to reject <PERSON> Witters </PERSON>' appeal, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Eikenberry </PERSON> argued, `` The problem with what -LRB- <PERSON> Witters </PERSON> -RRB- wants arises from the type of instruction which he wishes the state to fund, not from his career goal or from the institution he wishes to attend.'' <PERSON> Eikenberry </PERSON> said <PERSON> Witters </PERSON> would be eligible for state funding if he took non-religious courses, even at the Bible school. The case is <PERSON> Witters </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> for the Blind, 89-94.
