 President <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> called on fractious Afghan rebel groups Monday to unite to form an Islamic government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and to reject <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support. The official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, also quoted <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> as calling for an end to superpower intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, where U.S.-backed Moslem rebels have been fighting 11 years to oust the Soviet-backed government. Opening an international seminar on the Afghan issue, the president urged all Afghan groups to cooperate in their fight for self-determination and `` to isolate ideologies alien to Afghan culture and tradition.'' The seven-group guerrilla alliance is based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The Sunni Moslem alliance has been at odds with another guerrilla coalition of Shiite Moslems based in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which is overwhelmingly <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> as saying only <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION> could guarantee <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s territorial integrity and independence. `` We are for an independent, Islamic and non-aligned <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>,'' he declared. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has been taking a growing role in efforts to form an interim government dominated by the guerrillas, known as mujahedeen, following the Soviet military withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in February. The Iranian effort has developed as <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s relations with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> have improved, in large part because of the Soviet withdrawal. The Soviets regularly consult the Iranians on developments in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s northeastern neighbor. Iranian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> told delegates to the <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> conference that recognizing <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s role in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> contradicted the interests of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s Moslem people, <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` The future of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> does not depend on a certain person or group, but rather on the Afghan nation which has suffered a great deal and should decide the country's fate,'' he added. That was an apparent reference to the split in guerrilla ranks.
