<HEAD>31 Killed Despite Government Cease-fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty-one people died in the bloodiest 24-hour period since the government declared a unilateral cease-fire last week, military officials reported Monday. Twenty-four people were murdered by Sinhalese radicals, six were killed by soldiers they had ambushed, and a jailed Sinhalese extremist committed suicide, the officials said. A soldier and a child were wounded in the ambush Sunday at <LOCATION> Girikola </LOCATION> village, 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, said the officials, whose names can not be used under briefing rules. The deaths brought the total to 59 since the government proclaimed the cease-fire Wednesday. It originally was called for three days, then extended until 6 a.m. Tuesday. President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> instructed the military to halt operations against members of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, a Sinhalese radical group, but said they were allowed to defend themselves. He declared the truce to give the radicals among the Sinhalese, <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s predominant ethnic group, an opportunity to end their 2-year-old uprising and join peace talks. At least 5,000 people have been killed in the violence. The People's <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> rejected negotiations and continued its campaign of killings and arson, but the government said 869 extremists had surrendered during the cease-fire. Military officials said the 24 people killed by Sinhalese radicals included two soldiers whose vehicle was blown up. They said the other victims were police informants, members of policemen's families or supporters of the government. At least 14 post offices, 17 government buildings and three buses were burned, the officials reported. Violence increased after <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> took office in January, after elections the extremists claimed were fraudulent. They oppose the 1987 peace accord with ethnic Tamil separatists and the presence of Indian soldiers assigned to supervise the peace plan. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has said it will withdraw its troops by Dec. 31. About 11,000 people have been killed in the Tamil war, which began in 1983. Tamils, predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Hindu </ORGANIZATION>, make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and claim discrimination by the Sinhalese, most of whom are Buddhists <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved because it is the regional power and has a Tamil population of 60 million. Most live in <LOCATION> Tamil </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nadu </LOCATION> state, just across the <LOCATION> Palk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>.
