<HEAD>Court To Decide Bar Association Dues Issue in California Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether attorneys may withhold their state bar association dues if the association uses the money to campaign for various causes and issues. The justices said they will hear arguments by 21 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> lawyers who say their free-speech rights are being violated because they are forced to pay dues to the bar group in order to continue practicing law in the state. The attorneys said the money is being used to promote numerous ideological causes, including a nuclear weapons freeze and handgun control, that they do not support. The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in February that the lawyers' rights were not violated, except if money is used by the bar association to help finance campaigns of candidates for public office `` We conclude that the state bar may use dues to finance any activity, except election campaigning, which is germane to its statutory mission to promote the improvement of the administration of justice,'' the state court said. The ruling conflicts with decisions by other state courts that limit the power of state bar associations to use members' dues for ideological purposes. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> court said the bar association, with power to license and discipline lawyers, is more like a state agency than a labor union. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has limited the power of unions to spend dues money for public-issue lobbying. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> court noted that every lawyer in the state must be a member of the bar to practice law there. Also, the state court said, the bar association is run by a governing board that includes six of 22 members appointed by the governor with approval of the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Constitution, statutes and judicial decisions ... appear to envision the bar as a governmental agency,'' the state court said. Therefore, the state court continued, the bar association may use its revenues `` for any purposes within its authority.'' Issues of public health, safety and welfare fall within that category, the state court said. But the state court said the bar association went too far in 1982 when it distributed material supporting justices of the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> who were up for re-election. The material permissibly supported the independence of the judiciary, the state court said. But `` its primary purpose, we believe, was to assist in the election campaign on behalf of the justices.'' That exceeded the association's authority, the state court added. The case is <PERSON> Keller </PERSON> vs. State Bar of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, 88-1905.
