<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 40 years of living together, <PERSON> Axel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eigil </PERSON> <PERSON> Axgil </PERSON> spent a happy first day as a `` married couple'' Monday. <PERSON> Axel </PERSON>, 74, and <PERSON> Eigil </PERSON>, 67, were among the first 11 male couples to exchange vows Sunday as <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> became the first country to give homosexual couples legal status and the right to join in a `` registered partnership.'' Hundreds of homosexuals applauded, waved flags and threw rice on them on the Town Hall steps, while <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> fundamentalists demonstrated on the other side of the square. One demonstrator waving a Bible called it `` Sodom's Day.'' `` Homosexuality is a sin,'' he said. Parliament in May approved a gay rights bill by a lopsided majority. Only the small <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> party opposed the measure. The law, which took effect Sunday, gives homosexual couples nearly equal rights as heterosexual couples but bars them from adopting children. They have the same inheritance rights, tax advantages and the right to share a last name. Under the new law, at least one partner must have Danish citizenship and live in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>. Like the other 10 couples, <PERSON> Axel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eigil </PERSON> solemnly answered `` yes'' to deputy mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahlberg </PERSON> when he asked if they consented to tie each other in `` a registered partnership.'' They combined their first names to form a common last name. `` We decided to get officially ` married' because we have the same feelings for each other as heterosexual couples,'' said <PERSON> Axel </PERSON>, speaking on Danish television. He and <PERSON> Eigil </PERSON> later left town for several days, friends said, apparently on a honeymoon. No lesbian couples have been registered. `` We do n't like to be in the front