<HEAD>Czechoslovak Dissident Writer Honored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Czechoslovak writer <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> on Monday was named winner of the $ 16,000 Olof Palme Prize for public service. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s most prominent human rights activist, was cited for `` his consistent and brave efforts for truth and democracy,'' said Foreign Minister <PERSON> Sten </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersson </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Olof </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, a playwright, was jailed for four months this year. `` <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> is today a uniting figure in the struggle for human rights _ not only in his own country. In spite of his beliefs, which resulted in repeated jail terms, his humanistic view on life is unbroken, and through his literary work he is an inspiration to us all,'' <PERSON> Andersson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was invited to receive the prize in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> in November, a statement said. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> was given the award last year and black South African labor leader <PERSON> Cyril </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramaphosa </PERSON> received it in 1987. The prize was created three days after Palme, the Swedish prime minister, was assassinated on a street in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> on Feb. 28, 1986. <PERSON> Christer </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> was sentenced to life imprisonment for the murder earlier this year. His appeal is being heard in a higher court.
