<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. SOBRIETY CHECKPOINTS The court agreed to decide whether police nationwide may try to curb drunken driving by stopping motorists at sobriety checkpoints. The justices said they will review <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> court rulings that struck down that state's sobriety checkpoint program as an unconstitutional invasion of privacy. Courts in other states have upheld virtually identical checkpoint programs. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Sitz </PERSON>, 88-1897. PATRONAGE The court agreed to decide whether public employers may be forced to put aside partisanship when hiring, promoting and transferring workers. The court said it will hear an appeal by two men and a woman who said their job status suffered because they did n't support the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. The cases are <PERSON> Rutan </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1872, and <PERSON> Frech </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Rutan </PERSON>, 88-2074. WORKER SAFETY The court let states file criminal charges against employers accused of neglecting the health and safety of workers. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling in an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case that federal workplace regulations do not bar such state prosecutions. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Asta </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1783. BAIL The court agreed to consider increasing the federal government's power to keep some accused criminals behind bars while they await trial The court said it will review a ruling in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> case that forces the government to free, on bail, some defendants deemed to be dangerous or a risk to flee before trial. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. Montalvo-Murillo, 89-163. TRESPASSING The court turned aside an appeal by three people convicted of trespassing for handing out anti-abortion booklets to students outside a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> high school. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that distribution of the `` pro-life'' literature on school grounds was not protected by the Constitution's free-speech guarantees. The case is <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, 88-2077. EVANGELICAL GROUP The court turned aside an appeal by an evangelical <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> group ordered to return most of the $ 6.5 million donated by a wealthy ex-member. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that the group, The Bible Speaks, received the donations after exerting undue influence on department store heiress <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Dovydenas </PERSON>. The religious group now must return $ 5.5 million. The case is The Bible Speaks vs. Dovydenas, 88-1977. FOSTER CARE The court refused to revive an allegedly abused foster child's federal lawsuit against the social workers and government agency that placed him in his foster home The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling in a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> case that no such right to sue exists. The case is <PERSON> Milburn </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Anne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arundel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, 89-96. MAFIA APPEALS The court turned aside appeals by eight Mafia figures from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> convicted in the 1979 killings of crime chieftain <PERSON> Carmine </PERSON> <PERSON> Galante </PERSON> and two of his associates. The court, without comment, let stand the federal racketeering convictions of family bosses <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Salerno </PERSON>, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Corallo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carmine </PERSON> <PERSON> Persico </PERSON>, high-ranking mobsters <PERSON> Salvatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Santoro </PERSON>, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Furnari </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gennaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Langella </PERSON>, and mob members <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Indelicato </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Scopo </PERSON>. The cases are <PERSON> Indelicato </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-1881; <LOCATION> Salerno </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-2060; <PERSON> Persico </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-2061; Scopo vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-2071. LAWYERS FEES The court agreed to decide whether lawyers who win civil rights cases can collect a big chunk of their clients' awards under an agreement made when the attorneys were hired. The court said it will hear an appeal by a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> man awarded $ 2.12 million and then ordered to pay 40 percent of the judgment to his lawyer. The case is <PERSON> Venegas </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, 88-1725. PILOT The court turned down the appeal of a former <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> pilot fired for operating a commercial jet while drunk who is trying to win back his job. The justices, over one dissenting vote, let stand lower court rulings that the pilot's reinstatement would be contrary to public policy. The case is <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1901. AUTOMOBILE INSURANCE The court let states require automobile insurance for motorists who say it violates their religious convictions. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> man who believes having insurance belittles a promise from God to provide in any situation. The case acted is <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, 89-10. GENERAL MOTORS SUIT The court let stand a $ 1.2 million bonus in fees awarded to the lawyers of consumers who sued over allegedly defective transmissions in some General Motor cars. The justices, without comment, turned away arguments that federal law does not allow such fee bonuses when lawyers win cases in which there was a substantial risk of non-payment because of a loss. The case is <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Skelton </PERSON>, 88-1848. BANKRUPTCY The court said it will consider placing new limits on the ability of convicted criminals to avoid making restitution to their victims by declaring bankruptcy. The court agreed to hear an appeal by <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> officials seeking to recover $ 4,145 from a couple who pleaded guilty to welfare fraud. The case is <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Davenport </PERSON>, 89-156. HUSTLER The court rejected an appeal by an anti-pornography activist who says sexually explicit photographs and caricatures in Hustler magazine libeled her and invaded her privacy. The court, without comment, refused to revive a $ 150 million lawsuit by feminist author <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON>. The case is <PERSON> Dworkin </PERSON> vs. Hustler, 88-1900. GRAND JURY WITNESSES The court agreed to decide whether states may prohibit grand jury witnesses from making public their own testimony once the investigation has ended. The justices said they will review an attempt by <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> officials to block a former newspaper reporter from disclosing details of his appearance before a grand jury three years ago. A federal appeals court said a state law barring such public disclosure violates free-speech rights. The case is <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 88-1993. MEDICAID The court agreed to decide whether hospitals and nursing care homes may sue in federal court to challenge how a state-run Medicaid program reimburses their costs. The court said it will review a ruling that would allow a hospital association to invoke a federal civil rights law in suing <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> over the state's Medicaid reimbursement rates. The case is <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, 88-2043. DISABILITY The court agreed to consider making it easier for the government to cut off disability pay to some former federal workers. The court said it will review a ruling that barred termination of a disability annuity for a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> man who was given incorrect information about benefits eligibility. The case is Office of Personnel Mangement vs. <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, 88-1943. BLACK LUNG The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> agreed to decide whether a federal law unfairly makes it too difficult for coal miners who contract `` black lung'' disease to obtain a lawyer's help when seeking benefits. The justices said they will review a <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruling that the system for awarding lawyer fees in black lung benefits cases violates due-process rights. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Triplett </PERSON>, 88-1671.
