<HEAD>Official Hopeful Two Months After Dog's Disappearance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOPKINTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The town council president remained hopeful Monday that her golden retriever will be returned, two months after it disappeared in a possible political extortion attempt. The 7-year-old dog, <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, failed to return home July 31 from a nightly romp on <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Johanson </PERSON>'s 64-acre estate. Twelve hours later, Mrs. <PERSON> Johanson </PERSON> received an anonymous telephone call from a man who said: `` Get off the council and you'll get your dog.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Johanson </PERSON> said she is confident the dog is alive. And she vowed to remain in office. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Weeden </PERSON>, chief of the town's 10-member police force, said Monday he has no new leads. Several people were interviewed, and at least one was given a lie-detector test, but no arrests had been made. Some residents of this rural town of 7,000 people, about 45 miles south of <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, have speculated the dog's disappearance could be related to the November firings of the town dump custodian and the highway supervisor. The highway official was reinstated, then resigned.
