<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 51-year absence from the stage in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> only made <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> more charming to an enthralled audience. The Academy Award-winning actress was joined briefly on stage by her son, actor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> MacArthur </PERSON>, for a Sunday benefit performance attended by about 400 people at the <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> theater. Ms. <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> gave a lecture peppered with anecdotes from her eight decades on the stage and performed a humorous <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurber </PERSON> sketch with her son. At the end of the 90-minute program, the audience sang `` Happy Birthday'' with <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> accompanying on the piano. Ms. <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> will be 89 on Oct. 10. Ms. <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> last appeared in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> in 1938, in the touring version of `` <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> <PERSON> Regina </PERSON>,'' playing Queen <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> from youth to old age. She said she has been inspired for more than 50 years by a line from that play, in which a working-class Londoner shouts to the aged <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION>: `` Go it, old girl! You done it good!'' `` I think I want that on my tombstone,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
