<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Runs Out of Visa Applications for Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Emigration, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of would-be emigrants lined up outside the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy for visa applications Monday as new rules on emigration took effect, but the embassy quickly ran out of new forms and turned away thouands of angry people. Consular officials distributed 30,500 applications at a rate of 100 per minute, with a maximum of five allotted each person, before running out in about 2 -LCB- hours. Another 70,000 application forms were expected to be delivered to the embassy by the end of the week, an official said, and 300,000 more shortly thereafter. `` We hope to be out of the woods by Friday,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Many Soviets were angry at being turned away and are upset at the new regulations, which require applicants to deal with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> rather than the embassy in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The changes were made because the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy was unable to handle the flood of applications. `` It is a conspiracy between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and Soviet authorities,'' said one woman who refused to give her name. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Embassy should be ashamed of the way they are treating us,'' said another Soviet, who also refused to identify himself. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has long urged the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to liberalize its emigration policy. But now that Soviet rules have become more lax, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has found it can not accept all the Soviets who wish to emigrate. The new regulations that went into effect Oct. 1 spurred a surge in the number of people lining up at the embassy, and more than 15,000 lined up over the weekend to be among the first to get new forms. They organized themselves into groups of 100, with group leaders holding up signs so people could secure a place in line, then leave and return later. On Monday morning, traffic around the embassy on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s busy Garden Ring Road was snarled, and the sidewalks around the embassy were jammed with people. When the applications ran out, people still were lined up between signs with numbers up to 11,000. According to Soviets at a shack set up to register for a place in line, 17,000 people had signed up over the weekend. A reporter visiting the embassy was besieged by hundreds of people who though he was a consular official. They demanded to know when they would get the applications and whether photocopies would be acceptable in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Several times during the day, embassy officials waded into the crowd that had waited overnight to explain that new forms would be available Wednesday and that photocopies would be acceptable. Hundreds of people have lined up outside the embassy every working day since Soviet officials began liberalizing emigration policies last year, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have been swamped with paperwork. Under the new regulations, applications will be sent directly to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> rather than evaluated by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> consular officials. An official said last week that the embassy is likely to receive 300,000 applications in the next year but will be able to accept only about 70,000-80 ,000 Following ceilings set in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will accept 50,000 Soviets classified as refugees and another 20,000-30 ,000 on a so-called parole system that does not guarantee any government support The new system also gives priority to people with close relatives already in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and to those who belong to groups that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> considers to be persecuted in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
