<SECOND>AM-Runcie-Vatican,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Runcie Ends Visit on High Note but With Little Visible Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anglican leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> and Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> signed a document Monday committing their churches to eventually heal their 450-year-old split but recognizing they still had a long way to go. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>'s first official visit to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> yielded few other visible signs of progress in relations between the world's two largest groups of Christians. However, <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> said he had built trust with <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> officials during four days of talks and that their commitment to seeking unity was no mere `` academic exercise.'' `` The way in which the conversations we have had together bear fruit will come about gradually,'' he told a news conference. Among major points separating the churches is the doctrine of papal infallibility, which applies to Roman Catholic beliefs such as the Immaculate Conception of the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> and her assumption to heaven after death. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> is the fourth archbishop of <ORGANIZATION> Canterbury </ORGANIZATION> to visit the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> since the late <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> did so in 1960, ending four centuries of estrangement that began when King <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> VIII </PERSON> formed his own church after the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> refused to grant him an annulment of his marriage. Talks have been under way since 1966 on a theological framework for unifying the world's 850 million Roman Catholics and 70 million Anglicans. The document signed Monday said: `` We here solemnly recommit ourselves and those we represent to the restoration of visible unity and full ecclesial communion.'' But it noted the ordination of women in some of the Anglican Communion's 27 self-governing provinces, such as the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, `` prevents reconciliation between us even where there is otherwise progress toward agreement.'' Nonetheless, Cardinal <PERSON> Johannes </PERSON> <PERSON> Willebrands </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promoting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION>, said `` obstacles are there to be considered and overcome.'' <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>, the head of the state <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION>, repeatedly emphasized one of the advances in Anglican-Catholic talks _ an Anglican proposal to grant the pope a `` universal primacy'' over Anglicans. Other advances in recent years have included a draft agreement on how people's souls are saved. But many practical barriers to unity remain, including differences on the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> ban on artificial birth control; some Anglican churches' acceptance of abortion and divorce; the role of lay people in the church; and the Anglican practice of allowing married priests. Still, Anglican-Catholic talks are considered among the most promising inter-faith discussions in which the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> is involved, and Anglican officials say they expect some kind of unity in the 21st century. While both sides described the Anglican-Catholic meetings as extremely friendly, <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>'s speeches expressed more eagerness about unification than the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s. Willebrands indicated the hesitancy of some <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials when he discussed a delay in the church's response to a 7-year-old Anglican-Catholic report on possible theological agreements. `` We have often to consider in the church at large ... problems of internal struggles or differences of opinion, etcetera, and it is rather new to consider officially ecumenical documents,'' he said. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> left the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> meetings with the promise <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> officials would respond soon to the 1982 report by the theological commission. That report included agreements on the Eucharist and priesthood and said Anglicans could recognize the pope as a universal primate, but with somewhat reduced powers. <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>'s appeals for a leadership role for the pope drew fire from the Rev. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> Protestant leader and anti-pope activist, who charged at an impromptu news conference that <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> was trying to `` dethrone the queen and enthrone the pope'' in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON> said he envisioned a spiritual rather than political role for the pope, aimed at helping churches to promote religious practice.
