<HEAD>Gorbachev Asks Legislature for Ban on Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads thruout to add details, background on strikes, parliamentary
debate. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> urged the legislature on Monday to impose a 15-month ban on strikes that he says are wrecking the Soviet economy and threatening development. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> spoke at the end of a stormy two-hour legislative debate on a proposal of emergency economic measures put forward by First Deputy Premier <PERSON> Lev </PERSON> <PERSON> Voronin </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> urged legislators to discuss the strike ban overnight and be ready to vote on it Tuesday. He referred to the possible ban on strikes as a `` necessary measure ... which are called for to protect democratization from anarchy and irresponsible management.'' Plans for future economic development are `` under threat'' because of the strikes, he said. Emergency measures to bolster the rapidly faltering economy overshadowed Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>'s lengthy presentation of a package of legislation covering the government's long-term proposals on property, ownership and use of land, and taxes. <PERSON> Voronin </PERSON> told the legislature the Soviet economy had lost $ 6.15 billion in July and August alone due to strikes and that supplies of fuel are low enough that the country might be unable to supply enough heat to see Soviet citizens through the winter. The most damaging of a series of strikes to hit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> this year was a walkout in July by thousands of coal miners in the far north, <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, and the <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Basin </PERSON> of the eastern <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>. That strike alone cost the country millions of rubles, and the government agreed to a package of economic and social improvements that officials say will cost about $ 3 billion. Strikes also have become a way of expressing ethnic discontent. Such actions have idled the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region, the center of a dispute between the neighboring <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> republics of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Moldavia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, Russian and other workers walked off jobs at factories and offices during the summer to protest laws that they said favored the majority Moldavians and Estonians. After legislators expressed contradictory viewpoints during a debate, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> proposed they return Tuesday to vote on the strike ban, and an overwhelming majority agreed, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The package of government proposals also calls for imposing a `` special form of administration'' on railroads in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, with the ministries of railroads, defense and interior responsible for protecting the railroads and their workers. Armenian activists say Azerbaijani railroad workers recently have blocked the trains that <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> depends upon for 80 percent of the goods brought in from other parts of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Food stores have been emptied of many basic goods and there is no fuel even for vehicles such as ambulances. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said when the Supreme Soviet opened its fall session Sept. 25 that decisive steps would have to be taken if rails to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> were not cleared. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> and radical deputies both named the law on property as the most important of five key economic reforms presented to the legislature, but they disagreed on what it should say. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said the central government must learn to refrain from interfering in local economic affairs _ including its tendency to claim all forms of property for itself. `` As long as about 90 percent of the basic means of production belong in the framework of one owner _ the government _ all talk about developing a market will remain empty words, and progress is impossible,'' he said. But progressive Deputy <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobchak </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> said the government's proposal still started from the point of view that the state had priority of ownership, and individuals were last. He said it should be just the opposite. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said the government saw no reason to allow private ownership of land but supported expanded rights for farmers who lease land on long-term contracts from collective and state farms.
