<FIRST>u w AM-Soviet-Psychiatry     10-02 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Psychiatry,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say They've Reformed Psychiatric Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet authorities have formed an independent commission to monitor psychiatric abuses, an embassy spokesman testified Monday, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> experts said the reform was not adequate to readmit the Soviets to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Seeking to bolster the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> case, <PERSON> Georgi </PERSON> <PERSON> Markosov </PERSON> of the Soviet Embassy appeared before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel to detail reforms his government has taken to correct psychiatric abuses against political and religious prisoners. The Soviet `` All-Union Scientific Society of Psychiatrists ... is doing its utmost to implement and translate into reality the needed reforms in the field of medical care and psychiatric health,'' said <PERSON> Markosov </PERSON>, reading a statement prepared by the Soviet society for the hearing. `` To prevent the use of psychiatry for non-medical purposes as well as to assure maximum openness in specific cases of misuse of psychiatry, an independent commission has been established, which is composed of eight persons ... The commission is independent from the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> or any -LRB- Communist -RRB- Party or state organs,'' <PERSON> Markosov </PERSON> said. Before this year, it was rare for Soviet officials to testify before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but since January, about a half dozen have done so. <PERSON> Markosov </PERSON> also listed other reforms, including: _ New regulations that led to dropping 736,000 people from so-called psychiatric registration lists <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> experts said the lists contained 10.2 million names, and were used for job screening. _ New rules that bar forcible commitment to a psychiatric institution without the consent of patients or their relatives, unless the patient poses a physical danger `` Psychiatrists who wrongly hospitalize mentally healthy persons may be sentenced to a two-year prison term.'' _ Abolition in the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> federation, the largest of the 15 Soviet republics, of two laws often used against dissidents _ A ban on the use of sulphazine, a drug made of pulverized sulphur that has been injected into political dissidents, causing extreme pain, fever and disorientation Western experts say it has no medical value. Most of the steps had been publicized previously, but the existence of the commission was not known in the West, said another witness, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Reddaway </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor who has written two books on Soviet psychiatric abuses and was a member of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation that visited Soviet psychiatric institutions this year. `` It remains to be seen whether it is indeed vigorous and independent,'' said <PERSON> Reddaway </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which supported the work of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation, has voted to oppose readmission of the Soviet group to the world body, which is scheduled to meet in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, Oct. 11-16. `` It is my sincere hope as well as the hope of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, that there will be a time in the near future when we can whole-heartedly welcome the <ORGANIZATION> All-Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatrists </ORGANIZATION> and Narcologists of the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> into the World Psychiatric Assocation,'' testified <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON>, head of international programs for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> organization. `` It is also our concern that, unfortunately, this time has not yet arrived,'' said <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON>. Soviet health officials who in the past sent dissidents to psychiatric institutions remain in senior government posts, said <PERSON> Reddaway </PERSON>, and they could resume their abuses if there is a conservative reaction along the lines of the crackdown in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> this summer. The officials he mentioned were <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON>, the health minister, <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Zharikov </PERSON>, last year appointed the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatrists </ORGANIZATION> and Narcologists, <PERSON> Georgy </PERSON> <PERSON> Morozov </PERSON>, who for decades has headed the <ORGANIZATION> Serbsky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> where many political dissidents have been held in psychiatric care, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Churkin </PERSON>, chief psychiatrist of the ministry of health, and <PERSON> Marat </PERSON> <PERSON> Vartanyan </PERSON>. These conservatives, said <PERSON> Reddaway </PERSON>, `` have a well justified fear that if there is a genuine reform in Soviet psychiatry, they will be swept out of office.'' Senior Soviet psychiatric authorities want to be readmitted to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Reddaway </PERSON>, but `` the reformers within Soviet psychology are opposed to it.'' Denying the Soviets readmission to the world body, said <PERSON> Reddaway </PERSON>, `` would delay genuine reform of Soviet psychiatry ...'' Soviet psychiatric abuses have been publicized for years by Western experts, some of whom also testified Monday, and are now being discussed more openly in the Soviet press. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Delegation to Assess Soviet Psychiatry, which visited the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> this year, reported to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that `` while some victims have been released, forced incarceration under the guise of treatment for insanity, remains an institutional problem,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., who presided over the hearing `` Perhaps even worse, the perpetrators of these abuses remain in key leadership positions in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> psychiatry,'' said <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> on Health and the Environment.
