<HEAD>Four Sailors Tell of Survival at Sea</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AUK2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four men whose 42-foot sailboat was overturned in a storm say they drifted for nearly four months in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and survived by trapping rainwater, spearing fish and eating seaweed. `` We needed a miracle, and we got one,'' <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> skipper <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glennie </PERSON> said after the crewmen washed ashore Sunday and were rescued on the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barrier </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. The four were all reported in good condition. After wind pushed the overturned boat ashore, the survivors said they spent their first night on land in 120 days, sheltered from rain under a tree in the bush of the island, about 60 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION>. On Sunday, they walked through bush until breaking into an empty cabin and finding warm clothes. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Speck </PERSON>, an island resident, first met the sailors at the cabin. `` At first I thought these guys were nuts,'' Speck said. `` I could n't believe it.'' The crew included owner and skipper <PERSON> Glennie </PERSON>, a sailor who designed the craft for long-distance cruising; <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hellriegel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Nalepka </PERSON>, 38, of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, who was in the second of two years as caterer for the Outward Bound program in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nalepka </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brighton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, said he lost 25 pounds but was declared fit by doctors in <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION> after a two-hour hospital visit. `` We never gave up hope. He kept hoping he was safe. ... This is wonderful,'' she said. `` It's just an amazing story.'' The sailors' trimaran <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Noelle </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Picton </LOCATION>, on the northern coast of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, on June 1 for a three-week <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> cruise that was to take them to <LOCATION> Tonga </LOCATION>. On the night of June 3, a strong wind grew to a 60-knot gale. `` About six o'clock in the morning there was a huge wave, and it just flipped the boat upside down,'' <PERSON> Glennie </PERSON> said. The boat floated on its crossbeams and cabin top, with the cabin top _ now the floor _ beneath a couple of feet of water, <PERSON> Glennie </PERSON> said. The sailboat's light, buoyant bow rode high, so it always pointed away from the wind, he said. The craft was stable and would not sink unless it had broken apart. The men, jammed four abreast in its 54-inch width, cut a hole through the hull of the yacht to gain dry access outside, without having to swim through the now-watery tunnel of the hatch, <PERSON> Glennie </PERSON> said. The yacht's two emergency locator beacons, designed to transmit for 30 days, were switched on, but there was no sign from jets overhead that their signals were detected. The boat was reported missing June 24 after it failed to arrive in <LOCATION> Tonga </LOCATION>. For the first few weeks there were survival rations. `` We had plenty of soda stowed in the forward compartment,'' <PERSON> Glennie </PERSON> said. `` We had stacks of apples and kiwifruit and we got plenty of moisture from those. But the drinks were rationed to a few ounces every night. `` After about 40 days, when we had all come to terms with things and began working as a team, we organized ourselves into making a system to collect rainwater.'' They split some plastic piping and placed the pieces together to collect rainwater, which was drained into empty soft drink bottles, <PERSON> Glennie </PERSON> said. They also ate seaweed and speared fish. `` We ate them raw, and we had plenty of vinegar on board to marinate them in,'' he said. The sailors' families had given them up for dead, said <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomes </PERSON>, <PERSON> Glennie </PERSON>'s brother-in-law. `` We were absolutely ecstatic to hear <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s voice on the phone,'' Tomes said. `` We were just so thrilled that he and the rest of the crew are still alive after so many months ... The celebrations are already under way.''
