/PERSON>, convicted of murdering reporter <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolles </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bolles </PERSON>, who had been investigating organized crime for The <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, died June 11, 1976, nine days after his car exploded. The 9th Circuit, setting aside <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON>'s death sentence, said <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s death penalty law unconstitutionally deprives defendants of the right to a jury trial because the judge, not the jury, decides whether an accused murderer is guilty of a crime warranting capital punishment. The appeals court has jurisdiction in nine Western states, including <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. The case is <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, 88-7351.
