<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> urged the parliament Monday to impose a 15-month ban on strikes, which he said are wrecking the economy and endangering development. He spoke at the end of a stormy two-hour debate on emergency economic measures proposed by <PERSON> Lev </PERSON> <PERSON> Voronin </PERSON>, the first deputy premier, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> urged legislators to discuss the proposals and be ready to vote on Tuesday. He referred to the possible ban on strikes as a `` necessary measure ... called for to protect democratization from anarchy and irresponsible management.'' Plans for future economic development are `` under threat'' from the strikes, he said. <PERSON> Voronin </PERSON> said the ailing economy lost $ 6.15 billion in July and August because of strikes, and fuel shortages might mean inadequate heat this winter. Proposals for the next 15 months include `` a prohibition on conducting strikes ... in all branches of the economy,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The package also calls for a `` special form of administration'' for railroads in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, with the ministries of railroads, defense and interior responsible for protecting the lines and their workers. Armenian activists say Azerbaijani railroad workers have blocked the trains that carry 80 percent of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s goods from other parts of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Food stores have been emptied of many basic goods and even ambulances lack fuel. When the Supreme Soviet opened its fall session Sept. 25, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said decisive steps would be required if the rail lines remained blocked. The neighboring republics in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> are in conflict over <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, a regi