<HEAD>Jewish Emigration From Soviet Union Sets Record for Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the second straight month, Jewish emigration from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> reached an all-time high, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Soviet Jewry announced Monday. In September, 8,442 Jews left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, up from the previous monthly high set in August of 6,756 emigres. Before this year, the previous high was set in October 1979, when 4,746 emigrated. At the current rate of emigration, `` we are within sight of surpassing the benchmark year of 1979,'' when 51,320 Jews left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Strober </PERSON>, a spokesman for the conference. The cumulative total this year is 41,886. Of last month's emigres, 1,042 or 12.3 percent, went to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, the conference announced The group, which has been monitoring and lobbying for Jewish emigration from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for two decades, repeated its call for the Soviet parliament to pass legislation liberalizing regulations for people seeking to leave.
