<HEAD>House Passes Bill Allowing Torture Victims To Sue Foreign Governments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Victims or families of victims of foreign government-sponsored torture could sue for damages in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> district courts under a bill passed Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. Approved on a 362-4 vote, the legislation extends to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens who have been tortured abroad the same civil redress now available to foreign nationals tortured in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` This bill puts torturers on notice they will find no safe haven in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>. All of the four votes against the bill were cast by Republicans: Reps. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Barton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyl </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Stump </PERSON>, both of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the legislation was prompted in part because of a ruling in 1985 by then-U. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>. In a case involving alleged terrorist acts by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> ruled that courts could hear such suits having a possible impact on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign relations only through an explicit grant from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The bill deals only with officially condoned acts of torture or extrajudicial killings and does not touch upon acts of torture or killings by private groups.
