<HEAD>30 Percent of Voters Registered on First Day in Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first day of registration for February's national election went smoothly and about 30 percent of eligible voters signed up, a ranking international observer reported Monday. Spokesmen for an opposition coalition, however, accused the Sandinista government's electoral authorities of foot-dragging and said about half its own representatives were not given credentials to observe the registration. <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soraes </PERSON>, secretary-general of the Organization of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, described the complaints as `` administrative'' and said his organization's 52 observers throughout the country reported about 570,000 of an estimated 1.9 million eligible voters registered on Sunday, the first day. `` There was some -LRB- opposition -RRB- discussion of administrative aspects, for example the delay in accrediting representatives and the payment of the per diem, but ... everything proceeded normally,'' he told reporters Monday. `` I did not verify any obstacle or any complaint that could compromise the process.'' <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> visited 35 registration centers Sunday in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Leon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Granada </PERSON> and in two villages. Voters are permitted to register at 4,394 centers on the first four Sundays of October. General elections to be held Feb. 25 are for a president and vice president, mayors and a 90-member National Assembly. Publisher <PERSON> Violeta </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrios </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> coalition is challenging President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, who seeks another term as candidate of the ruling leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> party. Eight other parties are contesting the presidential election. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> called early elections as part of regional accords with the presidents of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> calling for demobilization of the Contras, U.S.-supported rebels fighting the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, spokesman for the opposition alliance, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> registration was slow and about half the opposition's representatives were not given credentials in time to help supervising the process. He said the alliance would file a formal complaint with the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. Of seven Managua-area registration centers the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> visited Sunday, the coalition was represented at only two. Other opposition parties had observers at two of the remaining five and there were no opposition observers at three. Observers from the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> were present at all seven centers. An official said a registration center in <LOCATION> Chontales </LOCATION> province was moved `` to a safer place'' five miles away because of armed men in the area, presumably rebels. <PERSON> Ofiel </PERSON> <PERSON> Acuna </PERSON>, president of the regional election council, said the center was in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guarumo </LOCATION>, 100 miles east of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. There were no reports of Contra military activity on Sunday. Most of the rebels are in jungle camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, but a few Contra groups remain in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, including Chontales. A joint commission of the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> is charged with supervising the demobilization and re-integration of the Contras into civilian life. <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> said the necessary elements for fair elections appear to be present. `` Generally, I believe that on Feb. 25 there will be free and honest elections,'' he said. Thirty <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observers watched the registration Sunday but did not comment.
