<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-YonkersDeseg     10-02 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Yonkers Deseg,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices Hear Case of Defiant Yonkers Councilmen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Supreme Court Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge acted within his powers by fining four <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, city councilmen for disobeying his desegregation order, a lawyer for the federal government told the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday. But an attorney for the councilmen argued that the judge could have changed the city zoning ordinance, but chose instead to violate the councilmen's common-law right of legislative immunity, as well as their constitutionally protected freedom of speech. The case, argued before the high court Monday, is an outgrowth of the bitter, nine-year battle to desegregate <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>. The justices are expected to rule by July. The case centers around four city councilmen _ <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Longo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chema </PERSON> and Vice Mayor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON> _ who voted against a judge's order to pass a legislative package designed to lure subsidized housing to the city's white neighborhoods. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON>, the federal government's solicitor general, praised <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sand </PERSON> for not employing more stringent tactics to compel the councilmen to obey his July 26, 1988, order. In 1985, Sand found <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> that had for 40 years deliberately concentrated virtually all its subsidized housing in the southwest part of the city to keep blacks away from whites. Sand ordered the city to build 200 units of public housing in white neighborhoods in 1988 and to plan for 600 more. The city appealed, lost and seemed close to agreeing on a desegregation plan until <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> residents raised loud objections. The council defied Sand's order by voting 4-3 against the desegregation plan. Sand then set fines of $ 500 a day and threatened to jail the four unless they obeyed his order. `` They simply chose not to obey, and furthermore, they said, ` We do n't have to obey,''' <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> told the justices. Sand had also set fines for the city _ starting at $ 100 a day and doubling daily until they reached $ 1 million daily _ prompting Councilmen <PERSON> Chema </PERSON> and <PERSON> Longo </PERSON> to change their votes as <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> faced imminent bankruptcy. The councilmen ultimately paid $ 3,500 apiece in fines; none went to jail. <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> paid a total of $ 819,000 in fines, which were upheld by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the attorney representing the councilmen, argued Monday that the district court used `` the most intrusive means'' available to compel the four to change their votes, violating their legislative immunity. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> also argued that to vote is to exercise one's freedom of speech, which is protected by the First Amendment. `` Is this like the court ordering somebody to say something they do n't want to say?'' Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> at one point. `` Courts are always doing that.'' White gave the example of courts ordering employers to post notices they'd rather quash, and suggested <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> could make his argument without invoking the Constitution. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> also argued that there are limits to judicial authority, and that the councilmen were compelled to vote their consciences. This prompted Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> to ask whether the councilmen had the right to force the city into bankruptcy. `` Yes, and to be held accountable for that at the ballot box,'' <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> said. The cases are <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-854; <PERSON> Chema </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-856; and <PERSON> Longo </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-870.
