<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Perkins     10-02 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Perkins,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Agrees To Consider Use Of Undercover Agents To Gain Confessions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday agreed to consider allowing the use of police undercover agents to elicit confessions from jailed criminal suspects. The justices announced they will use the the case of an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> murder suspect to consider weakening its famous 1966 Miranda ruling that requires police to warn suspects of their right to an attorney and to remain silent. An <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> appeals court ruled last November that police violated the rights of <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> when they planted an undercover agent in jail to question him about a murder. <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> was charged with fatally shooting <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephenson </PERSON> on Nov. 8, 1984, in <LOCATION> Fairview </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>. Police lacked a suspect in the murder in 1986 when <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Charlton </PERSON>, an inmate at <ORGANIZATION> Graham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facility </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hillsboro </LOCATION>, told authorities he had information about the homicide. Police then placed <PERSON> Charlton </PERSON> and undercover narcotics officer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jail </LOCATION> on March 31, 1986. <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> was being held there awaiting trial on a charge of aggravated battery unrelated to the murder. <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON>, using the alias <PERSON> Vito </PERSON> <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON>, wore motorcycle garb and told <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> he was interested in planning an escape. <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Charlton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> arranged to meet in the cellbock after the other inmates went to sleep. At that meeting <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> whether he had ever `` done someone,'' a phrase the appeals court said was intended to elicit information about any killings in which <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> took part. The appeals court said <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> then recounted in detail the killing of <PERSON> Stephenson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> then was taken to the county courthouse, placed under arrest for murder and given his Miranda warnings. A state judge in 1987 ruled that <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>' jailhouse statements to <PERSON> Charlton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON> about the <PERSON> Stephenson </PERSON> killing could not be admitted as evidence. State officials, seeking to have the statements admitted, said the Miranda ruling is designed to protect suspects against police coercion. The officials said since <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charlton </PERSON> had engaged in friendly conversation pretending to enlist <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> in a jailbreak, there could be no coercion. But the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> appeals court said the Miranda ruling applies whenever a suspect is in custody, `` even when the purpose of the custody is unrelated to the purpose of the interrogation.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1980 ruled that law enforcement officials can not hire jailhouse informants to induce criminal defendants in custody to make incriminating statements. The justices in that ruling relied on their own 1964 decision _ handed down two years before <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON> _ that barred government agents from eliciting incriminating information from defendants entitled to a lawyer's help during interrogation. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> officials said the 1980 high court ruling permits <PERSON> Parisi </PERSON>'s questioning of <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> because no murder charges against <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> had been filed. Under such circumstances, the state said, `` there exists no inherent danger that a suspect will believe he has no choice but to submit to -LRB- police -RRB- will and to confess.'' The case is <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>, 88-1972.
