<HEAD>Supreme Court to Review Federal Crime Victims Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> agreed Monday to review a law requiring people convicted of federal crimes to pay money to help crime victims. The court said it will study a ruling that the law is unconstitutional because it is a revenue-raising measure that originated in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rather than the House of Representatives. The Constitution requires that revenue-raising measures start in the House. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is seeking to have the appeals court ruling reversed. The case stems from a $ 50 `` assessment'' against German Munoz-Flores, convicted of helping an illegal alien evade inspection by immigration officials in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Munoz-Flores </PERSON> also was placed on probation for two years The assessment was ordered under a 1984 law aimed at raising money to offset the cost of helping victims of crimes. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last December that the law is a revenue-raising measure that should have originated in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rather than the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The appeals court's ruling is binding in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said the ruling invalidates assessments imposed against thousands of people convicted in those states. The government's appeal said that the 9th Circuit's ruling, if adopted nationwide, would affect tens of thousands of criminal cases each year. Government lawyers argued that the 1984 law is not primarily designed to raise revenue, but rather was part of a package to help crime victims. The lawyers also said the assessments measure is designed in part to punish those convicted of crimes. The appeal said the appeals court was mistaken in describing the measure as originating in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> because it actually originated in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which passed a crime-control bill that included the assessments feature. The law calls for assessments ranging from $ 25 to $ 200 per offense. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. Munoz-Flores, 88-1932.
