<HEAD>Consultants Push Contemporary Art Museum to Bolster Milltown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH ADAMS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Converting an abandoned, 28-building factory into a $ 77.5 million contemporary art museum could revitalize this remote milltown, consultants said Monday. A commission is working on such a museum, but critics question whether art lovers would drive to <PERSON> North </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> _ three hours northwest of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, four hours from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> _ for the stark enticements of contemporary art. Backers of the so-called <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contemporary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> want to use a plant complex abandoned in 1984 by the town's largest employer, <ORGANIZATION> Sprague </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> They want to convert the vast, grimy plant into rooms of unique environmental works or sculptures. Sprague employed more than 1,000 people before relocating to <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. A draft of the consultants' feasibility study projects the museum could employ 640 people in the town of 16,000 people where unemployment is about 4 percent. Consultants hired by the commission project as many as 150,000 people would visit the museum in a year, pumping $ 22 million into the region's economy. `` The sheer reality of marketing this museum will depend in a certain extent to a creative approach,'' said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bidwell </PERSON>, one of the consultants. The idea of turning the complex of 28 buildings into 350,000 square feet of gallery space was devised by <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Krens </PERSON>, former director of the <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Berkshires </LOCATION>. Shortly after launching the project, <PERSON> Krens </PERSON> was named director of the <ORGANIZATION> Guggenheim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Plans for the museum call for an accompanying restaurant and luxury condominiums selling at $ 160,000 to $ 250,000. `` The project will work,'' <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonz </PERSON>, another of the consultants, told the commission Monday during review of the draft study. The commission is looking for $ 35 million from the state, spread over four or five years. The remaining $ 44.5 million would come from private donations. Members of the commission did not take final action on feasibility of the project. They endorsed the draft study and scheduled a presentation to the state Dec. 11.
