<HEAD>British Socialists Abandon Non-Nuclear Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs with delegates supporing PLO and clarification
of block casting of millions of votes; picks up 6th pvs `Under the'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> abandoned its controversial policy of unilateral nuclear disarmament Monday, overturning the vote-losing doctrine at its annual conference. It also approved a motion urging <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to begin a dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and called the Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> a `` just revolt.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> refuses to negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, which it describes as a terrorist group bent on destroying the Jewish state. The motion said that, since <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> seized the territories in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war, `` the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> military occupation has prevented the Palestinians from living under their own chosen form of government and enjoying civil and political rights.'' Delegates reaffirmed previous party positions backing the right of both Palestinians and Israelis to states with internationally recognized borders and calling the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> the only legitimate representative of the Palestinians. It referred to the 21-month-old uprising in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> as `` the just revolt of the Palestinian people calling for an end to the ` iron fist' policy of the Israeli military ... and a withdrawal from the occupied territories.'' After sometimes heated debate, delegates voted for a policy that commits a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government to give up <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s nuclear arsenal only as part of a negotiated arms deal. Dismayed left wingers hung peace symbols from balconies in the conference hall as speakers warned that the socialist movement must change or suffer a fourth successive election defeat by Conservative Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. `` It puts us in a very strong position to argue for an effective and realistic initiative and to get verifiable -LRB- nuclear arms -RRB- agreements,'' party leader <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> said after the vote on the first full day of the weeklong conference. Delegates at the convention in this south <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> resort cast votes totaling 3.6 million to 2.4 million to ditch unilateral nuclear disarmament after leaders of big, moderate trade unions swung behind <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON>. There are 1,500 conference delegates but the votes are counted in the millions because the leaders of trade union that control 90 percent of the voting power cast blocks of tens of thousands of votes based on the memberships of their unions. In a victory for party leftists, the conference voted by a 4-2 margin for a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> government to cut defense expenditures by one-fourth, bringing it in line with the average in other West European members of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. Under the new policy, a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> government would retain <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s submarine-launched Polaris nuclear missiles It would also stick to Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s decision to replace them in the early 1990s with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trident missiles, which are nine times more powerful than Polaris missiles. Legislator <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Benn </PERSON>, a former energy secretary and doyen of the Labor left, accused the party of betraying `` the basis of our whole policy.'' `` <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> does not need nuclear weapons. There is no Soviet nuclear threat. That is the challenge we can not ignore,'' declared <PERSON> Benn </PERSON> to cheers from sections of the conference hall. A succession of speakers cited strides in superpower arms control negotiations since Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> s. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took office, and they said a new Labor policy suited the improved East-West relations. But others argued simply that <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> must change to win. `` We know it is the policy which is at fault, not the presentation,'' said delegate <PERSON> Sylvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Heal </PERSON>. `` The leadership has been accused of betrayal. But the people who will be guilty of betrayal are those who by their actions ensure <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s return for another term.'' Labor adopted its policy on nuclear weapons in 1981 as the party lurched left after losing power to Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> two years previously. Polls show the policy was a major factor in Labor's two subsequent defeats by Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> in 1983 and 1987. She must call the next election by mid-1992. Dropping the non-nuclear doctrine was part of a major new policy platform aimed at shifting the party toward the center. The conference is to vote on the changes, the result of a two-year review, through the week.
