<SECOND>AM-Designs On The Future,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Designs Studied As Competitive Launchpads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLISON J. PUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sony Walkman, the <ORGANIZATION> Dictaphone </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> coffeemaker were successful industrial designs that are the focus of designers gathered to look for an edge on products of the future. Those products succeeded because their companies took their industrial designers seriously, said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Design </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>, which is conducting a four-day symposium with the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. Most business managers say they use engineers or others to create a product, and `` then get the flakes to get the color picked out,'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, one of those `` flakes'' by training, said designers can be the consumer's advocate inside the firm, choosing the right size knobs and switches that can make a product work easily or not. <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which had an electronic saxaphone in the exhibit, used its designers to find a modern shape that would match the new technology of digital wind music. The first design was described by one <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION> worker as a `` snake that ate a lunch box.'' Several versions later, the final product resembles a futuristic rifle. Embellished with the standard finger pads in black, the instrument is a long black tube, bent down at one end for the mouthpiece. The sound that emerges from the instrument can range from synthesized voices to the acoustic timbres of wind instruments. The product dominates the professional wind digital music market, according to <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION>. Designers at AB Bahco Vertyg, the tools division of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bahco </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, helped the company maintain its share in the screwdriver market, while increasing its profit margin by 20 percent, said <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>. The company had discovered in market research that carpenters use a two-handed grip 70 percent of the time, and gave the problem to its designers. The new screwdriver, which was presented at the exhibit, is shaped like the numeral 8, with textured polypropylene where the handle widens. At <LOCATION> Braun </LOCATION>, business managers faced the problem of an extremely low share of the coffeemaker market. The KF20 model, introduced in 1972, had won awards for its simple, cylindrical design, but it was too expensive. `` Artists and designers would collect our things to add to their collections, but we were not succesful,'' said <PERSON> Dieter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rems </PERSON>, the company's chief designer, who spoke at the symposium Monday. The solution, which included cheaper materials and fewer parts, may not seem that innovative at first glance. But Rems said the new design, marketed as the KF40, used one heater for both coffee and water instead of two, which cut the price dramatically. More than 2.5 million units of the new design sold in 1988, giving <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> a 12 percent market share. The company makes 12,000 units a day. Rems said having the designers talk to the manufacturers was a crucial element in the <PERSON> Braun </PERSON> story, because the design could be adapted to cut production costs. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said he thinks if American businesses adopted more of these tactics, the competitiveness of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products would improve vastly. Designers are still supposed to pick the right color, though. Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> wanted its new educational toy, a headset computer, to appeal to both boys and girls. But the company's research showed that boys liked black headsets and girls liked lavender, and each sex hated the other's top choice. The result is a grand compromise: a slate-gray headset with cushioning foam done in purple, yellow, blue, green and magenta.
</TEXT>
