<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX6</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Violinist <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON>, whose skills won him international acclaim, was placed on probation Monday after being indicted on cocaine and heroin charges. `` Of course I'm relieved that this ordeal is over,'' <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON> said. `` The experience has been a frightening and profound one. What I want to do now is get back to my music and my life.'' <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON>, 39, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, pleaded guilty to breaking into a <PERSON> Martha </PERSON>'s Vineyard motel room where he was discovered July 27. A search of the room found a bottle containing more than 20 grams of cocaine, a hypodermic needle with a small amount of heroin and a dagger. A Dukes County Grand Jury on Monday morning returned indictments of breaking and entering, possession of heroin and cocaine and possession of instruments used to administer drugs. After lawyers on both sides conferred, <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON> pleaded guilty to the breaking and entering charge, which carried a maximum penalty of six months in jail. Judge <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON> to three years probation, during which he must continue a drug treatment program and submit to random drug testing. <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON> pleaded innocent to the other charges, and they were placed on file, pending his completion of probation. `` This should n't have been treated as a serious criminal matter and it was n't,'' defense attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON> has been to a treatment center and has turned his life around.'' Born in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON> began playing violin at age 8. He has performed at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, where in 1974 he became the first American medalist at the Tchaikovsky Violin Competition. After <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON>'s arrest, family members and colleagues said his drug use had begun recently, after he had trouble building on his early celebrity. `` This was a very important experience actually in his life,'' <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> said. `` He was feeling down in the dumps and he turned toward drugs.'' <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Fodor </PERSON> has undergone seven weeks of treatment, and couselors say his progress has been good and they are confident he can remain drug free.
