<HEAD>Justice Stevens Removes Himself from Illinois Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> will not take part in a key <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case over abortion rights to be decided during the 1989-90 term, a court spokeswoman said Monday. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> had not disqualified himself when the justices agreed last July 3 to review the case, one of three abortion disputes before the high court this term. But a minor court order issued in the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case Monday noted that <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> did not participate. Asked about that, court spokeswoman <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON> said the justice had disqualified himself from the case for unstated reasons. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> was one of four dissenters from the court's decision last July letting states make abortions harder to get. He has provided a consistent vote in support of the 1973 court decision that women have a constitutional right to abortion. The <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case focuses on a state law that would require abortion clinics to add services and equipment now found only in hospitals. The law could force many clinics to close down, and could add up to $ 50 to the cost of an abortion performed in the first three months of pregnancy. In invalidating the law, lower courts said it violated a portion of the 1973 ruling in <LOCATION> Roe </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> that limited state regulation over first-trimester abortions. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> officials are not asking the justices to use the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case to reverse <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, but legal experts say the court's ruling could chip away at the trimester-by-trimester approach taken in the 1973 decision. The two other abortion cases under high court study this term focus on parental notification requirements for unwed minors seeking to end their pregnancies in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> has not disqualified himself from those cases. The <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case is Turnock vs. <PERSON> Ragsdale </PERSON>, 88-790.
