<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> testified Monday at his fraud trial that he and his wife, <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON>, accepted $ 3.1 million in bonuses while the ministry's finances foundered. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> board members granted the bonuses `` of their own free will'' and often told him, `` I was worth much more than this, and they would say that over and over again.'' <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> left the witness stand Monday, completing 10 hours of testimony that began Friday. Both sides rested their cases Monday, with closing arguments scheduled for Tuesday. The case could go to the jury as early as Wednesday. The disgraced television evangelist testified that he raised more than $ 425 million for <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> from 1984 to 1987, when he and his wife received $ 3.1 million in bonuses. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> was asked by his lawyer, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, what he did with the $ 425 million. `` I put it to the work of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>,'' he said. During defense questioning, <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> summed up his defense: `` We were a church, and people always wanted to run it like a business. I had to keep telling them, this was a church, not a business.'' As <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> left court during a break, he was smiling, saying, `` I feel fine.'' He turned to <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and said, `` This is a nice place to visit but I did n't plan to live here.'' In other testimony, M.C. <PERSON> Benton </PERSON>, the trustee overseeing the ministry's property since it filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from creditors, testified <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> was $ 50 million in debt and had $ 160 million in claims against it from `` lifetime partners'' when <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> resigned in March 1987. <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>, 49, is charged with 15 c