<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Calls For `New Deal' Worldwide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet foreign minister called Monday for an international `` New Deal'' to avert an impending economic disaster fueled by militarization, Third World debt, poverty and environmental problems. `` Right before our eyes the world is sliding into a deep economic depression,'' <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said in a speech in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` The debt of the Third World countries, the interest they have to pay and the pace of their economic development _ are these not the signs of an impending catastrophe?'' He added: `` We could one day begin competing not for political supremacy or spheres of influence but for access to water, fresh air and even a green lawn.'' <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> told the audience of about 350 people that the abolition of nuclear weapons, forgiveness of some Third World debts and increased protection for the environment will be essential for peace and worldwide stability in the next century. `` Radical bold steps are needed, a kind of ` New Deal,' a transition to a policy that would draw developing countries into the scientific, technological and information revolution,'' he said. In the 1930s during the Great Depression, President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> promised Americans a `` New Deal'' of government-sponsored social welfare programs. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> compared pessimism over the future of perestroika, the economic liberalization of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, to pessimism over the future of capitalism during the 1930s in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He noted that in 1931, 100,000 Americans requested permission to emigrate to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` There were bread lines in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Times Square and tents of the jobless huddled along <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Drive </LOCATION>,'' he said, adding: `` It is well known that in those years there were widespread expectations in left-wing circles that the severe crisis of the world capitalist system would finally bring about the world revolution.'' He said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s `` economic system is undergoing an adjustment. ... Something similar happened in the Unites States 60 years ago.'' But he predicted that `` so long as there is the will, the understanding of the situation and the determination to change things for the better _ and we certainly have them _ the economy can remedy its ills.''
