<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Monday overwhelmingly approved President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s compromise plan to extend steel import restrictions on 29 foreign trading partners until April 1992. The vote was 354-10. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan, announced July 25, called for immediate negotiations with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and other leading steel-exporting nations to extend annual limitations on the volume of steel allowed to be shipped to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The original pacts, which expired Saturday, were negotiated by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in 1984 to give domestic steelmakers breathing space from subsidized, foreign competition. Many steel-district lawmakers had pushed the administration this summer to extend the curbs for five years. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> opted for a smaller-scale, 2 -LCB- - year program in deference to steel-using manufacturers who argued that the quotas have driven up steel prices and caused supply shortages of some steel products The compromise all but eliminated debate on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. Opposition came largely from free-traders who felt the steel industry has had enough protection. `` It's not my first choice,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Minn </LOCATION>., who had opposed the industry's requests for a longer extension `` Nevertheless, I have to admit it's about as good a compromise as could be achieved.'' Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaydos </PERSON>, D-Pa., who represents a western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> steel district, said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> program `` is not a cure-all, but has been the most effective method of dealing with dumped imports `` This legislation is basically and fundamentally giving the steel industry in this country a little more time to become competitive. And they're well underway,'' <PERSON> Gaydos </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., has introduced a companion measure in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, but no action on it has yet been taken With the old steel program due to expire Sept. 30, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration could not afford to wait until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acted to begin the painstaking process of negotiating new import ceilings. Trade representatives from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> were all in town last week for meetings on renewing their pacts. Many of the negotiations are already complete, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON>. Even though <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has not yet finished work on the bill, she said steel imports would continued to be monitored by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. No details on individual pacts have yet been announced.
