<HEAD>Karpov Draws with Yusupov in Battle To Challenge World Chess Champion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with chess results, Kasparov earns
record rating. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former world champion <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> drew with fellow Soviet <PERSON> Artur </PERSON> <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON> in their first game Monday in a battle among four top chess grandmasters to decide the challenger to reigning champion <PERSON> Garri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and British grandmaster <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> adjourned on the 60th move in the other game in the World Championship Candidates' semifinal at <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON>'s Wells ballet theater in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> was a pawn ahead in an endgame but most experts predicted a draw when play resumes. <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>, in the 13th annual <ORGANIZATION> Interpolis </ORGANIZATION> chess tournament in <LOCATION> Tilburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>, on Monday earned the highest rating record in the history of the game, shattering <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> player <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>'s 1972 record. The Soviet champion, by defeating <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Simen </PERSON> <PERSON> Agdestein </PERSON> in the final round, won 12 points out of 14 matches, the best tournament record ever. A win scores one point, and a draw half a point. This entitled 26-year-old <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> to a total of 2,795 points on the international ranking list of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, known by the French initials FIDE. <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>'s 1972 record was 2,785 points. Although the next rating list will not be officially published before Jan. 1, <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>, who plans no further tournament appearances this year, seems certain of his record. The second round in the semifinals in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> will be played Tuesday. The two winners of the semifinals contest will meet in the Candidates' final scheduled for March in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The winner will challenge <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> for his world title in a 24-game contest in October 1990. Playing with the disadvantage of the black pieces, <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> quickly neutralized <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON>'s opening advantage and exchanged both pairs of rooks to reach an endgame where neither side could make meaningful progress. After further exchanges, <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON> forced a draw on the 44th move. <PERSON> Timman </PERSON>, playing white, gained an early opening initiative. <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> mistakes on the 17th and 21st moves let <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> reach an endgame with an extra pawn and superior placed pieces. `` It's just one of those days when you miss everything,'' said British grandmaster <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Short </PERSON>, the third ranked player in the world, of <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON>'s early play. But having gained a winning position, <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> failed to find several promising continuations and <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> put up the toughest of defenses. In the adjourned position, each side has a rook. <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> has three pawns and <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> two. `` It looks like a draw now,'' said <PERSON> Short </PERSON> after <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> sealed his 61st move. `` <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> missed a lot of chances.'' <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>, 38, is heavily favored to knock out the 29-year-old <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON>. The outcome of the Timman-Speelman contest remains, in the words of British Grandmaster <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, `` completely unclear.'' <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>, ranked second in the world, held the world title for 10 years before losing to <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> in November 1985. <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> is famous for his so-called creeping style which analysts say squeezes the play out of his opponent's position like a boa constrictor squeezes the life from its prey. He has never lost to <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON>, the world's 14th ranked player, rose to prominence in 1977 when he won the world under-20 championship at age 17. He will be hoping for a repeat of <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>'s astonishing collapse at a June tournament in <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. Over a dramatic final three rounds, <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> lost every game for the first time in his long career. The winner of that tournament was <PERSON> Timman </PERSON>, a 37-year-old who is ranked eighth in the world. By virtue of his formidable performances, <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> was for many years the top Western grandmaster and in 1987 a magnificent run of victories put him within striking distance of <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON>, who celebrated his 33rd birthday Monday, is ranked 13th in the world. He has a solid and tricky playing style, punctuated with flashes of brilliance. <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON>, in the six-game quarter final, defeated Short by 3.5-1 .5 <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> said of the semifinals in his column in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s newspaper The Sunday Correspondent: `` Before <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>'s collapse at the end of <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION> I would have rated him the overwhelming favorite against <PERSON> Artur </PERSON> <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON> Now I put him at about 70-30. I rate <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> favorite by about 55-45, but will strive mightily to upset these odds.'' The winner of each contest will receive $ 77,000, the loser $ 46,000. If the matches are tied 4-4 after eight games, two more games will be played. If it is still tied, the rules call for sudden death games. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> has scheduled the 1990 title final for <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, starting Oct. 7.
