<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Newfoundland'sWhales Adv15-2Takes   10-02 1029</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Newfoundland's Whales, Adv 15-2 Takes,1054</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w photos,
1 graphic. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Slowly, the largest animals ever to roam the planet are returning to the craggy coves and lofty fiords of <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, beckoning the curious from across <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, as well as scientists who want to study them. While the seasonal arrivals of the whales are met with some trepidation by fishermen, Newfoundlanders are learning that a live whale can be just as valuable as a dead one.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRINITY, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spring comes late and winter comes early to these climes, governing the coming and going of exotic seabirds, moose, caribou and seals. But the creatures that linger most on the mind are the whales. In fact, a group of scientists will gather in <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> in February under the auspices of <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> to tally the number of humpback whales left in the world by comparing thousands of photographs taken over the years of humpback tails, which have telltale fluke patterns. Situated off the food-rich Grand Banks, where codfish is king, the seas around <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> provide enough food, deep water and isolation to satisfy the pickiest leviathan. `` This is the biggest restaurant in the world's oceans. It's got a varied menu, everything you want and all you want, and it's cheap,'' says whale researcher <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON>, who conducts whale-watching expeditions out of Trinity The waters off <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> have the highest concentration of whales in the world, says <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON>, who holds a doctorate in marine bioacoustics from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> and a master's degree from <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> Up to 25 species of cetaceans _ whales, dolphins and porpoises _ migrate every summer to the northwest <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> to feed. `` If a place like <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> is a fish-and-chips joint that seats 25 people, then this is the entire city of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, which seats 5 million people all eating gourmet, 15-course meals,'' <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON> says. But the waters around <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> have not always been hospitable to whales, whose numbers have been decimated by 500 years of relentless pursuit and slaughter by whalers from several continents. Since the time of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, the coastlines of <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Labrador </LOCATION> were littered with makeshift whale factories, which were moved from one site to another after whales in an area were depleted. Whales were deemed expendable. The rendering of their blubber provided light for the streets of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and food for <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Observations of their habits were limited to those who hunted them, almost to extinction. Since the turn of the century, more than 2 million whales have been reported killed for food, oil, cosmetics and other products. But after the 1960s, the decade of increasing environmental awareness, and the 1970s, the decade of discovery about the intelligence and gentleness of whales, the 1980s have been a decade in which most nations banned whaling _ at least temporarily. While tourists spend thousands of dollars to travel here to view whales, the fishermen who spend the most time in the company of the gentle giants view them more like city pigeons than a national treasure. `` My stepfather is a fisherman and I ca n't go home and speak of what a great day I had,'' says <PERSON> Collette </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>, 21, of <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rexton </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON>'s assistant on the whale-watching expeditions. `` To him, the whales are a nuisance. They get in their traps and cost them a lot of money.'' Whales often wreak havoc with expensive fishing nets, and toothed whales compete for the capelin, squid and cod that contribute to <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>'s $ 700 million fishing industry. `` For fishermen, whales are marine rats. It's a pest, an endangered pest, because it really does cost them money,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lien </PERSON>, professor of ocean studies at <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The provincial government and whale researchers such as <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lien </PERSON> have been working diligently over the past decade to create goodwill between whales and the fishermen. Educational programs about whales have been presented in just about every village and outport _ tiny settlements reachable only by boat. And when a whale gets trapped in a net, a toll-free hot line can put a fisherman in contact with a rescue team that will try to free the animal and save the net. `` In <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> as a whole, attitudes have changed,'' says <PERSON> Lien </PERSON>. `` We've printed a half million whale posters, and I claim they have replaced <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> catalogs in the outhouses. Now 90 percent of the fishermen can identify a humpback, for instance. Before, it was a very low figure.'' Before hot lines and whale rescues, one in two whales trapped in fishing nets would die, <PERSON> Lien </PERSON> says. This year, only three of 65 humpbacks that blundered into nets died. `` When I first came here, live whales cost <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> fishermen over $ 1 million a year from lost or damaged nets and all,'' <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON> says. `` And now tourism probably brings in $ 1 million a year to the island. `` What I did and what I'm proud of is that I came to <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> hoping to make live whales more valuable to Newfoundlanders than dead whales. And we did that.'' A new generation of Newfoundlanders also is emerging, one much more atuned to the special creatures in their midst. `` We surveyed 7,000 kids in <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> and found that seal pups and whales were their favorite animals. They were right up there with puppies and kittens,'' says <PERSON> Lien </PERSON>. `` That's probably the most important thing an animal can do for its survival _ get humans attached to it.'' There are two kinds of whales, toothed whales like the dolphin, sperm and killer whales, and baleen whales like the blue, humpback and right whales, which feed on krill, tiny shrimp-like plankton, gulped by the thousands while the water is expelled through a mesh of whalebone called baleen. Some whales, like the rare blue whale, the largest animal ever to have lived, can be seen in winter feeding near the edge of ice floes along the island's undulating, 5,500-mile-long coastline.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1438EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Newfoundland'sWhales Adv15-1stAdd   10-02 1035</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Newfoundland's Whales, Adv 15-1st Add,1058</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRINITY, Newfoundland: 5,500-mile-long coastline.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 But most of <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>'s whales, notably humpbacks, minkes and fins, breed and calve in warm southern waters during the winter and migrate north in summer to feed on the millions of tiny smelt-like capelin that spawn on <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> beaches. `` North to feed, south to breed,'' says <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON>. With little exaggeration, that's just about all that's known about these warm-blooded, air-breathing mammals. What they do at night, how deep they dive, where they go in the winter, how they communicate, how some species feed, why certain whales beach themselves, how long they live, how often they give birth, even whether some species still exist, are all mysteries. `` Whales are really mysterious animals because they seem to disappear. They'll go down and you do n't see them ever again,'' says <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON>, who spent 10 years at the <ORGANIZATION> Bedford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanography </ORGANIZATION>. `` We know a fraction about whales of what we do about other animals on Earth because we ca n't study them at nighttime, we ca n't study them when they're below the surface, we ca n't study them in captivity and we ca n't study them in the winter very well. Nevertheless centuries of hunting whales have yielded some of their secrets. The sperm whale for instance feeds mostly on squid, preferably the giant squid and octopus. That requires that it dive to great depths, although like all whales it is an air breather. One sperm whale, a relative youngster at 45 feet long, was found at a depth of 3,240 feet by the cable repair ship All <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in 1932. It drowned apparently in mortal combat with the cable it encountered while hunting squid. Almost 200 feet of cable was twisted around its jaws and body. While most whales have a gentle reputation, the killer whales are the most formidable. Thirty feet long and capable of swimming at about 30 mph, they are unmatched in lethal potential. They are voracious, some caught with the remains of more than 20 porpoises and seals in their bellies. But no whale challenges the imagination as much as the great blue, protected now but once hunted almost to extinction. Some 100 feet long and 150 tons, it is the largest creature on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, and may have begun its evolutional history on dry land. There are vestigial hipbones in the rear third of its body indicating that it may have prowled the primordial land. It was a boon to the whalers. One blue whale could yield 45 tons of meat and 40 tons of blubber. Its skeleton alone weighed 27 tons and its internal organs 18 more. <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON>, who moved to <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION> 10 years ago to study whales more closely, says he sometimes gets frustrated at the very thing that makes them so mysterious _ their elusiveness. `` Sometimes I feel like switching to an easier animal,'' he says wryly. `` I do this as well as anybody in the world, so I'm on the edge of knowledge. But you'd like to work on an animal you can work with more than just a few hours a day.'' Nevertheless, there is something about whales that makes them special in the marine kingdom and attractive to scientists. `` They are highly intelligent, and their brains are extremely unusual and as complex as ours,'' says <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Whale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` Not only that, they arrived at their brain size at least 2 million years before we attained ours.'' `` They are at the top of the evolutionary ladder among ocean animals and man is at the top among land animals,'' <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON> says. `` So even though you get less data, the data might be more meaningful.'' The body of knowledge about whales, for the most part, is a recent acquistion _ begun only in the latter half of this century. The reason may be found in a little clapboard museum in historic Trinity dedicated to the town's fishing and whaling past. Curator <PERSON> Calvert </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsworthy </PERSON>, a former fish-plant worker, fingers the long, sinewy fibers of a humpback's baleen. Looking out the window at <LOCATION> Trinity </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, a favorite haunt of whales, the slight man of 63 years remembers when fish plants smelling of salt cod covered the rocky coast and recalls stories of the carcasses of dead whales hauled ashore for rendering a century before. In many parts of the globe, the animals are still scarce. Some species, like the bowhead and right whale -LRB- so called by the whalers because it would float when killed, therefore `` right'' -RRB- are highly endangered, while others, like <PERSON> Longman </PERSON>'s beaked and the melon-headed whale, have not been seen for decades. Slowly, the largest animals ever to roam the planet have returned to the craggy coves and lofty fiords of this verdant island. And their arrival in the spring is met with both eagerness and trepidation by the local inhabitants. `` It means spring is here, just like when my animals have young, when the first lamb is born,'' says <PERSON> Goldsworthy </PERSON>. `` The first whale is like the first robin. The ponds start to melt and you take your rod and go out for a meal of trout.'' `` You get this burst of energy,'' says <PERSON> Collette </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>. `` Research does n't go so well on the first day because I ca n't sit down. I still feel like that every morning with our first humpback sighting.'' Sitting at a table in the small restaurant of <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Village </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inn </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> relaxes before the start of another day of note-taking on rough seas. After several days of rain and fog _ an obvious deterrent to whale watching _ the clouds part and the sun warms the small, clapboard houses built haphazardly along the steep slopes. `` You ca n't describe the feeling that goes over you when you see a whale for the first time or a humpback breach,'' <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> says, her face beaming. `` It does n't matter who you are, where you're from I do n't see how you ca n't feel that way, such a big animal, so friendly. It's like they have this need to communicate. `` They want to and are trying, it's just that no one understands them.''
</TEXT>
