<FIRST>s a BC-APN--WhaleWatchers Adv15   10-02 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Whale Watchers, Adv 15,0840</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Newfoundland's Whales    </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRINITY, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Like a roller coaster stuck on go, the 60-mph Zodiac raft assaults mile after mile of 12-foot swells, startling puffins into diving for safety, as tourists pursue an elusive minke whale. `` Blow, 2 o'clock,'' yells a passenger, pointing into a sun-washed horizon as the curved, black back of the minke appears for a split-second breath of air. Minutes elapse before the whale watchers, all peering intently into the vast expanse of ocean, spy the sickle-shaped dorsal fin that appears as a minke spouts. `` Blow, 6 o'clock,'' yell two people at once as the <ORGANIZATION> Zodiac </ORGANIZATION> makes a quick left turn and veers out toward open sea. After two days of rain and fog, the participants in a three-day whale-watch expedition in <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> are eager to see what they paid thousands of dollars and traveled thousands of miles to see. Their patience is rewarded this sunny day in late summer. Several minkes make appearances in coves at the base of high, rocky cliffs, and the group of seven whale watchers establish brief contact with a solitary humpback, an endangered whale known for its melodious songs. `` I felt totally overwhelmed by it all,'' says <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, 35, an English native teaching in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. `` You really felt as if the humpback was there with us. She came and rolled right beside the boat as if to say, ` Look, are n't I lovely?''' `` I think we were relieved, actually, that we had seen what we came here to see,'' says <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, 33, a stage technician for the Royal Shakespeare Theater in <LOCATION> Stratford </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Avon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Whale enthusiasts gravitate to this remote Canandian province at the easternmost edge of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> because of the abundance and variety of whales that migrate here every summer. What they find is sometimes more than they expected _ seals, bald eagles, Arctic seabirds, and, inland, caribou, bear and moose. What they get in programs like those run by whale researcher <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON> in the historic village of <LOCATION> Trinity </LOCATION> is a chance to participate in experiments in human-whale communication. `` Most people's expectations are just to see a whale, and as soon as they walk in the door we tell them that we do a lot more than that. We try to get them involved in a communication experience, which is a lot more valuable,'' says <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON>, who has operated his Ocean Contact program for 10 years. <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON> conducts three - and seven-day expeditions costing up to $ 1,000 Air fare is not included. Participants are fed and housed at an old inn in <LOCATION> Trinity </LOCATION>, where evenings consist of whale-related slide shows, movies and discussions. Days are spent at sea looking for and, hopefully, `` talking'' to whales. The talking actually consists of electronic beeps sent through the water several times at certain intervals. A `` conversation'' develops when a whale responds, either by spouting, breaching, slapping his tail or lifting his head above water. Participants help work the equipment and scan the horizon for the whale's response In his `` Whale Watcher's Handbook,'' author <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyt </PERSON> says, `` Sooner or later, the serious whale watcher finds himself in <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>.'' But serious whale watchers also are finding there's more to this ruggedly beautiful island than just whales. `` People come here to see whales. That's one of the things on the list, but it's not the only thing,'' says <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, chief of visitor activities at Terra Nova National Park near <LOCATION> Trinity </LOCATION>. `` They are also interested in seeing icebergs and the wide-open spaces.'' `` <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> is kind of like the last outpost,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Terra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nova </ORGANIZATION> superintendent <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Fulton </PERSON>. `` The frontier ethic that existed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is still here. You still go out and cut your wood, get your moose or caribou and your fish.'' <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, 40, an Englishman teaching in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, said the whales and the promise of pristine country are what attracted him to <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Beamish </PERSON>'s program. `` When I asked the travel agent if she could get me a flight to <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, she said: ` Nobody ever goes there. Why do you want to go there for?' I said, ` Great, then that's where I want to be.''' <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> woodworker <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Zadoretzky </PERSON>, 39, says she felt renewed by such close contact with animals that, to her, symbolize `` the things we are not'' in a land that is `` an idealization of what I think of as peaceful, beautiful country.'' `` Whales are superior beings who live in the ocean, and we are supposedly the superior beings on land. They are a great force who live peaceably under the sea, but we are a destructive force, and we are beginning to realize that it might cost us. `` They're our salvation. If we can save them, we are starting to save ourselves.''
</TEXT>
