<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ShipyardDown Adv15-1stAdd   10-02 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Shipyard Down, Adv 15-1st Add,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHESTER, Pa.: them over.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Nationwide, <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> said, shipbuilding is in trouble. `` There's no business,'' he said. `` The only new construction in this country for the past couple of years has been for the government.'' Why? `` Aging facilities, and other countries' yards are subsidized,'' he said. `` It's impossible to compete in the world market the way we're having to compete.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> maritime administration once subsidized the construction of new vessels, but those subsidies have been terminated, <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> agreed in part. `` For purposes of discussion, it's fairly accurate,'' he said. `` You can just watch the downward trend.'' In 1982, the council counted 110 shipbuilding companies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, employing 112,000 workers. This year it's down to 69 companies employing 72,000. `` We lost 41 shipyards and 41,000 people,'' <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> said. Shipbuilding in the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> area has been devastated in recent years, <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> said. Other areas that were hit hard were south <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> area. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration terminated shipbuilding subsidies, <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> said, arguing that the government should n't be interfering in the private sector, propping up the industry. `` But that was looking at the world through naive and myopic lenses,'' he said. `` It does n't recognize that if we are not subsidized and the rest of the world is, we are doomed.'' What saved American shipbuilding through the'80s, <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> said, was rebuilding the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. With that almost complete, American shipyards face tough times again. Rather than asking the government to return to subsidies, the council wants the major shipbuilding nations _ <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> _ to drop government intervention in the business. The council filed a complaint in June with the Office of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Trade Representative against the four. It agreed to withhold the petition while the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> tried to negotiate an agreement on shipbuilding subsidies. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> agreed to seek agreements with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading partners both through the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> and through the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round negotiations of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. `` I have received assurances from representatives of all these countries that they will negotiate seriously on this matter,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> set a deadline of March 31, 1990, which <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> called `` fairly aggressive.'' `` But we ca n't really allow the process to drag on,'' <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> said. `` A number of our companies are potentially in trouble.'' <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> agreed it will not be easy to persuade other governments to stop subsidizing shipbuilding. `` It depends on how you define a subsidy,'' he said. `` They tend to think of a subsidy as a direct payment from the government to a business. But when they make export credit available to a shipyard, they do n't think they're subsidizing it.'' <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> is pessimistic. `` Those countries have decided they want to maintain a shipbuilding industry,'' he said. `` In this country, we've apparently made the decision not to have one. <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> is more optimistic. The nation still has areas where employment is high in ship construction and repair _ the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> and the area around <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roads </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. Other big yards are in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade negotiators have started talks with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Stoker </PERSON> said the major talks are expected in mid-October. `` We are hoping the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiating position can be hammered out later this month,'' he said. `` We frankly think some attitudes about the shipbuilding industry in the nation have changed.''
</TEXT>
