<FIRST>s a BC-APN--LastShipyard Adv15   10-02 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Last Shipyard, Adv 15,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Shipyard Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHESTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The last working commercial shipyard in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> was started by an oil executive making sure his company had enough tankers. It went out of business trying to finish a pair of military fuel ships. <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> incorporated <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Drydock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in 1916, a year after company President <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Pew </PERSON> had taken a business trip to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and been impressed with that country's naval strength. Sun Ship's first vessel, the SS <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Sun </PERSON>, slid down the ways in October 1917. By the end of World War I the yard had built six tankers plus three minesweepers for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. Over the years <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> <PERSON> Ship </PERSON> emerged as one of the nation's largest privately owned shipyards. Its Sun Doxford diesel engine eventually made it the biggest American manufacturer of large marine diesel. It also launched the first all-welded tanker, the SS White Flash, in 1931. But its glory years were during World War II, when an average of a ship a week rolled down its 28 ways. On one day, the yard launched three ships. By the end of the war, Sun Ship had produced more than 250 ships _ 40 percent of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tankers built. It converted, armed and repaired 1,000 more. The yard employed 33,500 people. But the end of the war brought a sharp decline in ship construction. The other yards on the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> began closing and by 1975 only Sun Ship was left. By the end of 1980, the parent <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> estimated it had lost more than $ 200 million keeping the shipyard alive. Sun announced it was getting out of the shipbuilding business in January 1981. A company official estimated the shipyard would be sold for $ 30 million to $ 40 million. In February 1982 the yard and its assets were sold for a reported $ 8 million to <ORGANIZATION> Levingston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> company that renamed the yard <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Shipbuilding. <PERSON> Levingston </PERSON> sold control two years later to three real estate developers from Mobile, <LOCATION> Ala </LOCATION>. But shipbuilding has n't been very successful for Penn Ship. In May 1985, when the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> awarded the contract for two 677 -LCB- - foot fleet oilers, it was hailed as a deal that would keep the yard alive Later, <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Ship </PERSON> would argue that it had to submit an unreasonably low bid to get the contract and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> renegotiated the deal to $ 331.4 million. In February, <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ship </ORGANIZATION> said that was n't enough either, and it suspended work with an eye to hiring another yard to finish the job Finally the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> decided to find a new contractor itself. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON>, the yard's general manager, said <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ship </ORGANIZATION> made its bid when labor was plentiful and rates were low but soon had trouble finding qualified employees in a booming economy. How could a shipyard that built tankers for years lose a contract to build a couple of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> fuel vessels? <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON>, business agent for Local 802 of the <ORGANIZATION> Boilermakers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, says the company made a mistake by hiring Japanese consultants to introduce `` modular'' construction techniques. In traditional shipbuilding, workers build the hull and install mechanical and electrical equipment inside the cramped confines. The new technique has workers completely build entire sections and then weld or bolt them together. `` That's one thing we're bitter about,'' <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. `` We've been building 50-ton units and lifting them into place for years The Japanese did n't show us anything we did n't know already. But the company treated them like gods while they treated their own employees like dirt.'' <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> disagrees. `` The modular techniques helped,'' he said, insisting that the shipyard's troubles would have been even worse without them. Absenteeism was n't especially a problem, <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON> said, but hiring skilled workers was. `` That's really true throughout the country,'' he said. `` The shipbuilding industry used to have a lot of skilled people. Most shipyards used to have apprentice programs, and they were major employers. Those people have left and found work in other areas. `` These are people in the skilled trades _ electricians, sheet metal workers, machinists and so on _ and they do n't have any trouble finding new jobs. If you have to build up again, you have to start over.''
</TEXT>
