<FIRST>s i BC-APN--FrenchDrugs Adv15-2Takes   10-02 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--French Drugs, Adv 15-2 Takes,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 graphic.)
   </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Lifesaving drugs are often available in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> long before they are on the market in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The reason is a difference in the bureaucracies of the two countries. While some argue that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> should speed up its drug approval process, others warn that it's risky to be hasty.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In 1985, a desperately ill <PERSON> Rock </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> was one of many AIDS patients who fled to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for a drug they could n't get in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The drug did n't work. But at the time it was the only hope, and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> doctors could n't prescribe it. Last year, French doctors began prescribing the so-called abortion pill to terminate pregnancies. <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women may not get it for years. These are two examples among many in which the French became the first to receive the potential benefits of new drugs. It happens because the French drug approval system is simpler and faster than that of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Advocates of the French system say it has elements that could be adopted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, cutting the time that <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> must wait for new drugs. The issue has become increasingly important as the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> faces growing pressure to speed the approval of experimental cancer and AIDS drugs that might help patients who would otherwise be unlikely to survive. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has, in fact, responded to that pressure by speeding the approval of the AIDS drug AZT. And on Sept. 28, it announced that it was making a newer AIDS drug, called <ORGANIZATION> DDI </ORGANIZATION>, widely available while tests of its safety and effectiveness are still continuing. Defenders of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> argue the French system has certain drawbacks that would make it unworkable in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The French system is faster `` because it's very different,'' says <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON>, former deputy director of drugs at the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the drug approval process is subject to enormous oversight by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and consumer groups, says <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON>, who is now with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmacopeial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, a private organization that sets standards for drug quality, purity and strength. Some public interest groups are calling for a speed-up in drug approval, <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON> notes, at the same time that others are arguing that the agency takes unnecessary risks by sometimes being too hasty. The classic example of a drug being approved too quickly is thalidomide, which caused severe birth defects after it was approved in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in the late 1950s and early 1960s. The drug was never approved in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Oversight from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the public interest groups inevitably puts pressure on reviewers and slows down the drug-approval process, <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON> says. Similar government and public oversight does not exist in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` There is hardly ever anybody from the AP or <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> looking over their shoulders,'' says Dr. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON>, a clinical pharmacologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, who spent the 1980-81 academic year in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> studying its pharmaceutical approval process. `` Our system is much more political.'' Most Americans see that public scrutiny as important, even though it might slow new drug approvals, <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON> says. Nevertheless, he says, there are examples of drugs that get approved here before they get approved in other countries, including some AIDS drugs. `` I think the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has gone remarkably far in making experimental AIDS drugs available with as little administrative encumbrance as possible,'' <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON> says. The principal difference between the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> and American systems is that while the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> relies on an in-house staff of drug reviewers, the French rely on an outside committee of expert volunteers, says Dr. <PERSON> Yves </PERSON> <PERSON> Juillet </PERSON>, director of scientific affairs for the <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Some of the volunteers are drawn from the drug industry itself. That works well in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Juillet </PERSON> says, but the use of drug company scientists to review drugs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would likely draw allegations of conflict of interest.
</TEXT>
