<FIRST>s a BC-APN--FrenchDrugs Adv15-1stAdd   10-02 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--French Drugs, Adv 15-1st Add,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>PARIS: of interest.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The French expert committee meets every other Friday morning to review pending new drug applications. Individual committee members present written technical reviews of each application and then the committee makes its decisions. In cases in which unusual speed is needed, or in which research results are especially complicated, the health ministry simply invites additional experts to join the committee for a time. `` It does n't cost a lot because people are not paid for that,'' <PERSON> Juillet </PERSON> said in an interview at <LOCATION> Broussais </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, where he practices medicine. A decision is generally rendered within a few months after a company sends in its research reports. The health minister rubber-stamps it. `` When I was there, the limit was four months, and I almost never saw anything over four months,'' <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON> says. In contrast, at the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> `` some drugs are quicker than others but by and large it's about 18 months'' for approval after a final application has been submitted, <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON> says. `` In the French system, everything is reviewed within an hour or an hour-and-a-half in one day at one presentation,'' <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON> says. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> also places great emphasis on certain studies considered pivotal in demonstrating the safety and effectiveness of new drugs. The most important thing the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> could learn from the French would be `` not focusing on the so-called pivotal studies, but looking at all the studies and all the data,'' <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON> says. One of the drawbacks of the French system, according to <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON>, is that the health ministry does little until research is complete and the company is ready to ask for approval. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> requires a review of laboratory findings before it will allow a new drug to be tested on humans. The French do n't. Drug companies simply inform the health ministry that human trials are about to begin, and the ministry rarely intervenes. `` They ca n't guide you,'' <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON> says. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> meets regularly with drug companies testing new drugs to advise the companies on what further research is needed for approval. In <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, `` there are no contacts between the committee and the companies until the file is through,'' Juillet says. When the file of research data is complete, Juillet, acting as the industry representative, makes the company's case before the committee. `` My mission is to be a witness and defend the companies and give them information if there is a problem,'' he says. French drug companies have a much closer relationship with the health ministry than American companies do with the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON> says, `` because the reviewers do n't work for the government; it's not a ` them-and-us' thing. In contrast, <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> reviewers and drug companies often deeply distrust each other. Company officials charge the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> with dragging its feet, while the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> often blames delays on the inadequacy of the companies' research. Juillet suggests the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> should rely more on outside reviewers. `` I think the open system is a good thing, working with people on the outside,'' he says. Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Leighton </PERSON>, a senior vice-president at <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sharpe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Dohme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Blue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, says one reason French drug approvals are often faster is that the French have decided that the benefits of speeding new drug approval outweigh the risks. `` They realize there might be a risk,'' he says. `` If you're the first country to approve a drug, you might be the first to see a problem.'' <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON> says history shows, however, that the French have not in fact been subject to more problems with drug side-effects than have Americans. `` We are n't saved from every problem drug, nor are they exposed to every problem drug,'' he says. Although he believes the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has much to learn from the French, <PERSON> Weintraub </PERSON> praises the expertise of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s reviewers. `` Everybody respects those people. They're smart, hard-working. ... A lot of countries will allow marketing of the drug once the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> does. `` We are the benchmark, for good or ill.''
</TEXT>
