<FIRST>s i BC-APN--HimalayanBattleground Adv15-2Takes   10-02 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Himalayan Battleground, Adv 15-2 Takes,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo,
1 graphic.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The startling boom of heavy artillery reverberates through the world's highest mountains where for five years <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> have been fighting for control of an icy wasteland. While neither side will say how many casualities they have suffered, they estimate only one in three resulted from combat.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIACHEN GLACIER, Kashmir (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Top of the World is the battleground in a largely unknown and undeclared war raging between <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, a war in which wind, snow and ice often take a greater toll than the enemy. At stake is national prestige and possession of the Siachen, a Himalayan wasteland wedged between Pakistan-occupied <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> and territory controlled by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. After more than five years of fighting and artillery duels over what would appear to be a minor issue, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> are trying to end the costly war. Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and Pakistani Prime Minister <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, confident they can do business, are pushing to bury ancient animosities and move their countries into a friendlier era. But while they talk of peace, huge artillery guns continue to boom, each startling blast echoing through the stillness of the cathedral-like mountains. Fifteen years ago few thought it possible to fight, let alone hold ground, for years in the higher reaches of the <LOCATION> Karakoram </LOCATION> mountain range, where lie the Siachen and more than half of the world's 20 tallest peaks. Never had battles been fought for any length of time at heights of up to 4 miles, breathing air that contains less than half the oxygen at sea level and at temperatures that frequently drop to 50 degrees below zero. `` Climb a 21,000-foot mountain anywhere else in the world and you get an award,'' Brig. Gen. V.R. <PERSON> Raghavan </PERSON>, commander of the Indian troops, told foreign journalists flown to the base camp at the mouth of the Siachen and then taken by helicopter up the 45-mile-long, 6-mile-wide glacier. The number of casualties on both sides remains a military secret, although <PERSON> Raghavan </PERSON> estimated only one-third are actually due to combat. `` There are natural limits to this conflict _ the weather and the terrain,'' he said. `` Here one has to fight constantly and even more doggedly to survive. So much depends on so few and death can be just one false move away.'' The conflict's roots can be traced to the 1947 partition of Moslem <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, which is predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Hindu </ORGANIZATION>. Both countries have coveted the 85,000 square miles of <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION>, a predominantly Moslem state that acceded to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. The dispute led <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> to grab about one-third of the territory. In 1949, the two countries signed an agreement that drew a cease-fire line that stopped at the southern foot of the Saltoro range running along the glacier's western edge toward the Chinese border. Negotiators did not extend the line because there was no fighting in the region and glaciers were difficult to demarcate. Although there were minor adjustments following the 1965 and 1971 India-Pakistan wars, the question of Siachen was left unresolved. Almost from the beginning, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has said it is entitled to control all of <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, however, says it has controlled the Siachen all along, citing mountaineering expeditions that for years sought its permission to enter and atlases published in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in the early 1980s that showed the area under its control. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> first deployed troops to the Siachen in April 1984, a move it said was merely to pre-empt a planned Pakistani strike. <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> denied the charge. The conflict slowly escalated, with each side deploying thousands of soldiers, erecting outposts and setting up bigger, more powerful artillery. In the winter of 1987, Indian troops abandoned a 20,000-foot outpost on <LOCATION> Bilaford </LOCATION>, one of three key passes. When they returned in the spring and found the Pakistanis had moved in, a fierce six-day battle ensued, with both sides pounding the other with artillery. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> retaliated three months later with its biggest strike of the war, capturing one post and closing in on a second before the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> unleashed an artillery barrage.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891002-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 1511EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--HimalayanBattleground Adv15-1stAdd   10-02 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Himalayan Battleground, Adv 15-1st Add,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>SIACHEN GLACIER: artillery barrage.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` The secret to this conflict is to control the high ground, and we do. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is on the lower slopes, and we can punish them whenever necessary,'' <PERSON> Raghavan </PERSON> said as 130mm artillery guns fired, reverberating through the canyons. `` We have just given them our reply for firing at one of our posts.'' Indian soldiers posted on the peaks and ridges keep watch day and night for the other side's supply and patrols columns. It is a lonely existence for the soldiers, most of whom come from the palm-fringed beaches of southern <LOCATION> Kerala </LOCATION> state or the desert of western <LOCATION> Rajasthan </LOCATION> or the jungles of eastern <LOCATION> Assam </LOCATION> and have never lived _ much less fought in _ a snowbound environment. `` This is the hardest place on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Modhival </PERSON> <PERSON> Iqbal </PERSON>, a weary 23-year-old soldier who just completed four months of duty at a 19,000-foot outpost. From the base camp, soldiers armed with ice picks, skis, shovels, ropes and 65-pound backpacks trudge across the black moraine, through knee-deep snow and over 200-foot crevasses and up the walls of ice to their posts. But before leaving, each visits the cave-like enclave where there are hung images of the Hindu gods <PERSON> Rama </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Shiva </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Ganesha </PERSON>, as well as a portrait of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>. `` Everybody who goes to the glacier comes here first and says his prayers. It does n't matter if he's Hindu or Moslem or Christian,'' <PERSON> Raghavan </PERSON> said. The trek takes six to eight days, with brief rest stops at posts along the way, before reaching the small outposts where the soldiers live for months in bunkers dug deep in the snow. `` Every day up there is important because every day you survive means you're one day closer to leaving,'' <PERSON> Iqbal </PERSON> said. `` It's not just the Pakistanis. It's the blizzards, the howling winds, the blinding glare of the sun off the snow. It's the avalanches and the isolation. `` We have plenty of food and supplies, but not much else. Maybe someday somebody will organize a society for the prevention of cruelty to soldiers.'' A month-long clash erupted in April when <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> allegedly tried to establish a new post within easy firing range of the Indians and both sides dispatched soldiers to an icy 21,300-foot peak. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, however, said it had only discovered an old observation post. Accounts of what happened differ, but the Indians apparently requested a meeting between the two opposition commanders. After three sessions both sides agreed to pull back and the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> agreed to accept the post the Pakistanis had said was there all along. With <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> commanding most of the heights along the <LOCATION> Saltoro </LOCATION>, it now wants that boundary to serve as the northern extension of the line that divides most of <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Since January 1986, the two governments have met five times to discuss withdrawing their troops from the glacier and to consider declaring the region a demilitarized zone. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> officials believe the eventual withdrawal of <LOCATION> Indiain </LOCATION> troops would be a major victory for Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and a vindication of their position that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> started the conflict by sending troops into an undemarcated area. Both Pakistani and Indian officials say the rapport between <LOCATION> Gandhi </LOCATION> and Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> is helping but it still may be difficult for either to yield. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> is only months away from facing a national election. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> is in an even stickier situation, facing criticism at home from opposition leaders who accuse her of submission to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. While their leaders struggle to find a political solution, both sides contend they can hold out indefinitely. `` Whether there is a settlement is a matter between state and state,'' <PERSON> Raghavan </PERSON> said. `` Until then, we have a job to do. That does n't mean we want to stay here forever. Who would? But we can stay here as long as we have to.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
