<FIRST>s a BC-APN--IconPainting Adv15   10-02 1146</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Icon Painting, Adv 15,1185</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The painting of religious icons is an art form inspired by the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and now practiced by less than 100 artists across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. But there are two schools that teach icon painting in this country, one in a mountain community in western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIGONIER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> paints mystical `` windows to heaven,'' he says, haunting religious icons used as vehicles of prayer. `` Icons are a very important part of the church,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says. `` They are a spiritual and physical depiction of some sacred image _ of Christ or the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>, a saint or some other liturgical happening.'' Icons, popular in the Eastern Orthodox Church, are painted in rich, luminous colors. Faces are depicted with prayerful expressions, and religious figures usually are crowned with halos of real gold, not gold paint. Perpective and scale are distorted to give the religious scenes a supernatural feel. Some regard icons simply as products of religious devotion or art inspired by the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which began the tradition centuries ago. The religious regard icons as `` windows to heaven'' or `` theology made visible'' and believe focusing on them deepens prayer and meditation, <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON>, 36, of nearby <LOCATION> Johnstown </LOCATION>, has been teaching two-week classes in icon painting since last summer at <LOCATION> Antiochian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>, an Orthodox cultural center outside this mountain community about 60 miles east of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. The village, and the <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sacred </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, are the only schools in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> offering classes in icon painting. <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says there are about 90 iconographers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Students must learn to create within the strict conventions of the art. They eventually develop their own styles while absorbing hundreds of details on symbolism used in icons. For instance, halos _ blazing disks of golden light _ are applied in gold leaf around the heads of divine figures to depict emanations of radiant light. `` They are auras of spiritual holiness. Icons depict not just a person's earthly image, but a spritual-type image as well,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says. `` There is no light source like in other art. The light source comes from within the figure.'' Anatomical details such as facial features, fingers and body shapes are stylized to give figures an additional aura of the supernatural. Scenes are painted in two dimensions and no shadows are cast. `` That's why in iconography, the icons do not look like real people,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says. `` We're not trying to make them look like real people. It's a symbolic representation of a person.'' Certain colors are associated with some religious figures. Christ, for example, usually is depicted in blue and red. `` You usually never depict <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> in green,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says. `` It's not traditional.'' Iconographers say they technically do not paint icons, but `` write'' them. Artists are taught to create their works with thousands of tiny caligraphic strokes. `` What they are are scriptural pictures _ pictures of the scriptures,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says. `` When you write the icon, you're writing scriptures just the same as when you are using words. Although the mechanics of the art are important, theology debates often erupt during class sessions. `` It's very, very, very theological,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says. `` There's a lot of rules attached to this _ not a lot of painting rules, but a whole lot of rules on what's proper, what's liturgical, what's not liturgical Interest in icon painting has increased dramatically in recent years, and not just among the religious. `` People here in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> are just beginning to discover the art of the Orthodox church,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says. `` It's not just something <PERSON> Grandma </PERSON> brought over from <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>.'' `` I think the whole interest in religion is coming back,'' says <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON>, an official of the School of Sacred Arts. `` For a long time people were looking to Eastern religions and Eastern mysticism. While that's still popular, people are returning to their own traditions now.'' <PERSON> Iconographer </PERSON> <PERSON> Vladislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Andreyev </PERSON>, who was born in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, offers a 14-week class at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> school, which also offers classes on the art traditions of other religions. `` It's pretty international and we sell out every time. We usually limit classes to 10 students,'' he says. `` Many of the arts we teach are not available elsewhere.'' Classes offered in the subject are short-term, but it often takes years to develop competence, says <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Papas </PERSON>, 30, an iconographer from nearby <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. `` When I first started I was very timid and self-conscious,'' he says. `` I was pretentious, boxed in and stiff. I feel that it took me years to even begin to break out of that. I feel like I'm still breaking out of that.'' Papas began painting icons in 1979 and started full-time work as an iconographer in 1982. Papas sells notebook-size icons of a favorite subject, such as portraits of Christ, for as little as $ 175, but bigger and more complicated works can be worth thousands of dollars. `` Every iconographer has his own idea of what he should get for an icon,'' he says. Papas' icons usually are sold to churches or people who display them in their homes. A giant mural of his is displayed 30 feet above the ground in the dome of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Byzantine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in nearby <LOCATION> Homer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. A 70 - by 12-foot mural Papas currently is working on, `` The Communion of the Apostles,'' will attempt to depict what heaven looks like The idea of selling icons to people who admire them only as works of art is a sticky ethical problem for some iconographers who fear the buyer would be misusing a holy object. `` I would feel uncomfortable, but I would do it,'' says <PERSON> Papas </PERSON>, who was born to an Eastern Orthodox family. `` Even if a person asked me for an icon for the wrong reason, there's a possibility that the icon could be a good influence on them.'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> began painting icons 18 years ago, while studying to be an art teacher at <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>. An iconographer who served as the choir director of one local Orthodox church recruited him and several of his college friends to help him with his work. `` We made his job a little easier by filling in colors and stuff like that,'' <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> says. Also during college, <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON> decided to leave the <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> to become an Eastern Orthodox Christian. `` I was always interested in religion, always interested in exploring other religions as well,'' he says. `` I felt the Orthodox Church was very satisfying. I felt this church has so much to offer liturgically, spiritually, musically, artistically _ everything.''
</TEXT>
