<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv15   10-02 1100</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 15,1127</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)    </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Before he returned to Broadway for the first time in 25 years, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> wondered whether audiences would forget television's <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Unger </PERSON> long enough to accept him as the tormented protagonist of `` M. Butterfly.'' After all, <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> was <PERSON> Felix </PERSON>, the fussy, fastidious half of `` The Odd Couple,'' for five years on prime time television as well as in nine stage productions with four different <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Madisons </PERSON>, including his TV co-star, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Klugman </PERSON>. `` That question came up a million times,'' <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> recalled the other day. `` Would they want to laugh instead?'' He need not have worried. `` There's not a moment of rejection and having to win them over,'' he says now, talking about his performance as <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallimard </PERSON>, the French diplomat who has an affair with a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> opera singer. And theatergoers go along willingly with the more bizarre plot developments in <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hwang </PERSON>'s Tony award-winning play. <PERSON> Gallimard </PERSON> is seduced by the singer who turns out to be a man masquerading as a woman. `` But then director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> has set up the play so that when the first voice comes out of this miasma of light and movement and music, the audience is already captivated,'' the actor says. `` He's the only director I ever worked with in my life who I thought was a genius. <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> is one of those actors who's not afraid of opinions. Asked why it has been more than 25 years since he has appeared on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>, he says, `` No one's asked me. `` I've frequently had a year off or more and have noised it around town that I was available. The fact that a man is a Broadway producer does n't make him any more intelligent than a network executive.'' Not that he has n't been on stage during this time. Last year, there was a <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON> farce done at the Paper Mill Playhouse in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, and he has worked for <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Neville </PERSON>'s theater company in <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION> as well as in all those tours of `` The Odd Couple.'' `` ` The Odd Couple' is a masterpiece,'' he states matter-of-factly. `` The laughs just roll in. But you have to play it as if it's ` Hamlet' _ very, very seriously. `` Any play that is good has some ideological basis behind it. In ` The Odd Couple,' it's male bonding. The play is very chauvinistic and anti-feminist. The only women in it are two dingbats, and the men hate their wives. The only happiness these men have is when they are away from their wives.'' <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> has worked in just about every medium except burlesque. Last year when he was honored at the <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION>, four videocassette machines simultaneously unspooled `` The Odd Couple,'' `` The <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Show </PERSON>,'' `` Love, <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON>'' and `` Mr. Peepers,'' the four television series he has done. `` There was my life on the screen,'' he recalls. `` You could watch me go bald.'' Bits and pieces of <PERSON> Randall </PERSON>'s story also are told in `` Which Reminds Me,'' a collection of show business anecdotes he has gathered during his more than 40 years as an actor. <PERSON> Randall </PERSON>, who says he's `` cursed with almost total recall,'' wrote the book in collaboration with and at the urging of a good friend, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mindlin </PERSON>, an advertising executive and movie publicity man. It arrives in bookstores in November from <ORGANIZATION> Delacorte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Randall </PERSON>, fresh out of <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Olka </LOCATION>., and one year at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, came to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in the early 1940s His first Broadway show was <PERSON> Thorton </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s `` The Skin of Our Teeth'' in 1942. Well, almost. He was drafted into the Army the second day of rehearsals. Four years later, <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where he found a lot of work on radio and a few small parts in the theater. But he did n't _ and still does n't _ think much of radio work. `` It was nothing,'' <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> recalls. `` Standing there reading a script. What was that? And the script, for the most part, was dreck. It probably had been written that morning. How could you act? You had one rehearsal and you were on the air.'' <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> had better luck _ and better parts _ on television, beginning in 1952, when he appeared as English teacher <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Weskitt </PERSON> in `` Mr. Peepers,'' one of the best of the early TV sitcoms. His big break on Broadway came in 1955 in `` Inherit the Wind,'' a retelling of the Scopes trial in which he played a reporter modeled after H.L. <PERSON> Mencken </PERSON>. The play propelled him to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> for scores of movies, including three <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Day-Rock </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> classics, `` Pillow Talk,'' `` Lover Come Back'' and `` Send Me No Flowers,'' as well as other films like `` Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter?'' and `` The Seven Faces of Dr. Lao.'' The 69-year-old <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> admits he was a little frightened about returning to Broadway in a play as physically demanding as `` M. Butterfly.'' `` That's what I thought would kill me,'' he says. `` Moving around like that and the knowledge that my predecessor -LRB- <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubinstein </PERSON> -RRB- had lost 25 pounds. And he was a young guy. They had to get new costumes for him. `` But I was at the doctor's this morning with my wife and I've gained weight. Memorizing was an easy part of the job, <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> says. He had four weeks of rehearsal before going on in `` M. Butterfly,'' and director <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> came back for a week to work with him. `` A replacement does n't have that much option really,'' <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> says. `` The first three weeks of rehearsal, he just works with the stage manager who takes him through the established staging. If he wants to change anything he can, but it's foolish. The stage is lighted. Everything is set. If you want to move here instead of there, that means they have to change the lights. It's not worth it.'' Actually, he adds, playing in `` The Odd Couple'' was more tiring than `` M. Butterfly.'' `` But the role of Oscar is harder than <PERSON> Felix </PERSON>. Oscar is a killer,'' he says of other half of `` The Odd Couple.'' `` I do n't think I could play Oscar too well. Although when I went into this play, a half dozen people asked me what part I'm playing,'' <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> laughs `` I do n't see myself as the young Chinese girl. `` I think it's ` The Seven Faces of Dr. Lao.' They know I played an Oriental in that movie.''
