<SECOND>BC-Taiwan-40 Years, Adv 08-2 Takes,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>After 40 Years, Taiwan Is Rich and Democracy Makes Inroads</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>By ANNIE HUANG</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> TAIPEI </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> _ Forty years after <PERSON> Generalissimo </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON> and his Nationalist Chinese arrived in defeat from the mainland, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> is prosperous _ the world's 13th largest trading nation _ and democracy is beginning to take hold. But in 1949, with <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>' Communists in control of mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the outlook for the Chinese Nationalists on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> was bleak. Not only had they been routed from their homeland, they faced a restive Taiwanese population that viewed <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> and his 2 million or so followers as an occupying force. The Nationalists prevailed, nevertheless, by dint of authoritarian rule and clinging to their contention, supported by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other Western nations, that they were the legitimate rulers of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. In the years since, firmly guided economic policies have transformed <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> into the economic success it is now as the island approaches its national day Oct. 10 _ Double Ten, for the tenth day of the tenth month. With prosperity at its peak and people demanding greater freedoms, the Nationalists have begun to loosen their authoritarian grip, slowly bringing democracy to the island of 20 million and permitting contacts with the rival Communist Chinese for the first time since the civil war on the mainland. `` Many people used to be disappointed with the government and tried to emigrate whenever they had the chance,'' said <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ya-li </PERSON>, political science professor of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taiwan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` They now feel there is some hope and have begun to care and criticize.'' An agrarian economy based on rice and sugar production has given way to the manufacturing of textiles, electronic products and machinery. The formula was capitalism mixed with government policies designed to stimulate selected industries. While the Nationalists controlled major monopolies, many of the light-industry factories were family-run operations that helped spread the wealth around the island. Annual per capita income rose from $ 50 in 1949 to $ 5,512 last year. Gross national product soared from $ 1.2 billion 40 years ago to $ 119 billion in 1988. Exports led the way, with foreign trade jumping from $ 300 million in 1952 to $ 110 billion last year. So much foreign exchange has poured in that the island's coffers bulge with $ 74 billion in reserves. Prosperity is everywhere on the streets of <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>. Porsche and BMW automobiles snake through the congested streets, fancy restaurants are on almost every block and the latest electronic gadgets fill store windows. Indeed, <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>, the island's capital, seems to lack nothing. Except foreign embassies. While the island advanced on economic successes, it faced bitter diplomatic defeats as the world recognized the Communist Chinese government in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Only 24 countries, mostly tiny island nations and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries, still recognize <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> diplomatically, down from 50 in 1949. The Communist Chinese government has formal ties with 135 countries. The toughest blow came in 1978, when <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s major ally, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, announced it was cutting diplomatic links and setting up formal relations with <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> dismantled its military bases on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and said military aid would not increase in quantity or quality. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market did not close to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and that helped assure its economic health. <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng-chien </PERSON>, a leading opposition politician, blamed <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s diplomatic isolation on the `` dream of a reunified <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'' ruled by a Nationalist government. The Nationalists also used that dream in their efforts to justify their monopoly on political power and the harsh quelling of dissent. The Nationalists placed <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> under martial law and refused to allow rival political parties or an opposition press. Critics who traveled overseas often were not allowed back; many of those who stayed in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> were thrown in jail. By claiming to be the rightful ruler of all <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the Nationalists insisted that native Taiwanese, who comprise about 80 percent of the population, could not replace any of the members of the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> and electoral college who had been elected in mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> before the civil war defeat. But as the Taiwanese prospered economically they demanded more political rights. It was <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON>'s son, the late President <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON>, who finally launched the political liberalization the Nationalists needed if they were to maintain popular support. In 1987, <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON> lifted martial law, which paved the way for the formation of opposition political parties. Some media restrictions were erased, leading to a more critical press. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> residents were allowed to visit relatives on the Chinese mainland, bringing a more relaxed attitude toward the Communists.
</TEXT>
