<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>TAIPEI: the Communists.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Demonstrations became an almost daily occurrence, with Taiwanese taking to the streets to protest everything from prostitution to pollution. By the following year, it became apparent that the gradual liberalizing trend would not easily be reversed. When <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON> died in January 1988, he was succeeded by Vice President <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Teng-hui </PERSON>, the first native Taiwanese to lead the Nationalist government and a supporter of democratic reform. Six months later, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was named chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and some, but not all, aging hardliners from the mainland retired from top party posts. The Nationalist leadership under <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> has proposed a gradual increase in the percentage of the Legislature that is elected on <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. Still, only less than half the seats will be contested in Dec. 2 elections, making it impossible for the opposition to wrest any real political power from the Nationalists. `` We are fully committed to democratization,'' government spokesman <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu-ming </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` We are moving slowly but surely to meet the demands of the time.'' But <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> still has problems: _ Rising wages and an appreciating currency: These have made <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> less competitive in low-cost exports and the government is seeking a new economic formula to deal with the problem `` We must actively push forward the research of top-notch industrial technologies,'' Premier <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Huan </PERSON> recently told the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>. `` The service sector should also grow quicker to become the center of our future economic development.'' _ Pollution caused by years of rapid development: <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>'s air is foul and the island's rivers are filthy Some villagers have protested the construction of new factories they fear will ruin the local environment. _ Gambling and speculation: Gambling is illegal but rampant, and speculating in the stock market has become the national pastime The <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> stock exchange is second only to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s in trading volume, and some analysts believe it is a speculative bubble waiting to burst. Some see the obsession as a temporary phenomenon following the easing of foreign exchange controls in 1987. Others argue that industrialists are more interested in quick profit than in longterm investment, such as automating factories and developing more sophisticated products. Perhaps the greatest challenge facing <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> is its policy toward mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Official policy remains the `` three no's'' _ no contact, no negotiations, no compromise with the Communists. But that policy today is a shambles. The government allows trade with the mainland if conducted through a third party such as <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, and Taiwanese businessmen have begun investing in the mainland to take advantage of low labor costs. Finance Minister <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuo </PERSON> traveled to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in May to attend an <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> meeting and met privately with Communist officials. The future of such contacts is somewhat clouded because of the Communists' violent suppression of the democracy movement this past spring. But the old Nationalist dream of returning to rule the mainland seems shattered. When the Chinese Communist government seemed in disarray during the spring democracy movement, the Nationalists were forced to acknowledge there was not much they could do but watch. `` We must have the courage to face the fact that at this moment we are unable to effectively exercise the right to govern the mainland,'' President <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> told a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> leaders on June 3.
</TEXT>
