<FIRST>s i BC-Afghanistan-Islam Adv08   10-02 1183</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Afghanistan-Islam, Adv 08,1225</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Differences Over Islam Are at Root of Afghanistan's Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFAQUAHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Differences over what is and what is not Islam lies at the heart of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s 10-year war. President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> has been attempting to deflate his foes' main rallying cry _ that his Marxist-based <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION> is a pack of godless Soviet stooges _ by transplanting the party's ideology into the country's Islamic heritage. But many Afghans hold deep suspicions that the party is rooted in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> next door. The assault on Islam by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s predecessors has not been forgotten Islam is the one link the violently competitive Afghan tribes all share. Being recognized as a good Moslem is an ironclad form of acceptance. Doubt in the leaders' faith is strongest among the Shiite Moslem minority known as the Hazara. They make up about 17 percent of the 16 million Afghans, 99 percent of whom are Moslems. The Sunni sect is the overwhelming majority. Hundreds of thousands of Hazara live in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, but most inhabit the mountains at the country's center, an area known as <LOCATION> Hazarajat </LOCATION>. The government has little control there, but the <PERSON> Hazara </PERSON> rejected a government offer of formal autonomy earlier this year. `` The Hazara want to be part of the government, but not their -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- government,'' said one 52-year-old professional interviewed at the <LOCATION> Chendawul </LOCATION> mosque. `` It is a communist government.'' The group was officially discriminated against for years, kept out of the army and their rituals banned in public. The Hazara now have religious freedom, but they contend the government ignores their development needs. `` If you go to <LOCATION> Hazarajat </LOCATION>, there are no houses, there are no schools, there are no hospitals,'' said a mullah, or prayer leader, at the <LOCATION> Chendawul </LOCATION> mosque. The Hazara spoke in interviews only on condition of anonymity, saying that many who publicly denounced the government in the past were sent to prison. They said the government's wooing them is in part motivated by the desire to improve relations with neighboring <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, founded by the late <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, is run by <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> clergymen and supports the <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> branches of the Moslem rebels, the mujahedeen, seeking to overthrow the government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The Hazara say they respect <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> as a religious figure but do not look to his revolution to solve their problems. Many Hazara reject fellow Shiites who have joined the government, such as Prime Minister Sultan <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Kishtmand </PERSON>. `` The people in the party, it makes no difference from what place, what religion they are, we still think they are communist,'' said the mullah. <PERSON> Najmuddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kawyani </PERSON>, secretary of the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committeee </ORGANIZATION>, says, `` Our party is not a communist party, our ideology is not a communist one.'' Government officials say development will come in time. They point out that President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, who uses just one name, went to the <LOCATION> Chendawul </LOCATION> mosque in August and pledged 10 million afghans, about $ 180,000, for reconstruction. Suspicions about the religious faith of the government also are held by other Afghan Moslems, including <PERSON> Maulavi </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Rauf </PERSON> at the upscale <PERSON> Wazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> mosque, which is surrounded by a rose garden in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s diplomatic quarter. `` Our people are Moslem,'' he said. `` We do n't know about the government.'' The Sunni <PERSON> Maulavi </PERSON>, who is roughly the equivalent of a bishop, spent five months in prison after he assailed Soviet influence in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> at a sermon the president had attended. He also opposes the government's practice of writing sermons in support of its policies for the 20,000 mullahs on its payroll. `` Religion should be free,'' <PERSON> Rauf </PERSON> said. The role of the government is `` to build more mosques, persuade people to pray more, to establish the conditions so people will want to pray,'' he said. The lack of trust in the party stems from alleged atrocities that followed the April 1978 Marxist revolution. Independent studies put the number of Afghans killed in those early days of the revolution at 50,000 to 100,000, with <PERSON> Hazara </PERSON> and clergymen a particular target. Hazara claim 13,000 of their tribesman disappeared from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in one day. The government's land redistribution program was seen as an attempt to rewrite Moslem inheritance laws and a heavy-handed literacy campaign as an attack on the clergy as teachers. Even the study of Islamic art was banned. These measures helped spark the rebellion against the government and all have been reversed since the Soviet intervention in December 1979, after which a more tolerant wing of the party was given power. `` The culture of the people must be taken into considertion,'' said <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghafoor </PERSON> <PERSON> Bahir </PERSON>, minister of Islamic guidance. `` When the revolution came there were some mistakes.'' Islam was enshrined as the state religion in the constitution adopted in 1987, which also stipulates that the president be a Moslem. New laws can not contradict Islamic law. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> has won praise for establishing the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The Soviet withdrawel in February gave a major boost to combating his un-Islamic image. The research center publishes books about Islamic history in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, such as a chronicle of the holy place in <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>. It is also a religious cheering section for the party, however. Its walls are plastered with stickers of Koranic quotations used by President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. `` He who destroys the house of one Moslem, he is in truth destroying his own house,'' said one quotation. It is a pointed reference to the destruction wrought by rockets of the mujahedeen, whose name means holy warriors. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Siddiq </PERSON> <PERSON> Sailani </PERSON>, the university's president, <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> said that its aim is to educate students and that the religious squabbling impedes progress. `` Some traditional customs that exist among the people are un-Islamic,'' he said. `` We want to replace them with the real Islam.'' Among the customs he listed as un-Islamic was what he described as the lack of equal treatment for women. `` A woman is not a toy,'' he said. `` Islam establishes many rights for women and the rights should never be threatened by men.'' The government viewpoint on this and other issues clashes sharply with that of <PERSON> Gulbuddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, leader of the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Hezb-e-Islami </ORGANIZATION> faction of the Pakistani-based mujahedeen. He has a reputation for having all the bars in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> bombed because <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION> forbids the consumption of alcohol. His group also is believed responsible for killing two women bus drivers by blowing up their buses when the government briefly experimented with women drivers several years ago. The government also highlights what it calls the atrocities committed in the name of Islam by the Saudi Arabian-financed Wahhabi mercenaries fighting for the mujahedeen. Reports of their mutilating victims and selling women into slavery are widespread. `` In our opinion, it is because of lack of knowledge of the Koran that makes people act like this,'' said <PERSON> Gholam </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Manzur </PERSON>, president of the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clergy </ORGANIZATION>. Afghans in general say they basically want Islam respected by the government.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 8</NOTE>
