<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   10-02 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Look Who's Talking''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Film opens nationwide Oct. 13.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Remember the `` Bachelor Mother'' kind of movie in which <PERSON> Ginger </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> seeks a husband so her baby will have a father? `` Look Who's Talking'' is a 1989 replay with all the old gimmicks intact -LRB- `` I do n't like to fly,'' she insists. Next scene, she's flying in his plane -RRB-. The only innovation: the baby talks. Not only that, the voice is that of <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>. The title, get it? It's a pleasant sitcom with amiable performances, especially by the four infants who play <PERSON> Mikey </PERSON>. The scenes under the titles will no doubt arouse controversy. A large round object floats amid translucent, undulating folds of matter, bouncing gently at the bottom of a pit. A flock of flittering, chattering polliwogs enters the space, and one of them joyfully discovers the round object and climbs inside. A new kind of sex education. Throughout the film, the voice of <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> makes comments, enjoying his nine-month swim, complaining about his abrupt emergence, conversing with other infants and generally observing the human comedy. The one-liners wear thin, but some of it is funny stuff. <PERSON> Mikey </PERSON>'s mother is <LOCATION> Kirstie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alley </LOCATION>, a thirtysomething accountant who has been impregnated by her client, a lecherous, charmless fast-food entrepreneur -LRB- <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> -RRB-. When she goes into labor, she hails a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> cab driven by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Travolta </PERSON>, who races her to the hospital, then dons a mask and gown and witnesses the delivery. As you can guess, he falls for <PERSON> Kirstie </PERSON> and her baby, but she considers him a loser. He becomes the sitter while she prowls for prospective fathers, not realizing that <PERSON> Travolta </PERSON> is really a struggling flight instructor. To illustrate his compassion, there is a subplot about his concern for his senile grandfather -LRB- <PERSON> Abe </PERSON> <PERSON> Vigoda </PERSON> -RRB-. <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Heckerling </PERSON> -LRB- `` Fast Times at Ridgemont High'' -RRB- directed her own script, a loose affair that allows the actors to ad lib aimlessly. The veracity of the film was not helped by filming it in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The producers saved money, but there's no way that <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> can double for <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kirstie </PERSON> <PERSON> Alley </PERSON> manages an endearing portrait of the beleaguered mother; she's as appealing on the big screen as she is in `` Cheers.'' <PERSON> Travolta </PERSON> is so laid back that he seems invisible at times, but it's good to see him back. <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has some bright moments as the worrying grandmother. `` Look Who's Talking'' is a Tri-Star release produced by <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Krane </PERSON>. The rating is PG-13, mostly for adult situations. Running time: 103 minutes.
