<HEAD>The Artists: Symphony Star Started Career Late, at Age Nine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Finnish conducter <ORGANIZATION> Esa-Pekka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Salonen </ORGANIZATION> is a star in the symphony orchestra world, and his only lament is that his career in classical music started late _ at age 9. `` In this business people start at age 4 or 5,'' said the 31-year-old <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON>, named in August as musical director of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philharmonic </LOCATION>. `` I realized young that this would have to be my life. I had no other hobbies.'' <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> recently as a guest conducter, said he looks forward to settling down with the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> orchestra after years of nomadic conducting. He begins with the 1992-93 season. He succeeds <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Previn </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. ` When I got the offer from <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION>, I did a hell of a lot of thinking ... finally, after some time, I decided it made a lot of sense,'' <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON> said. `` With the L.A. Philharmonic I have an instrument that is capable of anything. I have no other plans beyond it. It is definitely one of the world's most important symphonies and the possibilities are unlimited.'' Between bites of an apple during an interview in a hotel lobby, the boyishly handsome <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON> said, `` Frankly I'm fed up with hotels and guest conducting.'' He currently conducts the <ORGANIZATION> Swedish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> and is principal guest conducter of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philharmonia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> Philharmonic. These and other engagements keep him on the road up to 44 weeks a year. He speaks five languages, but countries often blur and, `` in the morning it does n't matter what I say, its always in the wrong language.'' <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON>, in jeans and a blazer, said his weariness goes deeper than jet lag. `` Guest conducting is almost doomed to be superficial unless you know the orchestra very well. You work with one orchestra and then a week later you go to another place,'' he said. `` What really excites me ... is getting beneath the skin of an orchestra, which is not possible as a guest conducter. It takes a long time to build up trust. You have to establish certain musical habits in an orchestra to be able to express yourself.'' So he will take a `` semi-sabbatical'' in 1991. `` I will lay down in my hammock and remain there until I feel the urge to do something.'' But he will remain open about guest conducting in <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> and elsewhere and about renewing his Swedish contract, which overlaps with his <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> contract for the 1992-93 season. <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON> drew international attention in 1983 when he conducted, with one week's notice, a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philharmonia </LOCATION> performance of <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahler </PERSON>'s Third Symphony. It was followed by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> debut with the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philharmonic </LOCATION> and concerts in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philidelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` I always have so much work to do that I have n't really had time to think about such concepts as success,'' he said. <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON> was raised in <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION>. His classical music training began at age 9. He studied composition and conducted at <ORGANIZATION> Sibelius </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION>. He eventually began to give concerts in <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>. `` I happened to be part of a stimulating group and we had a music society,'' he said of his childhood experience. `` I loved the instant feedback. It was fun.'' He still joins young Finns who compose and play their own music in a group called Avanti! A a composer, french horn player and pianist, <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON> began conducting to make a living, and `` because I needed a conducter who was sympathetic to my music, and that was me. `` Now I would rather see someone else conduct my music ... I get very nervous about conducting my own music.'' He is known as a champion of contempory music and avant-garde experimentation. A philharmonic has a dual function, he said: as a guardian of traditional music and as a forum for new ideas. `` Contemperary music allows you to understand old musical phenomena in new ways,'' he said. A conductor's frustration is having to depend on others, he said. `` You never make your own sound. You depend on the orchestra. The chemistry ... is essential. `` It's hard to describe what I will do in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. It must be something organic, something that emerges by itself from the collaboration between the orchestra and me.'' <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON> got to know the orchestra as a regular guest since 1984. His youth and small-country origins will be no problem, he said. In <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, talent finds encouragement. `` I never felt the age question as a problem in the States. The society favors youth ... and age does n't help if you ca n't deliver,'' he said Being a hot property presents other problems. `` You know three or four years in advance exactly where you will be on any given date. It creates a claustrophobic feeling, like your life is being taken away from you. You talk and think about things that are five years in the future, but by that time you will be five years older,'' he said. <PERSON> Salonen </PERSON> still has few hobbies. An avid reader and movie buff, he occasionally listens to pop music so he can know what's going on, and he can not relax with classical music. `` If I listen to classical music when I'm relaxing I immediately go to work, thinking about how I would do it,'' he said. `` I relax to enthic music, Indian and Japanese, because I can just listen.''
