<HEAD>Books and Authors: A Tapestry of Disppearances and Reappearances</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Money matters to <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>. But the author does n't yearn for luxury hotels or billion-dollar deals, just simple things _ a nice apartment or a good movie. The characters in her second novel, `` Disappearing Acts'' -LRB- Viking, $ 18.95 -RRB-, think a lot about money, too. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> works off and on as a construction worker. Zora is a school teacher dreaming of making it as a singer and songwriter. They're two warm, intelligent people living in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> who meet by accident and fall in love. But if savings are low, luck matters, and <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> and Zora are nearly destroyed by events they're incapable of controlling `` She loves <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> said. `` That's the whole point of the story. How much is enough? How much do you give before you say, ` I ca n't do this anymore'? `` It's like real life. Every relationship starts out great and then reality sets in and there are things you have to deal with. A lot of it boils down to how much of an investment you're willing to make in order to make a marriage, or whatever, work.'' The novel is a tapestry of exits and entrances, disappearances and reappearances. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>'s moods fluctuate like the Dow Jones average, ranging from playfulness to self-pity and violence. Zora, hiding a case of epilepsy she fears will drive her man away, juggles career and family, finding release in music, friends and the son conceived with <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>. `` The title of the book came to me in a dream,'' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> said. `` I was in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and I knew I wanted to tell the story about what can happen between a man and a woman when they fall in love and all these other things happen. `` I was in a similar situation where I could n't believe I had arrived at this point. I stopped seeing my friends, I stopped going to certain places because he was n't interested. I just disappeared. I went to sleep and when I woke up that morning, I said, ` Disappearing Acts.''' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> lets <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> and Zora tell their own stories, trading chapters between the two. She began with the names, originally wanting to call <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Langston </PERSON>,'' after author and poet <PERSON> Langston </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, and Zora `` <PERSON> Mona </PERSON>.'' But somehow, `` <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>,'' with its soft first syllable running into the hard `` k'' and gently trailing off again, fit the powerful, sensitive man tortured by his inability to find steady work. And the sophisticated but streetwise woman he alternately loves and torments was renamed `` Zora'' in honor of the great writer <PERSON> Zora </PERSON> <PERSON> Neale </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurston </PERSON>. The voices followed _ <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>'s earthy and angry, tender and romantic. A self-educated black man trying to win Zora's trust while battling a racist society and his own feelings of inadequacy. His voice is mirrored in the following passage: `` I could see that she was a little scared at first. I mean, sparks was flying so fast and everything, and I was just waiting for her to tell me that her heart had been broke so many times she did n't trust men no more. I was all set to tell her, ` This time, baby, do n't be scared. This man ai n't interested in breaking your heart _ he's interested in gluing it back together and keeping it for hisself.''' Zora's voice is hopeful and frightened. She's smart enough to know what she wants but too dependent on <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> to contend with his bitterness and physical power: `` One of the things I've loved about <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> from the start is how safe he makes me feel. Protected. I'm not even talking about his job situation. I'm talking about his heart. When he puts his arms around me, if the wind was blowing a hundred miles an hour, I would n't know it. ... One thing I'm sure of _ when <PERSON> God </PERSON> made him, he should've been cloned. More women need to feel like this.'' Zora was harder for <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> to write than <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>. `` I wanted her to have some street smarts, but I did n't want her to be one of these prissy <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> types,'' the author said. `` There are a lot of educated black people who sound white. I did n't want her to sound like that. There's a rhythm to her sentences.'' Much of <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>'s childhood can be traced by reading her first novel, `` Mama.'' She grew up in a poor section of Point Haven, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, but escaped to the sunshine and promise of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> as a teen-ager in the late 1960s. A love affair at 18 inspired her to write poetry, and soon <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> was writing vignettes. She attended the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, joining a fiction workshop run by novelist and poet <PERSON> Ishmael </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, who encouraged <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> to tap her writing talents. `` It was so easy, so gratifying,'' said <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>, who now lives in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION> `` Not to say I actually wrote and finished real stories, but the whole thing was emerging and it was just wonderful.'' Vignettes soon gave way to short stories and one short story gave way to `` Mama,'' published in 1985. <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> needed just two weeks to write the book's first draft and another two weeks to complete the second. `` My mother raised a houseful of kids, sort of alone, and I think she did a good job of it,'' she said. `` I could n't figure out how she did it. It was more of an exploration, or a recounting, of where she got her strength from. `` ` Mama' was autobiographical and so is ` Disappearing Acts.' When I say autobiographical, I mean being able to relate and identify with things that I have witnessed, seen, observed or experienced or a combination of all of them.''
