<SECOND>BC-PRI--Spouses-Poverty, Adv 05,0881</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, Oct. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Rules Ease Threat of Poverty When Spouse Enters Nursing Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Husbands and wives struggling with the staggering costs of nursing home care for a spouse have new protections against the threat of poverty under rules that kick in this month as part of the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> catastrohic health insurance program. The `` spousal impoverishment'' rules have broad support on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> and appear safe from repeal as <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> debates whether to scrap major provisions of the catastrophic-care package to appease senior citizens angry at the costs of the coverage. The new nursing home protections most typically will benefit older women who might otherwise be left destitute when their husbands are institutionalized at costs averaging more than $ 25,000 a year, advocates say. In the past, Medicaid would help pay nursing home bills only after couples spent most assets and income of the institutionalized spouse, often leaving the at-home spouse little to live on. `` It was really a very tragic situation,'' said <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Loeb </PERSON> of the Older Women's League. `` With women living on average about eight years longer than men, these older women were forced to live out their remaining years in poverty.'' Attorney <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemore </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> said that if most of a couple's assets and income were listed in the name of the spouse who went into the nursing home, `` you could lose pretty much everything.'' Some couples were driven to divorce to establish court-ordered property and income rights for the non-institutionalized spouse. A 1987 congressional study found that the high costs of nursing-home care were quickly exhausting many couples' resources, leaving more than half of all couples impoverished within six months after one spouse entered a nursing home. About 15 percent of the nation's 1.5 million nursing home residents are married. `` Most often it is the wife who remains in the community, and she often is left with little or no money with which to meet her own health care and other needs,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging reported last year. Under rules that took effect Sept. 30 and being implemented by states this month, the spouse in the community will be able to keep more of the couple's combined assets and income. Where couples in the past could qualify for Medicaid help only after spending all but about $ 2,000 - $ 3,000 in assets other than their homes and certain personal belongings, now they will be able to keep $ 12,000 - $ 60,000, depending on the level set by their The minimum monthly income allowed in the past was set at the Supplemental Security Income level, $ 368 in 1989, but now rises to 122 percent of poverty, or $ 815, and will increase to 133 percent in July 1991 and 150 percent in July 1992. States will be allowed to let couples keep up to $ 1,500 a month in 1989, with the maximum rising in future years. Income and asset limits could be even higher if ordered by the courts. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Families </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>, an advocacy group for the elderly, said that while the new protection does n't solve the problem of rising costs for long-term care, `` it certainly provides tremendous relief. `` For somebody who has lived relatively well, the amount they can keep still may be seen as a hardship, but for those of moderate to middle income, it is going to substantially improve the protection that they had before,'' <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has estimated that in fiscal 1990 the new protections will cost the federal government $ 165 million and state governments $ 135 million. The federal share will rise to $ 245 million in 1991 and the state share to $ 200 million. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rother </PERSON>, legislative director for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION>, said the costs are `` a drop in the bucket'' yet produce a benefit that is `` a real lifesaver'' for many older Americans. `` It does n't do anything for the person without a spouse, but it does protect many of the people who've sacrificed the most,'' husbands and wives who already have spent years taking care of a spouse at home, <PERSON> Rother </PERSON> said. The new impoverishment rules were enacted as part of a program to insure the elderly against the costs of catastrophic illness, but even before all the program's benefits have taken effect, many senior citizens are demanding its repeal because they say it is too costly. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is expected to scrap much of the program or cut it back, but even legislators leading the call for repeal favor preserving the new impoverishment rules as a worthwhile and inexpensive protection. Advocates for the elderly, meanwhile, say that even if the whole catastrophic program survives, the nation still needs a solution to the high costs of long-term care, largely overlooked in the package. `` Spousal impoverishment is a result of the fact that our health care system does n't cover these costs,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Loeb </PERSON>. `` We still need some sort of public program that provides protection for the really catastrophic costs of nursing and home health care.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday, Oct. 5</NOTE>
