<HEAD>Unusual Home For Seniors Provides Alternative To Nursing Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANSELMO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiel </PERSON> is 80, nearly blind and ca n't live on her own. Yet she bristles at talk of a nursing home. But Wiel lives at <ORGANIZATION> Tam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a communal home on a tree-lined street in the shadow of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tamalpais </LOCATION>, with seven other women and two men. Its directors call <ORGANIZATION> Tam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> an idea whose time has come; residents are simply thankful it exists. `` It's perfect for someone like me. I needed to be around people but I needed to be independent and on my own,'' said <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, 70, who moved in 18 months ago after separating from her husband of 46 years. Now <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> spends her time gardening, playing bingo, visiting nearby senior centers and hiking six miles a day. `` It's great to be able to walk to a good trout fishing lake from your home,'' she said. <PERSON> Charlotte </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulford </PERSON>, 79, came to <ORGANIZATION> Tam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> after staying with a cousin on his houseboat in <LOCATION> Sausalito </LOCATION>. Now she would n't feel comfortable going back. `` If I did n't live here, I could n't afford to live anywhere else,'' she said. The 7-year-old, private, non-profit home owned and operated by the <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ecumenical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, offers more independence than a board-and-care home, while fostering companionship and support. Although there is a waiting list, there has n't always been. Communal living is n't for everyone. It took more than a year to fill the six-bedroom main house and four-bedroom annex, said <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Dougherty </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> RVEHA </ORGANIZATION> executive director. `` It was a new idea. Shared living was not a real popular idea with seniors.'' Many wanted their own apartment and were reluctant to squeeze a lifetime's belongings into a bedroom, <PERSON> Dougherty </PERSON> said. And for many, <ORGANIZATION> Tam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> also is the first time they've lived with a group since they were youngsters. Tam House is the product of a group of local church members who started meeting in 1975 to discuss senior housing. In 1980, they found the house, which was bought and renovated with federal development funds. Residents must be at least 55 and able to live independently when they move in. Rents range from $ 400 to $ 425 a month, including dinner and food for do-it-yourself breakfasts. Operating costs were $ 78,780 in 1988, <PERSON> Dougherty </PERSON> said. Advocates for the elderly expect shared group housing to become increasingly common among seniors. `` It's very common among young people, it's just not been an acceptable mode of living among old people until recently,'' said <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Caulfield </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Marin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> on Aging. `` I think it is an extraordinarily viable concept but it takes the right mix of people.'' This year, for the first time, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> expanded its senior housing program to include funds for such shared group residences. For those who do n't mind paring down, group housing offers a balance of privacy and company. <PERSON> Mulford </PERSON>'s tidy room disguises the fact that she has boxes and crates under the bed, jammed in the closet and covered with afghans in the corner. Little things can rankle, she admitted, laughing at her own annoyance when others forget to refill the ice cube tray or replace a roll of toilet paper. But the good outweighs the bad, she said. Tam House is within walking distance of shopping, restaurants, entertainment and public transit. Although residents must be independent, <ORGANIZATION> Tam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is small enough to accommodate changes. <PERSON> Wiel </PERSON>'s glaucoma has reduced her vision since she moved in so `` that they would n't take me this way now.'' But residents help her with chores, and all agree she is coping remarkably well with her handicap. <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>, 81, is a senior member of the house, having moved in in 1983. Boxes of files create a maze-like pattern on his floor, and books and more files practically spill off the bookshelves. A portable computer hums in the corner. <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> is writing his memoirs. He is a survivor of German concentration camps and was a spy for the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> who worked to rescue Jews during World War II. He was imprisoned for refusing to divorce his Jewish wife, who escaped. Family photos hang on the wall beside framed commendations from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Although his two daughters have each offered to share their homes, <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> will never accept. `` I would have the feeling that I am burdening someone. We have a wonderful relationship but I would n't want to encroach on their privacy. Even if you have a big house, it's a problem to have old people around.'' Although only one person, who had a drinking problem, has been evicted, <ORGANIZATION> Tam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> residents are sensitive to the ruptures that conflicts can cause. <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> said he is sometimes bothered by noise but uses earplugs rather than complain because `` it would establish a certain tension.'' `` This is 10 crotchety old people,'' said <PERSON> Teddy </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, 81. `` We're all set in our ways before we get here. It's simply amazing how we all get along.''
</TEXT>
