<HEAD>For release Thursday, Oct. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Patriarch of Journalism Still Going Strong at 93</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. IGNACE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Journalism careers begin humbly under <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON>, a 93-year-old patriarch of the profession who starts the process by having bright young students restock newspaper vending machines. <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> teaches an old school of journalism, the small-town kind known unkindly in big-city newsrooms as `` chicken dinner news.'' It's the toughest journalism there is, and the most important, he believes. <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> bought the <LOCATION> Mackinac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crier </LOCATION> for his students and the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ignace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> for himself. At both weeklies, reporters and interns write about ice cream socials and summer parades. They sell ads, take subscriptions, paste up the paper and collect quarters from the stands. They also probe social issues and pry truth from rumor. And they listen for the beat of the community heart. `` The idea to know about journalism is to know the whole thing,'' <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> says. That means living with the people you write about and to whom you sell the stories and the ads. Shed your cynicism and tell readers of their own decency, grace and commonweal, <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> says. You might not expect to learn such high ideals selling ads for an obstinate man who can hardly hear, who sits dwarfed in his dim office beneath a wall of books, ripping into newspaper stories. Here is a man who advocates such old-school and now taboo ideas as doctoring quotes to improve their clarity. Some of <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON>'s students start their summers on <LOCATION> Mackinac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> thinking they're entering a museum. The necessity for reporters to cover their beats by riding bicycles on the motorless island does n't help. `` I think they look at him, in a way, just as an old man. I hate to see it but I know where it's coming from,'' said one of <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON>'s disciples, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>, a publisher who came out of retirement to be advertising manager `` I know they respect him but they wonder with his age that he might be out of touch with reality. ... They look at him as a stodgy old professor. `` Then, all of a sudden, it's a rude awakening. Here's this man tearing into their copy and they're not prima donnas anymore.'' There is more to <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> than this. He works every day of every week and always wears a suit with a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> pin _ he joined the faculty in 1928 and was journalism chairman for two decades starting in 1947 _ and a tie with a perfect <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION> knot, even when weeding his beloved roses. Sunday mornings, he gathers his interns for three-hour lectures on topics ranging from the Cold War to why papers did n't sell. `` He called me back into his office once and I thought there was something wrong with one of my stories,'' said former <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ignace </LOCATION> reporter <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Esper </PERSON>, now at the <ORGANIZATION> Ironwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>. `` Instead, he leans back in his chair and says ` Light can illuminate but it can also blind.''' Vintage <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON>. The reporters he has coached, encouraged and tormented have gone on to become correspondents, editors and publishers around the world. `` He is a terrific teacher, a very stimulating fellow. He makes you think,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottschalk </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON>'s first island interns, now senior writer for the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> bureau of the Wall Street Journal. <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON>'s students tell of a relentless teacher and perfectionist. The idiosyncrasies are tolerated. The ideologies are cherished. `` I feel every moment I can spend with him is worthwhile. He is forever the teacher,'' says senior intern <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Reavie </PERSON>. `` I know new students see this 90-year-old man waddling around and they say, ` What can he do for us?' But they genuinely love the man at the end of the summer.'' And how <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> loves them. `` I get always connected with young people. It's a delight. I find them interesting.'' Age now is wedging itself between <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> and the business he loves. Bypass surgery last fall knocked him off his feet. `` Despite doctors' orders, he would come down here and be on his feet to check the paper,'' <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> said. `` He was just obstinate. I know he had said to me at one time when he was recovering, that he thought it could be the beginning of the end. `` I had never seen that attitude in him.'' <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> has, however, turned over more of the daily newspaper work to his son, <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON> <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and to <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>. Neither man has a journalism degree, but both are lifelong students of <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON>'s community news `` I'm an old man who does n't know when to retire,'' <PERSON> Maurer </PERSON> says. `` As long as I can, I will do some kind of work, because I think that keeps you alive.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 5</NOTE>
