<HEAD>Blind Volunteers Sought in Program to Help Blind Elderly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Blind Americans aged 60 and over will be recruited as volunteers to help other visually handicapped elderly people under a project being launched as part of the government's Senior Companion Program <ORGANIZATION> SCP </ORGANIZATION> announced Sept. 15 that it had awarded a $ 220,000 grant to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for the <PERSON> Blind </PERSON>, which will help find and train visually impaired senior volunteers and locate other blind seniors who need help. The Senior Companion Program uses low-income citizens 60 and older to provide care and companionship to other adults to help them live independently. The program is sponsored by ACTION, the federal domestic volunteer agency. Acting ACTION Director <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> said the new program targeting the blind is designed `` to focus attention on the abilities of the disabled.'' Under the grant, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blind </ORGANIZATION> will assist four local <ORGANIZATION> Senior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Programs </ORGANIZATION> in developing two-year demonstration projects, which have not been selected. The foundation will help develop training materials, evaluate the projects and offer information to other <ORGANIZATION> SCP </ORGANIZATION> groups interested in using blind volunteers or serving more visually impaired elderly people. The New York-based, non-profit foundation is contributing 12 percent in matching dollars toward the cost of the demonstration project.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Screening, Brochure Available on Leg Pains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 3 million Americans ignore leg ache, pain or cramps during walking or exercise as simply signs of aging, but they could have an easily diagnosed and treated disease that could be incapacitating. Peripheral arterial disease is a narrowing or blockage of arteries, generally in the lower abdomen or extremities and especially in the legs. The most common cause is atherosclerosis, or hardening of the arteries. P.A.D. most often afflicts people over 50 and has most commonly hit men, though women also are at increased risk because more women are smoking. Other risk factors include diabetes, hypertension and high fat levels in the blood. `` P.A.D. is easily treated if detected in its early stages,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilo </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. LEG ALERT, a 3-year-old program established by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aging </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Hoechst-Roussel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has screened over 34,000 people. The <ORGANIZATION> NCOA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hoechst-Roussel </ORGANIZATION>, which makes a drug that increases blood flow, also have prepared a booklet describing P.A.D. and what to do about it. For a copy of `` Step Lively,'' send a stamped, self-addressed, business-size envelope to CMC-PK, Department PAD, P.O. Box 830, <LOCATION> Andover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> 07821.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Outreach Program Aims to Increase Access to Government Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An advocacy group for older Americans is expanding its outreach program to help more elderly and disabled poor people get the government benefits to which they are eligible. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION> said it will help people in 30 communities nationwide learn about and apply for Medicaid, food stamps, low-income home energy assistance and Supplemental Security Income benefits. The outreach program earlier had been planned for 10 cities and was focused on helping eligible people obtain <ORGANIZATION> SSI </ORGANIZATION> benefits, which provide a minimal income floor for the nation's blind, aged and disabled. A pilot SSI outreach program in 1988 in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, resulted in a 97 percent increase in <ORGANIZATION> SSI </ORGANIZATION> applications and a 58 percent jump in SSI awards, <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION> said. Training, community presentations and publicity are among the methods used to reach people who may be eligible for benefits, the group said. <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION>'s expanded outreach program, scheduled to run through 1990, is being financed with help from The <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Elderly People Living Alone. Cities to be included in the project will be selected after local organizations apply to assist in the outreach program.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Organizations interested in the outreach program can get more information by writing to: Public Benefits Outreach Project, <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION> Consumer Affairs, 1909 K St. N.W., <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> D.C. 20049. The deadline for applications is Oct. 16.
</TEXT>
