<HEAD>Land Prices in Tokyo Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Land prices in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s residential areas have fallen for the first time since the government began keeping records in 1975, but real estate costs have been rising elsewhere in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, a report released Monday said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said residential land prices in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> were down 4.4 percent as of July 1 from 1988, when they rose 8.1 percent. The highest residential land price in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was $ 88,000 a square meter, or 10.76 square feet, in the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> area, said an agency official, speaking on condition of anonymity. The official declined to say who lives there, but <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Prime Minister <PERSON> Toshiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> lives in an apartment house in that area, and owns his apartment. Last year's highest price was $ 79,000 a square meter. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s most expensive commercial land was $ 254,000 a square meter at the site of a building of <ORGANIZATION> Meidi-Ya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a trading firm, in the <LOCATION> Ginza </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s leading shopping district. That area also was most expensive last year, at $ 242,000, the official said. He said the report was based on a survey of land prices conducted on July 1 at 25,216 spots throughout the nation. The official said the nation's average land price went up by 6.8 percent from a year earlier in residential areas and 7.5 percent in commercial areas, compared with 7.4 percent for residential land and 8.0 percent for commercial land last year. In <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> and neighboring areas in western <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, residential land prices rose 37.3 percent from a year earlier, compared with an increase of 26.9 percent last year. In <LOCATION> Sanrizuka </LOCATION>, land prices went up 96 percent, the highest in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> this year, to $ 317 a square meter from $ 162.
