<SECOND>BC-Japan-Bullet Train,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>High-Speed Train Celebrates 25th Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s `` bullet train,'' named for its shape and high-speed, is 25 years old. The train began service on Oct. 1, 1964, running at speeds of up to 131 miles an hour and making the 324-mile run between <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>, in western <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, in 3 hours, 20 minutes. `` Since then, the bullet trains have carried 2.7 billion passengers between <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Tomoko </PERSON> <PERSON> Shimokawa </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railways </ORGANIZATION>, the private company that replaced the government-owned railroad in April 1987. The train never has been involved in a major accident. The introduction of bullet train services in 1964, shortly before the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> Olympic Games, was seen as a symbol of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s remarkable postwar economic recovery The <LOCATION> Tokyo-Osaka </LOCATION> run has since been cut to three hours, with trains running at up to 138 miles an hour, Ms. <PERSON> Shimokawa </PERSON> said Monday. In 1975, the original line from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> was extended past <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Hakata </LOCATION>, on the southernmost main island of <LOCATION> Kyushu </LOCATION>, 563 miles west of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. In the late 1980s, new lines were added from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Morioka </LOCATION>, 289 miles to the north, and from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Niigata </LOCATION>, 160 miles northwest of the capital. The fastest train on the line to <LOCATION> Morioka </LOCATION> runs at up to 150 miles an hour, the railway says.
</TEXT>
