<HEAD>Rumored Soviet Demand Fuels Crop Futures Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices rose sharply in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid signs the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has returned in a big way to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural markets. Corn futures soared the permitted daily limit of 10 cents a pound shortly after the opening on rumors the Soviets had bought 1.5 million to 2 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn over the weekend. Rumors of an impending Soviet corn purchase had simmered through the markets last week despite statements last month by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s grain-buying agency that the country would purchase no more grain this year. Further buying of grain futures was prompted by a news service's report that an agricultural aide to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had said an `` unprecedented'' sale of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm goods to the Soviets would be announced soon In early trading, wheat futures were 1 -LCB- cents to 4 -LCB- cents higher wiith the contract for delivery in December at $ 4.11 -RCB- a bushel; corn futures were 9 cents to 10 cents higher with December at $ 2.43 a bushel; oats were 4 \ cents to 5 cents higher with December at $ 1.48 \ a bushel; soybeans were 8 -RCB- cents to 18 cents higher with November at $ 5.86 a Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were unchanged to .35 cent higher with October at 71.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .13 cent lower with October at 82.82 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to .78 cent higher with October at 44 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .40 cent to .78 cent higher with February at 48.77 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Friday.
