<FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 2302EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv04   10-02 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 04,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Wednesday, Oct. 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Odd Position For The Fed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You have the assurance of a person with 60 years of experience that there will be no recession so long as interest rates remain high. That might sound odd, because conventional thinking associates high or rising interest rates with a downturn sometime in the future. This fellow says high rates will protect us from recession. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sindlinger </PERSON> has been analyzing public and economic opinion for close to six decades, during the past three of them through information gathered from an average of 110 telephone calls a day, seven days a week. The staff of <ORGANIZATION> Sindlinger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> asks probing personal questions of a scientific sample of households, and obtains remarkably straight answers. Out of each interview comes about 95 pieces of information. The staff is especially interested in levels of income compared with six months earlier, and income expectations for the next six months. They ask about job security, and about the household's view of business six months ahead. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sindlinger </PERSON>, a pioneer in consumer research, analyzes the data. Of late, that data has suggested a lot of Americans feel rather well-heeled. As usual, he wanted to know why and made sure his staff probed into the subject. Answer any question asked by a canny interviewer and you're likely to provide more information than you realize One bit of information stood out: People felt comfortable because they are getting good returns on their savings. This is part of what often is referred to as the wealth effect, although it is a lot more complicated than that. With banks deregulated _ remember the old days of 5.25 percent interest a year _ people know they can get good returns. To say that they have gone `` yield crazy'' may be an exaggeration, although <PERSON> Sindlinger </PERSON> used the term a couple of times. But they are squeezing every nickel they can out of their assets in savings bonds, certificates of deposit, corporate and junk bonds. It is an accepted dictum of market psychology that when consumers feel comfortable they are inclined to spend. This being so, says <PERSON> Sindlinger </PERSON>, there's a real question of whether the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> can wrestle inflation by raising rates. But these people also carry a lot of debt, too. Sure they do, says <PERSON> Sindlinger </PERSON>, but never forget that you ca n't go into debt unless you have assets _ not just a nest egg of collateral but a good secure job too. This situation tends to feed inflation, but there is more: For the first time in seven years, <PERSON> Sindlinger </PERSON> is finding an ominous rise in the wage demands of service workers. That also is an inflationary sign. The stock market? <PERSON> Sindlinger </PERSON> is finding that while households might have debts, some of those debts are going to finance stock purchases, adding to the wealth effect. This debt situation, household and corporate, might cause problems down the road, but he believes the immediate impact is to sustain a relatively high level of stock prices, together with a sense of financial well-being. Many people feel capitalistic today, he said. About 20 years ago fewer than 25 percent of households had $ 100,000 of liquid assets. Now, he says, 55 percent do. It's a bullish feeling, even if $ 100,000 is n't what it used to be. As <PERSON> Sindlinger </PERSON> sees it, the household financial condition explains why <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democrats lost the battle of capital gains taxes. He says too many of their old constituents think of themselves as taxpayers rather than tax recipients. But the biggest lesson of all, he maintains, is for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. That August body, he says, appears to be in the position of trying to fight inflation via high interest rates, but is fueling it instead.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Wednesday, Oct. 4</NOTE>
