<HEAD>Nissan Executive Predicts '90 Vehicle Sales Will Drop</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT7 of Oct. 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> car sales should drop in 1990 although it expects its truck sales to increase, led by its new four-door Pathfinder sport-utility vehicle, a <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> executive said Monday. Overall, sales throughout the industry in 1990 will drop to about 14 million cars and trucks from nearly 15 million in 1989, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, general manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> Division of <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION>, the Japanese company's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marketing arm. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s share of that market should be about 660,000 vehicles in each year. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales in 1990 should drop by about 0.8 percent but truck sales should rise by 2.5 percent. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> estimated the four-door Pathfinder would make up 90 percent of the vehicle's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales of about 31,000 vehicles. About 24,000 two-door Pathfinders were sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> during the 1989 model year, but <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said that number would drop drastically because of price increases needed to recover tariff costs effective on the 1990 models. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, under rules announced earlier this year, classified the four-door version of the imported Pathfinder as a car, making it subject to a 2.5 percent tariff. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> officials had worried that the four-door Pathfinder would be classified as a truck, making it subject to a 25 percent import duty. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> now makes pickup trucks and Sentra automobiles at its <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, plant. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> projected that Sentra sales will fall to about 180,000 cars in the 1990 model year, down 21.1 percent from the 228,000 the company expects to sell in the 1989 model year. Sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> built pickup trucks should increase slightly, he said. When asked if a larger car would be made at the <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION> plant, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said only that it would be two to three model years away. However, he later said a redesigned Stanza would be offered at about the same time, and with design work done in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, `` at that time it could be an all-American vehicle.'' He predicted the newly redesigned 1990 Stanza would more than double <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales for the nameplate during the 1990 model year. He also forecast that sales of the 300ZX sports car would rise in 1990, with sales of other cars flat or lower.
