<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Touch 16-Year Low On Ivory Coast Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Cocoa futures prices plunged to a 16-year low Monday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on indications that more cocoa from the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> may be headed for an already overburdened world market. On other commodity markets Monday, cotton futures rallied strongly, grains and soybeans were sharply higher, most energy futures fell, livestock and meat futures were mixed, and precious metals were mixed. Cocoa settled $ 25 to $ 34 lower with the contract for delivery in December at $ 1,008 per metric ton. The December contract traded as low as $ 995 during the session, marking cocoa's first dip below $ 1,000 since 1973. The close was also the lowest since 1973. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds. Analysts attributed much of the market's weakness to confirmation that the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, the world's largest cocoa producer, had slashed by 50 percent the support price it pays to cocoa farmers. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the price-support cut had been urged by international lending agencies and could signal a more aggressive selling posture on the part of the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, rumors resurfaced that a 500,000-ton Ivorian cocoa deal involving two trade houses had collapsed. `` It just means there is that much more cocoa to be sold,'' <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> said. Cotton futures soared on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Cotton Exchange, largely reflecting bullish chart signals. Further buying was linked to speculation that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s cotton crop may be smaller than forecast and to position-evening by traders in a market that has fluctuated wildly in recent weeks. `` A lot of people have been whipsawed by this market,'' said analyst <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Corn futures prices soared on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid rumblings of a major Soviet purchase of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn, and the other grain and soybean markets went along for the ride. Rumors that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had bought as much as 3 million metric tons of corn over the weekend sent futures prices for corn up the permitted daily limit of 10 cents a bushel shortly after the opening. The other markets rose in sympathy with corn, but prices retreated from their highs across the board in afternooon profit-taking. Wheat futures settled unchanged to 4 -RCB- cents higher with December at $ 4.07 \ a bushel; corn was 6 cents to 8 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 2.41 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 2 -RCB- cents to 4 \ cents higher with December at $ 1.46 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 4 -LCB- cents to 9 cents higher with November at $ 5.77 a Energy futures finished mostly lower on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, led by a drop in near-term heating oil contracts that was viewed as a technical correction following five days of steady gains. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 12 cents lower with November at $ 20.01 a barrel; heating oil was .30 cent to .45 cent lower with November at 59.58 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was 1.42 cent lower to .05 cent lower with November at 56.80 cents a gallon. Live cattle futures dropped sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid worries that cash prices would not follow through on expectations for higher levels. Pork futures advanced moderately following Friday's quarterly <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> hogs-and-pigs report, which showed lower-than-expected hog-breeding intentions. Live cattle settled .05 cent to .90 cent lower with October at 71.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .60 cent lower with October at 82.60 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent lower to .65 cent higher with October at 44.17 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .03 cent to .33 cent higher with February at 48.55 cents a pound. Precious metals finished nearly unchanged on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Gold was 20 cents lower to 40 cents higher with October at $ 367.60 a troy ounce; silver was 0.6 cent to 1 cent lower with December at $ 5.303 a troy ounce.
