<HEAD>Oil Futures Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices fell Monday as a recent rally inspired by a new <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production agreement ran out of steam. The November contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, slipped 12 cents to close at $ 20.01 per 42-gallon barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The contract had gained 27 cents on Friday. Friday's advance was sparked by an agreement among the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> that raised the ceiling on the cartel's overall output to 20.5 million barrels of oil a day from the previous limit of 19.5 million barrels. Oil investors were encouraged by the group's ability to reach an agreement to limit production. On Monday, though, many traders sold futures contracts to cash in their profits and halted the rally, analysts said. `` There was a feeling the market was overbought'' on Friday, said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Haskins </PERSON>, a vice president of energy futures trading at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Home heating oil futures traded on the mercantile exchange also declined The November contract for heating oil, in its first day of trading, fell 0.38 cent a gallon to close at 59.58 cents and subsequent months also retreated. The November contract for gasoline, also in its initial trading day, dropped 1.42 cents a gallon to 56.80 cents. Most subsequent months also fell.
</TEXT>
