<FIRST>r f AM-BankofBoston     10-02 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank of Boston,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Bank Announces It Will Take a Loss to Cover Shaky Loans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, expressing concern about the economy, announced Monday it was diverting $ 370 million from its earnings to increase its reserve for possible loan losses. <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, said based on current estimates, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> will have a third-quarter loss of approximately $ 125 million after placing the money in its reserve for credit losses. But he said <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> should end the first nine months of 1989 with a profit. `` It's a good deal of money,'' said bank spokesman <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>. `` It's certainly a big hit for us.'' In a separate matter, <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON> said the bank has taken steps to strengthen its internal controls, real estate lending and review of credit risk, as suggested by federal regulators after a review by the office of the Comptroller of the Currency. `` The issues raised by the regulators are ones we take very seriously,'' <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON> said in a prepared statement. On the new reserve, <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON> said the bank was taking a leadership position similar to 1987, when it shifted money to cover loans to Third World countries. Among the reasons he cited for Monday's action were continued weakness in the real estate industry and `` further signs of softness in general economic conditions.'' The bank already had 100 percent reserves against its non-trade-related lending to Third World countries. Also, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said, one of the bank's business customers assumed a large amount of debt for a transaction, and now the bank is concerned that the company might have trouble paying off the loan. He declined to name the company or the amount of the loan. By shifting money into the reserve account, `` it does n't just forgive the debt,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. `` We're taking it off the books so it does n't just hang there,'' he said, adding that the bank would still try to recover the money. The additional reserve, combined with $ 70 million in charge-offs for bad loans in the quarter, brings the total reserve to about $ 945 million, or 3.5 percent of total loans and leases. <PERSON> Stepanian </PERSON> said the bank expects to enter an agreement with the federal agency in which the board of directors will review steps to improve its performance in those areas cited in the governmental review.
</TEXT>
