<HEAD>Say Lease Renegotiated for About Half the Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will retain its <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> headquarters at least until 2004 but with about half the space currently occupied, under terms of a renegotiated lease announced Monday by the investment banking firm that recently settled widespread fraud charges. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> said it had reached agreement with landlord <ORGANIZATION> Olympia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; York, a large real estate concern that owns many <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> properties, to restructure and extend for 10 years <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s lease on its world headquarters in southern <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. The lease had been due to expire in about four years. Within two years <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> expects to consolidate most of its New York-based operations into 700,000 square feet in one building, vs. 1.5 million square feet in four locations now, the firm said. Financial details of the restructured lease were n't disclosed, but <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement it will `` result in a substantial cash savings over the next three and a half years.'' <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> was once the fifth-biggest Wall Street firm but underwent a drastic restructuring earlier this year, after agreeing to settle securities fraud charges that stemmed from a prolonged federal investigation. As part of the settlement, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> pleaded guilty to six felonies and paid more than $ 650 million in fines, penalties and interest. The firm eliminated its retail operations and terminated about 4,000 employees of its 9,300 workforce worldwide. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> staff was cut by 1,345 people to 3,635.
