<FIRST>r f BC-SEC-BreedenAnswers     10-02 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SEC-Breeden Answers,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Nominee Speaks His Mind _ in Writing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-SEC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The man picked to head the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> believes he can fight to keep the nation's stock markets honest, but that it's up to the industry to woo back small investors <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, replying at length Monday to a series of written questions from the senators who will vote on his appointment, said restoring investor confidence in the wake of the 1987 crash and the insider trading scandals is a job for the securities industry itself. `` Many Americans may also have a perception that self-interest and corruption among securities industry participants are widespread,'' said <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> in the 109-page question-and-answer sheet. `` The commission can help correct this perception through vigorous enforcement, but much of this change must be accomplished by the industry itself through renewed attention to retail customers and dedication to ethical business practices.'' <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> also said that the head of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> does not have the authority, on his own, to halt trading in the midst of a disaster such as the 1987 crash _ and even if he did, `` I would not consider such a step.'' <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> said that there's too much uncertainty about when the markets would close and for how long. `` In a crisis, this uncertainty and the related rumors concerning its likelihood could have seriously adverse consequences.'' <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, 37, a key White House aide, was nominated by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in August to succeed <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON>, who returned to teaching law last week. The Senate has yet to confirm <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, the assistant to the president for issue analysis and the chief <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> liaison on the recent savings and loan bailout bill. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> received a warm reception last month at his confirmation hearing before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. A committee vote is expected later this month. In the meantime, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischman </PERSON> has been tapped as acting <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> chairman until the <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> nomination is decided. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> said in the written response that he believes vigorous enforcement of existing rules against insider trading and other illegal activities is `` one of the most effective means to increase individual investor confidence and participation.'' He added that his experience with the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L restructuring `` has largely confirmed my prior views rather than changing them'' about `` strict enforcement of safety and soundness standards.'' On other topics <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> said he: _ Believed securities laws `` would benefit from modernization'' because `` current law often excessively restricts competition. _ Does n't think the rival <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> should have exclusive control over all `` hybrid'' financial products that have some characteristics of securities and futures contracts because it could `` stifle innovation. _ Favors breaking down the Glass-Steagall Act's barrier between commerical banking and the securities industry `` but only if the entire regulatory structure'' that would replace it `` was adequate to protect the integrity of the securities markets.
