<SECOND>BC-Honeywell-NEC,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honeywell Sells Its 50 Percent Stake In HNSX Supercomputers To NEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has sold to <ORGANIZATION> NEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> its 50 percent ownership in <ORGANIZATION> HNSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supercomputers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> company that markets <ORGANIZATION> NEC </ORGANIZATION> supercomputers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Terms of the agreement were not disclosed Monday. HNSX, based in <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, had been jointly owned by <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NEC </ORGANIZATION> since its inception in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> said the venture is no longer within its `` strategic focus.'' The Minneapolis-based controls maker and defense contractor lost $ 435 million in fiscal 1988 and announced a sweeping restructuring in July. Earlier <ORGANIZATION> Honeywell </ORGANIZATION> had sold its other computer operations. The HNSX deal puts <ORGANIZATION> NEC </ORGANIZATION> in complete control of its attack in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> against Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> is the world's largest supercomputer maker, but <ORGANIZATION> NEC </ORGANIZATION> threw <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s long-term dominance of the industry into question in April when it announced it will introduce the world's fastest supercomputer next year. Supercomputers are considered crucial to national security because they are heavily used for designing nuclear weapons. They also are used for such tasks as scientific research, oil exploration and weather forecasting. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has strongly discouraged federal agenies and universities that receive government grants from buying Japanese-made supercomputers.
