<HEAD>Lockheed To Take $165 Million in Charges Against 3rd-Quarter Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it would take a charge of about $ 165 million against its third-quarter profits because of overruns on fixed-price contracts. The writeoffs will result in an after-tax loss of about $ 35 million for the three months ended Sept. 31, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tellep </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, said in a statement. The charges stem mainly from a subcontract for wing parts on the C-17 transport that <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is building for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and a contract to modify 12 EP-3E patrol planes for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. Also included in the charge are overruns on some smaller fixed-price development contracts and certain other programs, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s initial cost figure was $ 1.3 billion for the C-17 wing work, and $ 59.8 million for the EP-3E modifications. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON> said the company is continuing efforts to persuade the government that <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> should be paid more because hundreds of changes were made in design specifications after the contracts were made. `` The assumption was these were build to -LRB- blue -RRB- print,'' he said. `` But then there were many changes made in those prints.'' Despite the expected third-quarter loss, <PERSON> Slayman </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> expected the year to be profitable as a whole.
