<HEAD>Coal Strike Blamed for Profit Decline at CSX</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s third-quarter profit declined, due in part to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> strike against <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the Richmond-based railroad, barge and natural resources company said Monday. <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> said third-quarter earnings totaled $ 94 million, or 91 cents per share, compared with $ 120 million, or 75 cents a share, for the same period last year. Revenue for the quarter totaled $ 1.9 billion, $ 1 million less than last year's third quarter. The disparity in the per-share earnings between the two quarters reflects an ongoing share-repurchase program. In addition to lower coal traffic caused by the ongoing coal strike, which began April 5, <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> cited an overall weakening of the economy's industrial sector as well as service disruptions and damage caused by Hurricane Hugo for its lower earnings. The company said earnings for the first nine months of 1989 totaled $ 327 million, or $ 3.10 per share, compared with earnings of $ 25 million, or 11 cents a share, for the first nine months of 1988. Last year's results reflected a post-tax special charge of $ 492 million, or $ 3.16 per share. Revenue for the first nine months was $ 5.7 billion, compared with $ 5.5 billion for the same 1988 period.
