<TEXT>
 A Canadian family considering a hostile takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has asked the board of directors to allow a special stockholders meeting. Lancaster-based <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION>, which manufactures interior furnishings, said in a news release Monday it is examining the request from the <PERSON> Belzberg </PERSON> family of <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, which has interests in real estate and a financial company. The family's petition asks the board to amend its articles of incorporation to allow investors holding 20 percent of the company's stock to call a special meeting. According to the petition, two companies controlled by the <ORGANIZATION> Belzbergs </ORGANIZATION> own 4.56 million shares, or 9.85 percent of the company. The shares were purchased for $ 181 million this summer. The petition, which was filed with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, indicates the <ORGANIZATION> Belzbergs </ORGANIZATION> have not acquired any more <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> stock since announcing their initial stake July 5. Under <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> law, only investors holding at least 10 percent of a company's stock can file amendment petitions. The <PERSON> Belzbergs </PERSON> were joined in the action by <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which together own nearly 800,000 shares. <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION>'s stock closed Monday at 44.62 -LCB-, up $ 1.37 -LCB-, on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The petition also seeks to waive the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> business combination statute, which is intended to discourage takeovers. The Belzbergs asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> to approve the petition's requests.
